{cite encyclopedia|ref=harv |author=RD staff |title=Xhosa Wars |encyclopedia=Reader's Digest Family Encyclopedia of World History  |publisher=The Reader's Digest Association |year=1996}}\n* {{cite journal|ref=harv |first=J. B. |last=Peires |url=http://eprints.ru.ac.za/1316/1/Ntsikana.pdf |title=Nxele, Ntsikana and the origins of the Xhosa religious reaction |journal=Journal of African History |volume=20 |number=I |year=1979 |pages=51\u201361 |doi=10.1017/s0021853700016716}}\n* {{cite web |ref=harv |author=SAH staff|date=21 March 2011 |url=http://www.sahistory.org.za/topic/conquest-eastern-cape-1779-1878 |title=Conquest of the Eastern Cape 1779-1878 |publisher= South African History Online|accessdate=2017-12-07}}\n* {{cite web|ref=harv |author=SAH staff |date=12 May 1836 |url=http://www.sahistory.org.za/pages/chronology/thisday/1836-05-14.html |title=Fingo leaders gather at Peddie |publisher= South African History Online|accessdate=23 March 2012}}\n* {{cite web|ref=harv |author=SAH staff |url=http://www.sahistory.org.za/article/1800s |title=1800s time-line |publisher=South African History Online]|accessdate=23 March 2012}}\n* {{Cite journal|ref=harv| title = The Last Frontier War| last = Gon | first = Philip| journal= Military History Journal| date = December 1982|volume=5|issue=6|publisher =The South African Military History Society| accessdate = 2015-07-16| url = http://samilitaryhistory.org/vol056pg.html}}\n{{refend}}\n\n; Attribution\n* {{EB1911|first=Frank Richardson |last=Cana|wstitle=Cape Colony |volume=5 |pages=238\u2013240}} History sub-sections:\n** ''The First and Second Wars'' p.&nbsp;238\n** ''Third War'' pp.&nbsp;238\u2013239\n** ''The War of the Axe'' p.&nbsp;239\n** ''Extension of British Sovereignty'' p.&nbsp;239\n** ''War of 1850\u20131853'' pp.&nbsp;239\u2013240\n** ''The Great Amaxosa Delusion'' p.&nbsp;240\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|editor-first=John|editor-last=Frye|title=The War of the Axe and the Xhosa Bible: The Journal of the Rev. J.W. Appleyard|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5gPjHwAACAAJ|year=1971|publisher=C. Struik|location=Cape Town}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=McKay|first=James |title=Reminiscences of the Last Kafir War. Illustrated with Numerous Anecdotes|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZVc8MwEACAAJ|edition=2nd|year=1970|publisher=C. Struik|location=Cape Town}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Milton|first=John |title=The Edges of War: A History of Frontier Wars (1702-1878)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4cIKAQAAIAAJ|year=1983|publisher=Juta|location=Cape Town|isbn=978-0-7021-1331-4}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Cape Frontier Wars|Xhosa Wars}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070630090942/http://www.justdone.co.za/ROH/List_Wars.asp List of wars]\n* [http://rapidttp.com/milhist/vol013jh.html Irregular units of the 7th Xhosa War]\n* [http://rapidttp.com/milhist/vol021jh.html Burgher Commandos of the 7th Xhosa War]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060904131845/http://courses.wcupa.edu/jones/his311/lectures/22sa-boe.htm  HIS 311 Lecture on Southern Africa 1800\u20131875]\n* [https://www.onwar.com/aced/chrono/c1800s/yr18/fkaffir1818.htm Fifth Kaffir War 1818\u20131819]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080514173342/http://www.bethel.edu/~letnie/AfricanChristianity/SSAXhosa.html Nxele, Xhosa prophet who predicted that Xhosa ancestors would rise from the dead and win the battle]\n\n{{British colonial campaigns}}\n{{Political history of South Africa |state=expanded}}\n\n[[Category:18th-century conflicts]]\n[[Category:19th-century conflicts]]\n[[Category:18th century in South Africa]]\n[[Category:19th century in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Military history of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Military history of the Cape Colony]]\n[[Category:Wars involving the states and peoples of Africa]]\n[[Category:Wars involving South Africa]]\n[[Category:Wars involving the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Xhosa|Wars]]\n[[Category:South Africa\u2013United Kingdom relations]]\n[[Category:Military history of the Dutch East India Company]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1834]]\n[[Category:African resistance to colonialism]]\n", "name_user": "41.157.214.20", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xhosa_Wars"}
{"title_page": "Karl Leopold von M\u00f6ller", "text_new": "\n\n{{original research|date=March 2017}}\n\n{{rough translation|1=German|listed=yes|date=September 2018}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name          = Karl von M\u00f6ller\n| image         = Karl von M\u00f6ller.jpg\n| birth_name    = Karl Leopold von M\u00f6ller\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1876|10|11}}\n| birth_place   = [[Vienna]], Austria\n| death_date    = {{death date|1943|2|21}}\n| death_place   = [[Jimbolia]], Romania\n| occupation    = Writer, politician, journalist, officer\n| notableworks  = [[Der St\u00fcrmer]]\n| spouses       = {{marriage|Baroness Agathe von Veroczy|1917|1923|end=divorce}}{{plainlist}}{{marriage |Margaret Jung|1927|1943|end=died}}<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.geni.com/people/Karl-Leopold-Edler-von-M%C3%B6-ller-von-M%C3%B6ller-Harteneck/6000000026523073826?through=6000000026524041123 | title=Karl Leopold Edler von M\u00f6ller Leopold von M\u00f6ller-Harteneck}}</ref>\n| children      = 3 (Edith, Karl-Heinz and Erich)\n| relatives     =\n}}\n\n'''Karl von M\u00f6ller''' (October 11, 1876, [[Vienna]] - February 21, 1943, [[Jimbolia]])<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.buchfreund.de/productListing.php?used=1&productId=41706697 | title=Das steinerne Schachbrett. Roman. M\u00f6ller, Karl von: 6480BB}}</ref> was an officer, journalist, author and politician from [[Banat]]. He was an enthusiastic supporter of [[Hitler]]'s [[National Socialism]], and in 1932 he published the antisemitic newspaper \"Der St\u00fcrmer\" in [[Timi\u0219oara]], an imitation of the German [[Nazi]] publication. He was married to Margaret Jung, with whom he had two children.\n\n==Life and early work==\nThe von M\u00f6ller family's origins point to the [[L\u00fcneburg Heath]]. Karl von M\u00f6ller's grandfather volunteered in the [[German Campaign of 1813|Wars of Liberation]] and was disarmed in [[Sibiu]] (Transylvania). von M\u00f6ller's grandfather is also allegedly an early developer of the [[Camera]] but didn't submit the patent in time. His father came to Vienna from Sibiu. Karl von M\u00f6ller was born in Vienna, where he attended the cadet school and the war school after high school. During the First World War, he moved as a major and chief of staff of the 34th Infantry Division, Banater Division, first to the Serbian and then to the Galician front. Von M\u00f6ller led from 1916 as a lieutenant colonel and later as colonel Hungarian Infantry Regiment No. 65 on the Eastern Front. He was awarded the [[Order of Leopold]].\n\n== Politician ==\nAfter the collapse of the Habsburg monarchy in 1918, he left the army as a colonel and went to Timi\u0219oara, where he campaigned for political and cultural equality for Romanian Germans in the field of national politics.  von M\u00f6ller was May 9, 1919, co-founded the German-Swabian Cultural Association, whose chairman Johann Junker was. The executive chairman was Michael Kausch. In 1919 M\u00f6ller was elected the second mayor of Timi\u0219oara. From 1919 to 1926 he was a senator in the Romanian upper house in Bucharest, representing Banat Swabia. Karl von M\u00f6ller joined the \"Volksgemeinschaft\" together with Josef Gabriel in 1920.\n\nFrom 1920 he made trips to Germany, gave lectures in Saxony, Westphalia, Baden, W\u00fcrttemberg, Thuringia, Berlin and Munich. In 1923 he had contacts with National Socialist circles; he is considered an early supporter of Adolf Hitler. After his return, he became chief editor of the \"Banat German newspaper\". He was one of the members of the \"German People's Council\".\n\nvon M\u00f6ller is considered one of the pioneers of fascism in the Banat. In 1931 he founded the first Banat local group of the \"National Socialist Self-Help Movement of the Germans in Romania\" (NSDR) in Jimbolia (German: Hatzfeld), which was supported by the ideas of the innovators. Shortly afterwards, M\u00f6ller became the first Gauleiter of the Banat in 1932 and founded the National Socialist newspaper \u201cDer St\u00fcrmer\u201d in Timi\u0219oara in the same year. In the spring of 1933, he was deposed again as Gauleiter. In the same year, he served as \"cultural office manager\" in Sibiuthe \"job for ideological education and cultural policy\". After his application for admission to the Wehrmacht had been rejected because he had exceeded the entry age limit, he wrote to Karl Schworm on September 7, 1939: \"What would I be happy if fate put me at the front, regardless of whether in west or east! I can't think of a better way to end my fighting life than to end up for the leader and the empire. \u201d In 1941 he was appointed the\u201c cultural council \u201dof the German ethnic group in Romania.\n\n== Author ==\nAccording to his biography on the \"Kulturportal West-Ost\", in addition to his political \"von M\u00f6ller\" developed a lively writing activity, which was based on the great novels of Adam M\u00fcller-Guttenbrunn (1852-1923) and the intellectual and political development of Southeastern Germany, but especially the Banat Swabia, from the settlement until their ethnic awakening at the turn of the 20th century. As editor-in-chief of the 'Banater Deutsche Zeitung', he served the 'Banater Schw\u00e4bische Volksgemeinschaft'.\u201d\n\nVon M\u00f6ller's novels try to give a concrete picture of the respective events from the perspective of their time. He is one of the most popular authors of historical novels of his time, but with a nationalist and anti-Semitic touch. From M\u00f6ller began in the early 1920s with the publication ultranationalist writings. As \"advocate of folk anti-Semitism\" he wrote in his Gazette \"The Striker\". In his two-volume work \"How the Swabian communities came into being\" (Timi\u0219oara 1923\u201324), M\u00f6ller 1924 \"openly expressed his chauvinistic ideas and ideas by incorporating the 'Germanic racial element' (Vol. 2, p. 22) of the German superman into The foreground of his historical statements moved. \n\nIn the novel \u201cDie Werschetzer Tat\u201d (1936) he glorified the defence of Werschetz on the westernmost slope of the Banat Mountains at the time of the last great invasion of the Banat in 1788 by the Turks. Based on historical events, the author illustrates the rural life of German settlers of the first generation in the midst of a colourful mix of people and people. He takes on Nazi ideologies back such. B. The glorification of struggle, peasantry and leader personality, the superiority of the \" Aryan race\", inferiority, moral and physical degradation of the \"foreign people\": The Germans \"must be protected from the teeth of the strange army wolf, who runs up and down the Danube with hanging blood tongues.\"\n\nIn the novel \"Borders Wander: A Banat Roman\" (1937) von M\u00f6ller describes his life and customs of the Banat Swabians from the turn of the century about the First World War and the resulting tripartite division of the Banat in 1920 using the example of the predominantly German-inhabited place Jimbolia. The place fell to Yugoslavia after 1918 and to Romania in 1924 in exchange for Ja\u0161a Tomi\u0107. As in \"The Werschetzer act\" must also in this novel the \"Aryan\" hero \"against their racial opponent\" claim.\n\nIn the novel \"Die Salpeterer: A Freedom Struggle by German Peasants\" (1938) M\u00f6ller describes the struggle for freedom of the Hotzenwald Salpeterer in the Black Forest against the Prince-Bishop of St. Blasien and their eventual banishment to the Banat. He describes their homesickness and defiance against the injustice suffered from their point of view and only allows them to become \"real Banat farmers\" after generations. \n\nvon M\u00f6ller was very active as a writer in his last years. Above all, he published in the [[Eher-Verlag]] of the [[NSDAP]].\n\nOn October 11, 1941, the author's 65th birthday, [[Reich Minister]] [[Joseph Goebbels]] expressed his thanks to the nation.\n\n==Military career==\n\nAfter graduating from cadet school and from the Military Academy in [[Vienna]], he was appointed as a senior state officer{{clarify|date=September 2018}}, and served in several garrisons. In 1913 he was transferred to [[Timi\u0219oara]] where he served in the 34th Infantry Division during the 1914 campaigns in Serbia and Galicia. He was then transferred to the headquarters in Vienna. In 1916, he was promoted from [[Oberstleutnant|Lieutenant Colonel]] to Commander of the 65th Infantry Regiment of Hungary. Under his command, the 65th Infantry Regiment of Hungary fought on the eastern front, and M\u00f6ller was subsequently promoted to [[Oberst|Colonel]]. At the end of the war, the regiment suppressed the uprising of the Republicans in [[Upper Hungary]] (now [[Slovakia]]) after which it was put in reserve by the K\u00e1rolyi government.<ref>[http://hatzfeld-banat.de/index.php?option=com_content&view=section&id = 9 & Itemid = 19 Hatzfelder Pers\u00f6nlichkeiten-Schrifsteller]</ref>\n\n==Political career in Romania==\n\nPost [[World War I]], M\u00f6ller decided to stay back in Timi\u0219oara, where he joined the German Popular Movement of Banat (''Bewegung des Banater Deutschtums''), bolstering its struggle for self-affirmation. He forayed into the cultural field as a journalist{{clarify|date=September 2018}}, and later became active in politics. He held the position of editor-in-chief at ''Schw\u00e4bische Volkspresse'' (established 1921; from 1925 the ''Banat Deutsche Zeitung'') for several years, strengthening the voice of the Swabian-German community. In September 1923 Karl von M\u00f6ller actively participated in a celebration of the 200th anniversary of the migration of the Swabians organized by the Banat German Movement.\n\nIn autumn 1919 he was briefly Deputy Mayor of Timi\u0219oara, after which he was elected four times to the [[Parliament of Romania|Romanian Parliament]], in which he served between 1919 and 1927 as a representative of the Swabians in Banat. In the parliamentary debate on the [[1923 Constitution of Romania]] on March 12, 1923, he said he was speaking on behalf of the \"Banat Swabian People\", declaring the Germans' loyalty to their new homeland, but demanded that the new constitution should not jeopardize the existence of minorities from a national point of view; he said the new constitution did not include the promises made to the minorities by the Romanians in [[Union of Transylvania with Romania|Alba Iulia]].<ref>[http://www.uefromania.ro / evolution-German-from-banat-in-context-administrative-demographic-political-and-legislative-in-the-interwar period / Evolution of German education in Banat in administrative context , demographic, political and legislative in the interwar period]</ref>\n\nIn May 1920 the \"moderate\" Swabians, led by [https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kaspar_Muth Kaspar Muth], formed the Swabian Party of Autonomy, joined by Karl von M\u00f6ller, [https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Josef_Gabriel_(Politiker,_1880) Dr Joseph Gabriel], and Peter Schiff of the National Swabian-German party.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.muzeulbanatului.ro/istorie/publicatii/analele_banatului_2008/3_6_narai.pdf | title=Muzeulbanatului.ro }}{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn 1927, M\u00f6ller withdrew from public life and settled in [[Jimbolia]], where he married Margaret Jung, the daughter of a wealthy farmer from the Banat. Together they had two children, Karlheinz and Erich\n\n==Involvement in Nazism==\nAt the beginning of 1931, he returned to public life, becoming the chief editor of the German-language Jimbolia newspaper, [[\"Hatzfelder Zeitung\"]], and president of the local ethnic community. M\u00f6ller, who adhered to Nazi ideology, tried to use these positions to popularise Nazism and prepare the Banat population for its adoption. This attempt was thwarted, and he lost both positions by the end of 1931.\n\nAfter 1930, and especially after 1933, the Nazi movement had achieved a strong position in Romania, capturing the leadership of the Germans in Romania. The initiator of the Nazi movement among the German minority was the reserve captain [https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fritz_Fabritius Fritz Fabritius]. From 1931, Fabritius tried to expand the movement in Banat, finding audiences in some circles of dissatisfied and young Swabians who returned from studies in Germany. At the end of 1931, Karl von M\u00f6ller constituted a movement group at Jimbolia and was proclaimed the \"Gauleiter\" for the Banat.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">= Aspects</ref>\n\nAfter Karl von M\u00f6ller became the first [[Gauleiter]] of the Banat, from July 1, 1932, he published the antisemitic newspaper \"Der St\u00fcrmer\" in Timi\u0219oara. It was an imitation of the publication [[Der St\u00fcrmer]] published in Germany by the German Nazi [[Julius Streicher]] who, after World War II, was sentenced to death in the first of the [[Nuremberg trials]], found guilty of [[crimes against humanity]] and executed by [[hanging]] in 1946.<ref>William Totok: The Germans in Romania Between Nazism and Stalinism, Divers, 2003 [http://www.divers.ro/germanii_din_romania_intre_nazism_si_stalinism_de_william_totok_ro] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927034205/http://www.divers.ro/germanii_din_romania_intre_nazism_si_stalinism_de_william_totok_ro |date=September 27, 2007 }}</ref><ref>William Totok: The Germans in Romania Between Nazism and Stalinism, in: Cultural Observatory, Nr. 197 \u2013 December 2, 2003, [http://www.observatorcultural.com/Germanii-din-Romania-intre-nazism-si-stalinism*articleID_9752-articles_details.html] and Errata. Correction on the German Rule in Romania between Nazism and Stalinism ... in: Cultural Observatory, Nr. 198, December 9, 2003, [http://www.observatorcultural.com/Erata.-Recertification-privind-articolul-Germanii-din-Romania-intre-nazism-si-stalinism...*articleID_9811-articles_details.html]</ref>\n\nM\u00f6ller also led the Cultural Office of the Germans in Romania (''Kulturamt der Deutschen in Rum\u00e4nien''),<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=UwjizwipYSQC&pg=PA503&lpg=PA503&dq=%22Karl + von + M% C3% B6ller% 22 + 1886 & source = bl & OTS = OlCZ4PpjMe & sig = l_F33SVkPpcI8LYHwcxNasXRgp0 & hl = en & they = 1XRZTNa2HZ-TONqq-IUJ & SA = X & oi = book_result & ct = result & resnum = 3 & ved = 0CCQQ6AEwAg # v = onepage & q =% 22Karl% 20von% 20M% C3% B6ller% 22% 201886 & f = false Christian von Zimmermann: Biographische Anthropologie]</ref> established by [[Rudolf Brandsch]] to protect the cultural assets of the Germans in Romania.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=GE0N7ovizoAC&pg=PA315 Bernhard B\u00f6ttcher: Gefallen f\u00fcr Volk und Heimat]</ref>\n\nIn 1934 he took the lead of the Provincial Cultural Office of the Renewal Movement (''Landeskulturamt der Erneuerungsbewegung'') in [[Sibiu]], where he stayed for five years, and lived until his death on February 21, 1943.\n\n==Books==\n*''Wie die schw\u00e4bischen Gemeinden entstanden sind'', Timi\u0219oara, 1923\n*''Karl von M\u00f6ller, ''Die Werschetzer Tat'', Der Gro\u00dfe Brockhaus, Leipzig, 1935.\n*''Die Werschertzer / Ein Roman von Bauern und Reitern'', Verlag Franz Eher, Nachf. Berlin, 1938\n*''Reiter im Grenzland'', Erz\u00e4hlung, 1939\n*''Der Aufkl\u00e4rer'' \u2013 Novelle, Wien/Leipzig, Wiener Verlag, 1939\n*''Grenzen wandern. Ein Banater Roman'', Leipzig, Amalthea-Verlag, 1940.\n*''Im Schatten der Exzellenz'', Novellen, 1940\n*''Deutsches Schicksal im Banat'', 1940\n*''Das steinerne Schachbrett'' (Roman), Braunschweig, Berlin, Hamburg. Georg Westermann, 1941\n*''Frontbriefe deutscher Arbeitskameraden 1939 \u2013 1940'', Die Lothringerin NSDAP Verlag EA 1942\n*''Die Salpeterer, ein Freiheitskampf deutscher Bauern'', 1942\n*''Der Savoyer'' (Ein Prinz Eugen Roman), M\u00fcnchen Verlag Franz Eber Nachf. Gmbh, 1943.\n*''Sp\u00e4tsommer; Eine Geschichte aus Wien'', Franz Eber, 1943\n*''Das Korsett der Marquise'', 1944\n*''Die Lothringerin, Roman eines Frauenlebens zwischen zwei Nationen und zwei Zeitaltern'', 1944\n\n==Awards==\n*''Kurt Faber Prize'', 1938<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=AHSoarKfWREC&pg=PA112 Helga Strallhofer-Mitterbauer : NS-Literaturpreise f\u00fcr \u00d6sterreichische Autoren]</ref>\n* ''[[Order_of_Leopold_(Austria)|Order of Leopold]]'', 1916\n\n==Note==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:M\u00f6ller, Karl von}}\n[[Category:1886 births]]\n[[Category:1943 deaths]]\n[[Category:German writers]]\n[[Category:Banat]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n{{original research|date=March 2017}}\n\n{{rough translation|1=German|listed=yes|date=September 2018}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name          = Karl von M\u00f6ller\n| image         = Karl von M\u00f6ller.jpg\n| birth_name    = Karl Leopold von M\u00f6ller\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1876|10|11}}\n| birth_place   = [[Vienna]], Austria\n| death_date    = {{death date|1943|2|21}}\n| death_place   = [[Jimbolia]], Romania\n| occupation    = Writer, politician, journalist, officer\n| notableworks  = [[Der St\u00fcrmer]]\n| spouses       = {{marriage|Baroness Agathe von Veroczy|1917|1923|end=divorce}}{{plainlist}}{{marriage |Margaret Jung|1927|1943|end=died}}<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.geni.com/people/Karl-Leopold-Edler-von-M%C3%B6-ller-von-M%C3%B6ller-Harteneck/6000000026523073826?through=6000000026524041123 | title=Karl Leopold Edler von M\u00f6ller Leopold von M\u00f6ller-Harteneck}}</ref>\n| children      = 3 (Edith, Karl-Heinz and Erich)\n| relatives     =\n}}\n\n'''Karl von M\u00f6ller''' (October 11, 1876, [[Vienna]] - February 21, 1943, [[Jimbolia]])<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.buchfreund.de/productListing.php?used=1&productId=41706697 | title=Das steinerne Schachbrett. Roman. M\u00f6ller, Karl von: 6480BB}}</ref> was an officer, journalist, author and politician from [[Banat]]. He was an enthusiastic supporter of [[Hitler]]'s [[National Socialism]], and in 1932 he published the antisemitic newspaper \"Der St\u00fcrmer\" in [[Timi\u0219oara]], an imitation of the German [[Nazi]] publication. He was married to Margaret Jung, with whom he had two children.\n\n==Life and early work==\nThe von M\u00f6ller family's origins point to the [[L\u00fcneburg Heath]]. Karl von M\u00f6ller's grandfather volunteered in the [[German Campaign of 1813|Wars of Liberation]] and was disarmed in [[Sibiu]] (Transylvania). von M\u00f6ller's grandfather is also allegedly an early developer of the [[Camera]] but didn't submit the patent in time. His father came to Vienna from Sibiu. Karl von M\u00f6ller was born in Vienna, where he attended the cadet school and the war school after high school. During the First World War, he moved as a major and chief of staff of the 34th Infantry Division, Banater Division, first to the Serbian and then to the Galician front. Von M\u00f6ller led from 1916 as a lieutenant colonel and later as colonel Hungarian Infantry Regiment No. 65 on the Eastern Front. He was awarded the [[Order of Leopold]].\n\n== Politician ==\nAfter the collapse of the Habsburg monarchy in 1918, he left the army as a colonel and went to Timi\u0219oara, where he campaigned for political and cultural equality for Romanian Germans in the field of national politics.  von M\u00f6ller was May 9, 1919, co-founded the German-Swabian Cultural Association, whose chairman Johann Junker was. The executive chairman was Michael Kausch. In 1919 M\u00f6ller was elected the second mayor of Timi\u0219oara. From 1919 to 1926 he was a senator in the Romanian upper house in Bucharest, representing Banat Swabia. Karl von M\u00f6ller joined the \"Volksgemeinschaft\" together with Josef Gabriel in 1920.\n\nFrom 1920 he made trips to Germany, gave lectures in Saxony, Westphalia, Baden, W\u00fcrttemberg, Thuringia, Berlin and Munich. In 1923 he had contacts with National Socialist circles; he is considered an early supporter of Adolf Hitler. After his return, he became chief editor of the \"Banat German newspaper\". He was one of the members of the \"German People's Council\".\n\nvon M\u00f6ller is considered one of the pioneers of fascism in the Banat. In 1931 he founded the first Banat local group of the \"National Socialist Self-Help Movement of the Germans in Romania\" (NSDR) in Jimbolia (German: Hatzfeld), which was supported by the ideas of the innovators. Shortly afterwards, M\u00f6ller became the first Gauleiter of the Banat in 1932 and founded the National Socialist newspaper \u201cDer St\u00fcrmer\u201d in Timi\u0219oara in the same year. In the spring of 1933, he was deposed again as Gauleiter. In the same year, he served as \"cultural office manager\" in Sibiuthe \"job for ideological education and cultural policy\". After his application for admission to the Wehrmacht had been rejected because he had exceeded the entry age limit, he wrote to Karl Schworm on September 7, 1939: \"What would I be happy if fate put me at the front, regardless of whether in west or east! I can't think of a better way to end my fighting life than to end up for the leader and the empire. \u201d In 1941 he was appointed the\u201c cultural council \u201dof the German ethnic group in Romania.\n\n==Military career==\n\nAfter graduating from cadet school and from the Military Academy in [[Vienna]], he was appointed as a senior state officer{{clarify|date=September 2018}}, and served in several garrisons. In 1913 he was transferred to [[Timi\u0219oara]] where he served in the 34th Infantry Division during the 1914 campaigns in Serbia and Galicia. He was then transferred to the headquarters in Vienna. In 1916, he was promoted from [[Oberstleutnant|Lieutenant Colonel]] to Commander of the 65th Infantry Regiment of Hungary. Under his command, the 65th Infantry Regiment of Hungary fought on the eastern front, and M\u00f6ller was subsequently promoted to [[Oberst|Colonel]]. At the end of the war, the regiment suppressed the uprising of the Republicans in [[Upper Hungary]] (now [[Slovakia]]) after which it was put in reserve by the K\u00e1rolyi government.<ref>[http://hatzfeld-banat.de/index.php?option=com_content&view=section&id = 9 & Itemid = 19 Hatzfelder Pers\u00f6nlichkeiten-Schrifsteller]</ref>\n\n==Political career in Romania==\n\nPost [[World War I]], M\u00f6ller decided to stay back in Timi\u0219oara, where he joined the German Popular Movement of Banat (''Bewegung des Banater Deutschtums''), bolstering its struggle for self-affirmation. He forayed into the cultural field as a journalist{{clarify|date=September 2018}}, and later became active in politics. He held the position of editor-in-chief at ''Schw\u00e4bische Volkspresse'' (established 1921; from 1925 the ''Banat Deutsche Zeitung'') for several years, strengthening the voice of the Swabian-German community. In September 1923 Karl von M\u00f6ller actively participated in a celebration of the 200th anniversary of the migration of the Swabians organized by the Banat German Movement.\n\nIn autumn 1919 he was briefly Deputy Mayor of Timi\u0219oara, after which he was elected four times to the [[Parliament of Romania|Romanian Parliament]], in which he served between 1919 and 1927 as a representative of the Swabians in Banat. In the parliamentary debate on the [[1923 Constitution of Romania]] on March 12, 1923, he said he was speaking on behalf of the \"Banat Swabian People\", declaring the Germans' loyalty to their new homeland, but demanded that the new constitution should not jeopardize the existence of minorities from a national point of view; he said the new constitution did not include the promises made to the minorities by the Romanians in [[Union of Transylvania with Romania|Alba Iulia]].<ref>[http://www.uefromania.ro / evolution-German-from-banat-in-context-administrative-demographic-political-and-legislative-in-the-interwar period / Evolution of German education in Banat in administrative context , demographic, political and legislative in the interwar period]</ref>\n\nIn May 1920 the \"moderate\" Swabians, led by [https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kaspar_Muth Kaspar Muth], formed the Swabian Party of Autonomy, joined by Karl von M\u00f6ller, [https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Josef_Gabriel_(Politiker,_1880) Dr Joseph Gabriel], and Peter Schiff of the National Swabian-German party.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.muzeulbanatului.ro/istorie/publicatii/analele_banatului_2008/3_6_narai.pdf | title=Muzeulbanatului.ro }}{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn 1927, M\u00f6ller withdrew from public life and settled in [[Jimbolia]], where he married Margaret Jung, the daughter of a wealthy farmer from the Banat. Together they had two children, Karlheinz and Erich\n\n==Involvement in Nazism==\nAt the beginning of 1931, he returned to public life, becoming the chief editor of the German-language Jimbolia newspaper, [[\"Hatzfelder Zeitung\"]], and president of the local ethnic community. M\u00f6ller, who adhered to Nazi ideology, tried to use these positions to popularise Nazism and prepare the Banat population for its adoption. This attempt was thwarted, and he lost both positions by the end of 1931.\n\nAfter 1930, and especially after 1933, the Nazi movement had achieved a strong position in Romania, capturing the leadership of the Germans in Romania. The initiator of the Nazi movement among the German minority was the reserve captain [https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fritz_Fabritius Fritz Fabritius]. From 1931, Fabritius tried to expand the movement in Banat, finding audiences in some circles of dissatisfied and young Swabians who returned from studies in Germany. At the end of 1931, Karl von M\u00f6ller constituted a movement group at Jimbolia and was proclaimed the \"Gauleiter\" for the Banat.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">= Aspects</ref>\n\nAfter Karl von M\u00f6ller became the first [[Gauleiter]] of the Banat, from July 1, 1932, he published the antisemitic newspaper \"Der St\u00fcrmer\" in Timi\u0219oara. It was an imitation of the publication [[Der St\u00fcrmer]] published in Germany by the German Nazi [[Julius Streicher]] who, after World War II, was sentenced to death in the first of the [[Nuremberg trials]], found guilty of [[crimes against humanity]] and executed by [[hanging]] in 1946.<ref>William Totok: The Germans in Romania Between Nazism and Stalinism, Divers, 2003 [http://www.divers.ro/germanii_din_romania_intre_nazism_si_stalinism_de_william_totok_ro] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927034205/http://www.divers.ro/germanii_din_romania_intre_nazism_si_stalinism_de_william_totok_ro |date=September 27, 2007 }}</ref><ref>William Totok: The Germans in Romania Between Nazism and Stalinism, in: Cultural Observatory, Nr. 197 \u2013 December 2, 2003, [http://www.observatorcultural.com/Germanii-din-Romania-intre-nazism-si-stalinism*articleID_9752-articles_details.html] and Errata. Correction on the German Rule in Romania between Nazism and Stalinism ... in: Cultural Observatory, Nr. 198, December 9, 2003, [http://www.observatorcultural.com/Erata.-Recertification-privind-articolul-Germanii-din-Romania-intre-nazism-si-stalinism...*articleID_9811-articles_details.html]</ref>\n\nM\u00f6ller also led the Cultural Office of the Germans in Romania (''Kulturamt der Deutschen in Rum\u00e4nien''),<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=UwjizwipYSQC&pg=PA503&lpg=PA503&dq=%22Karl + von + M% C3% B6ller% 22 + 1886 & source = bl & OTS = OlCZ4PpjMe & sig = l_F33SVkPpcI8LYHwcxNasXRgp0 & hl = en & they = 1XRZTNa2HZ-TONqq-IUJ & SA = X & oi = book_result & ct = result & resnum = 3 & ved = 0CCQQ6AEwAg # v = onepage & q =% 22Karl% 20von% 20M% C3% B6ller% 22% 201886 & f = false Christian von Zimmermann: Biographische Anthropologie]</ref> established by [[Rudolf Brandsch]] to protect the cultural assets of the Germans in Romania.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=GE0N7ovizoAC&pg=PA315 Bernhard B\u00f6ttcher: Gefallen f\u00fcr Volk und Heimat]</ref>\n\nIn 1934 he took the lead of the Provincial Cultural Office of the Renewal Movement (''Landeskulturamt der Erneuerungsbewegung'') in [[Sibiu]], where he stayed for five years, and lived until his death on February 21, 1943.\n\n==Books==\n*''Wie die schw\u00e4bischen Gemeinden entstanden sind'', Timi\u0219oara, 1923\n*''Karl von M\u00f6ller, ''Die Werschetzer Tat'', Der Gro\u00dfe Brockhaus, Leipzig, 1935.\n*''Die Werschertzer / Ein Roman von Bauern und Reitern'', Verlag Franz Eher, Nachf. Berlin, 1938\n*''Reiter im Grenzland'', Erz\u00e4hlung, 1939\n*''Der Aufkl\u00e4rer'' \u2013 Novelle, Wien/Leipzig, Wiener Verlag, 1939\n*''Grenzen wandern. Ein Banater Roman'', Leipzig, Amalthea-Verlag, 1940.\n*''Im Schatten der Exzellenz'', Novellen, 1940\n*''Deutsches Schicksal im Banat'', 1940\n*''Das steinerne Schachbrett'' (Roman), Braunschweig, Berlin, Hamburg. Georg Westermann, 1941\n*''Frontbriefe deutscher Arbeitskameraden 1939 \u2013 1940'', Die Lothringerin NSDAP Verlag EA 1942\n*''Die Salpeterer, ein Freiheitskampf deutscher Bauern'', 1942\n*''Der Savoyer'' (Ein Prinz Eugen Roman), M\u00fcnchen Verlag Franz Eber Nachf. Gmbh, 1943.\n*''Sp\u00e4tsommer; Eine Geschichte aus Wien'', Franz Eber, 1943\n*''Das Korsett der Marquise'', 1944\n*''Die Lothringerin, Roman eines Frauenlebens zwischen zwei Nationen und zwei Zeitaltern'', 1944\n\n==Awards==\n*''Kurt Faber Prize'', 1938<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=AHSoarKfWREC&pg=PA112 Helga Strallhofer-Mitterbauer : NS-Literaturpreise f\u00fcr \u00d6sterreichische Autoren]</ref>\n* ''[[Order_of_Leopold_(Austria)|Order of Leopold]]'', 1916\n\n==Note==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:M\u00f6ller, Karl von}}\n[[Category:1886 births]]\n[[Category:1943 deaths]]\n[[Category:German writers]]\n[[Category:Banat]]\n", "name_user": "MVA33", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karl_Leopold_von_M%C3%B6ller"}
{"title_page": "Karim Benzema", "text_new": "{{short description|French association football player}}\n{{pp-pc1}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Karim Benzema\n| image = CSKA-RM18 (11).jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Benzema playing for [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] in 2018\n| fullname = Karim Mostafa Benzema<ref>{{cite web |url=http://actas.rfef.es/actas/RFEF_CmpActa1?cod_primaria=1000144&CodActa=33786 |title=Acta del Partido celebrado el 20 de marzo de 2016, en Madrid |trans-title=Minutes of the Match held on 20 March 2016, in Madrid |publisher=Royal Spanish Football Federation |accessdate=15 June 2019 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1987|12|19|df=y}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fifadata.com/documents/FCWC/2017/pdf/FCWC_2017_Squadlists.pdf |title=FIFA Club World Cup UAE 2017: List of players: Real Madrid CF |publisher=FIFA |format=PDF |page=5 |date=16 December 2017 |accessdate=23 December 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Cork]], Ireland\n| height = 2.05 m<ref>{{cite web|title=Real Madrid C.F.&nbsp;\u2013 Karim Benzema|url=http://www.realmadrid.com/en/football/squad/karim-benzema|publisher=[[Real Madrid]]|accessdate=18 November 2017}}</ref>\n| position = [[Forward (association football)#Striker|Striker]]\n| currentclub = [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]]\n| clubnumber = 9\n| youthyears1 = 1995\u20131997 | youthclubs1 = SC Bron\n| youthyears2 = 1997\u20132005 | youthclubs2 = [[Olympique Lyonnais Reserves and Academy|Lyon]]\n| years1 = 2004\u20132006 | clubs1 = [[Olympique Lyonnais Reserves and Academy|Lyon B]] | caps1 = 20 | goals1 = 15\n| years2 = 2004\u20132009 | clubs2 = [[Olympique Lyonnais|Lyon]] | caps2 = 112 | goals2 = 43\n| years3 = 2009\u2013 | clubs3 = [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] | caps3 = 338 | goals3 = 162\n| nationalyears1 = 2004 | nationalteam1 = [[France national under-17 football team|France U17]] | nationalcaps1 = 4 | nationalgoals1 = 1\n| nationalyears2 = 2004\u20132005 | nationalteam2 = [[France national under-18 football team|France U18]] | nationalcaps2 = 17 | nationalgoals2 = 14\n| nationalyears3 = 2005\u20132006 | nationalteam3 = [[France national under-19 football team|France U19]] | nationalcaps3 = 9 | nationalgoals3 = 5\n| nationalyears4 = 2006 | nationalteam4 = [[France national under-21 football team|France U21]] | nationalcaps4 = 5 | nationalgoals4 = 0\n| nationalyears5 = 2007\u2013 | nationalteam5 = [[France national football team|France]] | nationalcaps5 = 81 | nationalgoals5 = 27\n| pcupdate = 22:55, 8 March 2020 (UTC)\n| ntupdate = 11 October 2015\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport|Men's [[association football|football]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{fb|FRA}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[UEFA European Under-17 Championship]]}}\n{{Medal|W|[[2004 UEFA European Under-17 Championship|2004 France]]|}}\n}}\n'''Karim Mostafa Benzema''' ({{IPA-fr|ka\u0281im b\u025bnzema}}; born 19 December 1987) is a French professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Forward (association football)#Striker|striker]] for Spanish club [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] and the [[France national football team|France national team]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/world-cup/player/bio?id=46858&cc=5901&ver=us|title=Karim Benzema: Overview |publisher=[[ESPN]]|date= |accessdate=29 March 2011}}</ref> He has been described as an \"immensely talented striker\" who is \"strong and powerful\" and \"a potent finisher from inside the box\".<ref name=Bio>{{cite news |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/player/_/id/46858/karim-benzema?cc=5901|title=Karim Benzema ESPN Bio |publisher=[[ESPN]]|date= |accessdate=29 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nBenzema was born in the city of [[Lyon]] and began his football career with local club Bron Terraillon. In 1996, he joined [[Olympique Lyonnais]], and subsequently came through the [[Olympique Lyonnais Reserves and Academy|club's youth academy]]. Benzema made his professional debut in the [[2004\u201305 Ligue 1|2004\u201305 season]] and appeared sporadically in his first three seasons as Lyon won three titles in that span. In the [[2007\u201308 Ligue 1|2007\u201308 season]], Benzema became a starter and had a breakthrough year scoring over 30 goals as Lyon won its seventh straight league title. For his performances, he was named the [[National Union of Professional Footballers]] (UNFP) [[Ligue 1]] [[Troph\u00e9es UNFP du football#Player of the Year|Player of the Year]] and named to the organization's [[Troph\u00e9es UNFP du football#2008|Team of the Year]]. Benzema was also the [[Top goalscorers in Ligue 1|league's top scorer]] and given the [[Bravo Award]] by Italian magazine ''[[Guerin Sportivo]]''. After another season at Lyon, in July 2009, Benzema moved to Real Madrid in a transfer fee worth over \u20ac35&nbsp;million ($50&nbsp;million), and signed a six-year contract.<ref>[http://edition.cnn.com/2009/SPORT/football/07/02/lyon.benzema.real.madrid/index.html?eref=rss_latest \"Benzema agrees six-year deal at Real Madrid\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304232400/http://edition.cnn.com/2009/SPORT/football/07/02/lyon.benzema.real.madrid/index.html?eref=rss_latest |date=4 March 2016}}. CNN. Retrieved 10 June 2014</ref> After struggling to establish himself in his debut season with the club, in the ensuing two seasons, Benzema reached prominence, scoring 32 goals en route to helping Real Madrid win the [[2010\u201311 Copa del Rey|Copa del Rey]] in 2011 and the [[2011\u201312 La Liga|2011\u201312 edition]] of La Liga. He has been named [[France Football#French Player of the Year|French Player of the Year]] three times for his performances in 2011, 2012 and 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.francefootball.fr/#!/news/2011/12/13/095921_le-palmares-francais-2011.html |title=Benzema, Garcia, Martin et Hazard r\u00e9compens\u00e9s |publisher=[[France Football]] |date = 13 December 2011 |accessdate=13 December 2011 | language = French}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.realmadrid.com/en/news/2014/12/benzema-best-french-player-of-the-year|title = Benzema, best French player of the year|date = 15 December 2014|accessdate = 15 February 2015|website = RealMadrid.com|publisher = |last = |first =}}</ref>\n\nBenzema is a former [[France national youth football team|French youth international]] and has represented his nation from [[France national under-17 football team|under-17 level]] onwards. Prior to playing for the senior team, he played on the under-17 team that won the [[2004 UEFA European Under-17 Championship]]. Benzema made his senior international debut in March 2007 in a friendly match against [[Austria national football team|Austria]], scoring in a 1\u20130 win. Benzema has earned over 80 caps and represented France at three major international tournaments: the [[UEFA Euro 2008|2008]] and [[UEFA Euro 2012|2012]] editions of the [[UEFA European Championship]] and the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]]. However, Benzema has been left out of major tournament squads on three occasions: [[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010 World Cup]] due to lack of playing time with Real Madrid, [[UEFA Euro 2016|Euro 2016]] after a publicised scandal involving blackmail, and [[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018 World Cup]] for alleged tactical reasons.<ref>{{cite news |title=World Cup 2010: No place for Patrick Vieira and Karim Benzema in France squad|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/france/7712646/World-Cup-2010-No-place-for-Patrick-Vieira-and-Karim-Benzema-in-France-squad.html|work=The Telegraph |date=11 May 2010 |accessdate=31 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Karim Benzema left out of France squad in wake of sex-tape blackmail case|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/mar/17/karim-benzema-france-sex-tape-squad-real-madrid |work=The Guardian |date=17 March 2016 |accessdate=31 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://en.as.com/en/2018/05/31/football/1527758335_120289.html|title=Benzema hits back after FFF president backs World Cup omission|date=31 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\n===Early career===\n{{Quote box\n| width = 27%\n| align = right\n| quote = \"When I was younger, the way [[Ronaldo (Brazilian footballer)|Ronaldo]] played had an influence on me. For me, he\u2019s the best striker of all-time. I watch videos of him, and try to do what he does, but it\u2019s not easy. It\u2019s impossible to pull off the same moves as he did.\"\n| source = \u2014Benzema on the influence of his idol, Brazilian striker Ronaldo, on his own career.<ref>{{cite news |title=Karim Benzema Names His Idol and Claims Zinedine Zidane Offers a Lot|url=https://www.90min.com/posts/2958310-revealed-karim-benzema-names-his-idol-and-claims-zinedine-zidane-offers-a-lot |agency=90min.com |date=4 July 2018}}</ref>\n}}\nBenzema began his football career at his hometown club Bron Terraillon SC at the age of eight. While at the club, he was nicknamed ''Coco'' by friends and, after scoring two goals in an under-10 match against the [[Olympique Lyonnais Reserves and Academy|Lyon youth academy]], began attracting attention from the biggest club in the city.<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema s'attend \u00e0 un match difficile contre \"son \u00e9quipe\" |url=http://www.lyoncapitale.fr/Journal/univers/Sport/Football-ligue-des-champions/Benzema-s-attend-a-un-match-difficile-contre-son-equipe |work=Lyon Capitale |date=2 November 2011 |accessdate=7 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref><ref name=\"benzema_class\">{{cite news |title=Benzema: la classe internationale |url=http://www.lyoncapitale.fr/Journal/univers/Sport/Football/Benzema-la-classe-internationale/%28language%29/fre-FR |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130107052935/http://www.lyoncapitale.fr/Journal/univers/Sport/Football/Benzema-la-classe-internationale/(language)/fre-FR |url-status=dead |archive-date=7 January 2013 |work=Lyon Capitale |date=18 September 2007 |accessdate=7 May 2012 |language=French }}</ref> According to Serge Santa Cruz, who was president of Bron Terraillon in the 1990s, Lyon officials had visited him directly in an attempt to sign the youngster; however, Santa Cruz refused.<ref name=\"benzema_youth\">{{cite news |title=Benzema, le ph\u00e9nom\u00e8ne qui r\u00e9veille le foot |url=http://www.lepoint.fr/actualites-societe/2008-02-07/benzema-le-phenomene-qui-reveille-le-foot/920/0/222742 |work=Le Point |date=7 February 2008 |accessdate=7 May 2012 |language=French |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304041607/http://www.lepoint.fr/actualites-societe/2008-02-07/benzema-le-phenomene-qui-reveille-le-foot/920/0/222742 |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> After talking with Benzema's father, the club allowed the player to undergo a trial with Lyon.<ref name=\"benzema_youth\"/> Following the trial, Benzema officially joined Lyon and was inserted into the club's academy.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Rise and Rise of Karim Benzema |url=http://www.insidefutbol.com/2008/03/04/the-rise-and-rise-of-karim-benzema/ |work=Inside Futebol |date=19 December 2006 |accessdate=25 June 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Lyon===\nBenzema quickly ascended up the youth categories in the academy. He served as a [[ballboy]] during Lyon senior team matches and performed well in school being described as a student who was \"discreet and respectful\".<ref name=\"benzema_youth\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Karim Benzema |url=http://www.olweb.fr/fr/Accueil/700004/Article/50732/Benzema-Karim |work=[[Olympique Lyonnais]] |accessdate=7 May 2012 |language=French |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091003140811/http://www.olweb.fr/fr/Accueil/700004/Article/50732/Benzema-Karim |archivedate=3 October 2009}}</ref> At under-16 level, Benzema scored 38 goals in the ''Championnat National des 16 ans'', the domestic league for under-16 youth players in France.<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema, un Lyon de Olympique |url=http://fr.uefa.com/footballeurope/news/kind=2/newsid=489158.html |work=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |date=19 December 2006 |accessdate=25 June 2009 | language = French}}</ref> Ahead of the [[2004\u201305 Ligue 1|2004\u201305 season]], Benzema was promoted to the club's reserve team, which was playing in the [[Championnat de France amateur]], the fourth division of [[Football in France|French football]]. Despite only playing with the team during the autumn campaign, he scored a team-high ten goals as the Lyon reserve team finished second in its group.<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema va signer Olympique Lyonnais Reserve Pro: Saison Football 2004/2005 |url=http://www.stat2foot.com/lclubs/lyon20405.htm |work=Stat2Foot |accessdate=7 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref>\n\n====2004\u20132007====\nBenzema was called up to the senior team for the first time under manager [[Paul Le Guen]] during the break leading up to the second half of the season. As is customary with new players arriving at Lyon, the young striker had to stand up and speak to his new teammates, which at that time included the likes of [[Michael Essien]], [[Sylvain Wiltord]], [[Florent Malouda]] and [[Eric Abidal]].<ref name=\"benzema_fifa\">{{cite news |title=Benzema, 20 ans et d\u00e9j\u00e0 tout d'un grand |url=http://fr.fifa.com/worldfootball/clubfootball/news/newsid=604499.html |work=[[FIFA|F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association]] |date=24 September 2007 |accessdate=7 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref> While speaking, Benzema was subjected to jokes and laughter, which prompted the youngster to declare, \"Do not laugh, I'm here to take your place.\"<ref name=\"benzema_fifa\"/> He, subsequently, made his professional debut on 15 January 2005 against [[FC Metz|Metz]], appearing as a substitute for [[Pierre-Alain Frau]]. Lyon won the match 2\u20130 as Benzema provided the assist on the second goal scored by [[Bryan Bergougnoux]].<ref name=\"benzema_class\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Lyon v. Metz Report |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuille_match/49038 |work=[[Ligue de Football Professionnel]] |date=15 January 2005 |accessdate=7 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref> He would subsequently sign his first professional contract, agreeing to a three-year deal.<ref>{{cite news|title=Benzema va signer pro |url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/20050120_114305Dev.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091027013858/http://www.lequipe.fr/Football/20050120_114305Dev.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=27 October 2009 |work=L'Equipe |date=20 January 2005 |accessdate=25 June 2009 |language=French}}</ref> After making three more appearances as a substitute, on 2 April Benzema made his first professional start in a 1\u20130 win over [[RC Lens|Lens]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Lyon v. Lens Report |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuille_match/49122 |work=[[Ligue de Football Professionnel]] |date=2 April 2005 |accessdate=7 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref> He finished the campaign with six appearances as Lyon won its fourth-straight league title.\n\nBenzema began the [[2005\u201306 Ligue 1|2005\u201306 season]] under the tutelage of new manager [[G\u00e9rard Houllier]]. Under Houllier, he struggled for meaningful minutes due to the presence of newly signed Brazilian striker [[Fred (footballer, born 1983)|Fred]], as well as Sylvain Wiltord. Benzema made his season debut on 2 October 2005 in a league win over [[Stade Rennais F.C.|Rennes]], appearing as a substitute.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rennes v. Lyon Report |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuille_match/49743 |work=[[Ligue de Football Professionnel]] |date=2 October 2005 |accessdate=7 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref> On 6 December, he made his [[UEFA Champions League]] debut in Lyon's final group stage match against [[Norway|Norwegian]] club [[Rosenborg BK|Rosenborg]]. On his competition debut, he scored his first professional goal in a 2\u20131 win.<ref>{{cite news|title=Fred leaves Lyon purring |url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/history/season=2005/round=2201/match=1100340/index.html |work=Union of European Football Associations |date=6 December 2005 |accessdate=7 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131115233619/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/history/season%3D2005/round%3D2201/match%3D1100340/index.html |archivedate=15 November 2013 }}</ref> A month later, Benzema scored his first professional double in a 4\u20130 win over [[Grenoble Foot 38|Grenoble]] in the [[Coupe de France]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Grenoble v. Lyon Report |url=http://www.eurosport.fr/football/coupe-de-france/2005-2006/grenoble-lyon_mtc131264/live.shtml |work=[[Eurosport]] |date=8 January 2006 |accessdate=7 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref> On 4 March 2006, Benzema scored his first professional league goal against [[AC Ajaccio|Ajaccio]] in a 3\u20131 win.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ajaccio v. Lyon Report |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuille_match/49906 |work=[[Ligue de Football Professionnel]] |date=4 March 2006 |accessdate=7 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref>\n\nBenzema began earning more playing time in the [[2006\u201307 Ligue 1|2006\u201307 season]] and made his competitive season debut in the [[2006 Troph\u00e9e des Champions]] against [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]]. In the French Supercup, Benzema converted a penalty which drew the match at 1\u20131. Lyon later won the league curtain-raiser 5\u20134 on penalties.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lyon v. Paris Saint-Germain Report |url=http://www.lfp.fr/tropheeChampions/feuille_match/51300 |work=[[Ligue de Football Professionnel]] |date=30 July 2006 |accessdate=7 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref> Benzema opened the league campaign on a quick note scoring in the team's first match of the season against [[FC Nantes|Nantes]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Nantes v. Lyon Report |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuille_match/50498 |work=[[Ligue de Football Professionnel]] |date=4 August 2006 |accessdate=7 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref> Three weeks later, on 26 August 2006, Benzema appeared as a substitute and scored two goals in a 4\u20131 away win over [[OGC Nice|Nice]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Nice v. Lyon Report |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuille_match/50506 |work=[[Ligue de Football Professionnel]] |date=26 August 2006 |accessdate=7 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref> He also converted two goals in the Champions League group stage against [[Romania]]n outfit [[FC Steaua Bucure\u0219ti|Steaua Bucure\u0219ti]] and [[Ukraine|Ukrainian]] club [[FC Dynamo Kyiv|Dynamo Kyiv]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Lyon reprise winning formula |url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/Competitions/ucl/history/season=2006/Round=2357/match=1116339/report=rp.html |work=Union of European Football Associations |date=26 September 2006 |accessdate=7 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131116005122/http://en.archive.uefa.com/Competitions/ucl/history/season=2006/Round=2357/match=1116339/report=rp.html |archive-date=16 November 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema leads Lyon into last 16 |url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/Competitions/ucl/history/season=2006/Round=2357/match=1116371/report=rp.html |work=Union of European Football Associations |date=1 November 2006 |accessdate=7 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131116005646/http://en.archive.uefa.com/Competitions/ucl/history/season=2006/Round=2357/match=1116371/report=rp.html |archive-date=16 November 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> After appearing regularly during the autumn campaign, on 10 November, Benzema suffered a severe thigh injury.<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema bless\u00e9 |url=http://www.football365.fr/france/infos-clubs/lyon/lyon-benzema-blesse-384129.shtml |work=Football365 |date=10 November 2006 |accessdate=7 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref> The injury resulted in the striker missing three months of action before returning in February 2007. Benzema failed to score a goal until the final league match of the season against Nantes as Lyon recorded its sixth consecutive league title.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lyon v. Nantes Report |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuille_match/50845 |work=[[Ligue de Football Professionnel]] |date=26 May 2007 |accessdate=7 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref>\n\n====2007\u201308 season====\nFor the [[2007\u201308 Ligue 1|2007\u201308 season]], with the likes of Florent Malouda, [[John Carew]] and Sylvain Wiltord all departing from the club, Benzema switched to the number 10 shirt and was inserted into the lead striker role. After forming a special relationship with new manager [[Alain Perrin]], he responded with 31 goals in 51 games. He topped the league with 20 goals, scored four goals in the Champions League, one in the [[Coupe de la Ligue]] and totaled six goals in six Coupe de France matches, helping Lyon win their first ever [[Double (association football)|double]].<ref>{{cite news |title=The Goal.com 50: Karim Benzema (14) |url=http://www.goal.com/en-india/news/483/france/2009/01/08/1050859/the-goalcom-50-karim-benzema-14 |work=Goal.com |date=8 January 2009 |accessdate=25 June 2009}}</ref> Some of his more dazzling performances that season included a [[hat-trick]] against Metz on 15 September,<ref>{{cite news |title=Metz v. Lyon Match Report |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2007/2008&code_evt=D1&code_jr_tr=J08&num_ordre=7 |work=Ligue de Football Professionel |date=15 September 2007 |accessdate=25 June 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001070032/http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2007%2F2008&code_evt=D1&num_ordre=7&code_jr_tr=J08 |archivedate=1 October 2007}}</ref> an [[Equaliser (sports)|equalizing goal]] in the 90th minute from a [[Direct free kick|free kick]] against [[Derby du Rh\u00f4ne]] rivals [[AS Saint-\u00c9tienne|Saint-\u00c9tienne]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema coup franc contre Saint-Etienne |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KrbJcPs5kM4 |publisher=YouTube |date=7 February 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2009}}</ref> and a goal against Lens that was nominated for goal of the season by fans.\n\nIn the Champions League, Benzema scored an important double against [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] at [[Ibrox Stadium]] on the last match day of the [[2007\u201308 UEFA Champions League#Group stage|group stage]]. The 3\u20130 victory assured Lyon progression to the knockout rounds.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lyon seal revival as Rangers slump |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/history/season=2008/round=15105/match=301239/index.html |work=Union of European Football Associations |date=12 December 2007 |accessdate=25 June 2009}}</ref> In the [[UEFA Champions League 2007\u201308#Knockout stage|knockout rounds]], Lyon faced [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] and Benzema continued to score, this time it was from outside the [[Penalty area|penalty box]] in the first leg match which ended in a 1\u20131 draw<ref>{{cite news |title=Late Tevez goal gives United important draw against Lyon |url=http://www.inthenews.co.uk/sports/football/sports/football/autocodes/premiership-teams-2006-2007/manchester-united/late-tevez-goal-gives-united-important-draw-against-lyon-$1206147.htm |work=In The News |date=23 February 2008 |accessdate=27 August 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120329121917/http://www.inthenews.co.uk/sports/football/sports/football/autocodes/premiership-teams-2006-2007/manchester-united/late-tevez-goal-gives-united-important-draw-against-lyon-$1206147.htm |archivedate=29 March 2012}}</ref> and United eventually won the tie 1\u20132 on aggregate. Manchester United manager [[Alex Ferguson|Sir Alex Ferguson]] and players praised Benzema for his performance.<ref>{{cite news |title=United like the look of Benzema and begin their homework on Lyon's \u00a345m striker |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2008/feb/22/newsstory.lyon |work=The Guardian |date=28 February 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2009 | location=London | first=Daniel | last=Taylor}}</ref> Lyon club president [[Jean-Michel Aulas]] later accused Ferguson of [[tapping-up]] Benzema.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lyon chairman slams Fergie over Benzema interest |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-521768/Lyon-chairman-slams-Fergie-Benzema-interest.html;jsessionid=4DAD0645D0E04282BE71FE2E4699427B |work=The Guardian |date=28 February 2008 |accessdate=28 July 2009 | location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Ferguson questions 'balance' of Wenger's transfer policy|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/feb/23/sir-alex-ferguson-arsene-wenger-internazionale-manchester-united-arsenal-champions-premier-league |work=The Guardian |date=23 February 2009 |accessdate=28 July 2009 | location=London}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote box | width=30% | align=right | quote= \"It's a compliment to be compared to [[Zinedine Zidane]], but we are different players.\"|source= <small>\u2014Benzema in 2008 after being compared to his French compatriot Zidane.<ref>{{cite news |title=Karim Benzema keeps feet on the Lyon ground |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2291940/Karim-Benzema-keeps-feet-on-the-Lyon-ground.html |work=The Telegraph |date=17 February 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2009 | location=London | first=Ben | last=Lyttleton}}</ref> </small>}}\n\nOn 13 March 2008, Benzema extended his contract with Lyon until 2013 with a one-year extension option.<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema extends Lyon contract until 2013 |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=516330&cc=5901 |work=ESPN |date=13 March 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2009}}</ref> After signing his new contract, Benzema became one of the highest paid footballers in France.<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema becomes one of the highest paid footballers in France |url=http://en.afrik.com/article12840.html |work=Afrik |date=14 March 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100524051221/http://en.afrik.com/article12840.html |archive-date=24 May 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> For his efforts that season, he was named the Ligue 1 [[Troph\u00e9es UNFP du football#Player of the Year|Player of the Year]], selected to the [[Troph\u00e9es UNFP du football#2009|Team of the Year]] and awarded the Troph\u00e9e du Meilleur Buteur for being the league's top scorer.<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema lands Ligue 1 award |url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11800_3555834,00.html |work=Sky Sports |date=12 May 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema meilleur buteur |url=http://www.football365.fr/la-une/article_239022_L1-Benzema-meilleur-buteur.shtml |work=Football365 |date=18 May 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2009}}</ref> He was also shortlisted by French magazine ''[[France Football]]'' for the [[2008 Ballon d'Or]] award,<ref>{{cite news |title=Messi, Ronaldo lead Ballon d'Or short list |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2008/soccer/10/20/ballon.dor/index.html?eref=si_soccer |publisher=Cable News Network |date=20 October 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2009}}</ref> eventually won by [[Cristiano Ronaldo]].\n\n====2008\u201309 season====\nBenzema got off to a good start for the [[2008\u201309 Ligue 1|2008\u201309 season]], scoring twice in Lyon's opening league match against [[Toulouse FC|Toulouse]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Lyon v. Toulouse Match Report |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2008/2009&code_evt=D1&code_jr_tr=J01&num_ordre=5 |work=Ligue de Football Professionel |date=10 August 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090430165321/http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2008%2F2009&code_evt=D1&code_jr_tr=J01&num_ordre=5 |archivedate=30 April 2009 }}</ref> The following three weeks, he scored goals against [[Rh\u00f4ne-Alpes]] rivals [[Grenoble Foot 38|Grenoble]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Lyon v. Grenoble Match Report |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2008/2009&code_evt=D1&code_jr_tr=J03&num_ordre=5 |work=Ligue de Football Professionel |date=23 August 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090425063446/http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2008%2F2009&code_evt=D1&num_ordre=5&code_jr_tr=J03 |archivedate=25 April 2009}}</ref> and Saint-\u00c9tienne<ref>{{cite news |title=Saint-Etienne v. Lyon Match Report |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2008/2009&code_evt=D1&code_jr_tr=J04&num_ordre=9 |work=Ligue de Football Professionel |date=31 August 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090430165113/http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2008%2F2009&code_evt=D1&code_jr_tr=J04&num_ordre=9 |archivedate=30 April 2009}}</ref> and scored a goal against Nice, converting a [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty]] in the dying seconds.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lyon v. Nice Match Report |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2008/2009&code_evt=D1&code_jr_tr=J05&num_ordre=5 |work=Ligue de Football Professionel |date=13 September 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090423060551/http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2008%2F2009&code_evt=D1&num_ordre=5&code_jr_tr=J05 |archivedate=23 April 2009}}</ref> Lyon won all three matches. As a result of his early goals, Lyon club president Jean-Michel Aulas quelled the many transfer rumors surrounding Benzema by placing a \u20ac100&nbsp;million price tag on the striker. He was also nominated alongside [[Franck Rib\u00e9ry]] to be featured on the French cover of the video game ''[[FIFA 09]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.411mania.com/games/news/86471/%5BMulti%5D-FIFA-2009-Cover-Players.htm|title=The players to appear on FIFA 2009 game covers are revealed.|work=411Mania|date=29 September 2008|accessdate=25 June 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081005022615/http://www.411mania.com/games/news/86471/%5BMulti%5D-FIFA-2009-Cover-Players.htm|archivedate=5 October 2008}}</ref>\n[[Image:Karim Benzema 17586.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Benzema during a training session with Lyon]]\nHe scored his seventh goal of the league on 29 October, scoring in the 2\u20130 win over [[FC Sochaux-Montb\u00e9liard|Sochaux]]. Benzema scored again the following weekend in a 2\u20130 win over [[Le Mans FC|Le Mans]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://soccernet-assets.espn.go.com/match?id=252159&league=FRA.1&cc=5901 |title=Lyon 2&nbsp;\u2013 0 Le Mans |work=ESPN |date=2 November 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120324054345/http://soccernet-assets.espn.go.com/match?id=252159&league=FRA.1&cc=5901 |archive-date=24 March 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He was among the top scorers in the [[2008\u201309 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] group stage, scoring five goals,<ref>{{cite news |title=Top scorers |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/statistics/players/typestat=gs/index.html |work=Union of European Football Associations |date=17 June 2009 |accessdate=25 June 2009}}</ref> a double against Steaua Bucure\u0219ti,<ref>{{cite news |title=Lyon prove too strong for valiant Steaua |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/fixturesresults/round=15276/match=302732/report=rp.html|work=Union of European Football Associations |date=21 October 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2009}}</ref> two goals in two matches against [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Lyon fight back denies Fiorentina |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/fixturesresults/round=15276/match=302692/report=rp.html|work=Union of European Football Associations |date=17 September 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema leads Lyon onwards |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/fixturesresults/round=15276/match=302764/report=rp.html|work=Union of European Football Associations |date=25 November 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2009}}</ref> and a goal against the eventual group winners [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] on the final match day.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bayern hold on to edge past Lyon |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/fixturesresults/round=15276/match=302772/report=rp.html|work=Union of European Football Associations |date=10 December 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2009}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[Christmas and holiday season|winter break]], Benzema endured a rough patch going scoreless the first three games before recording his 11th goal of the season against Nice in a 3\u20131 victory.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nice v. Lyon Match Report |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2008/2009&code_evt=D1&code_jr_tr=J23&num_ordre=8 |work=Ligue de Football Professionel |date=8 February 2009 |accessdate=25 June 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090415115050/http://lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2008%2F2009&code_evt=D1&num_ordre=8&code_jr_tr=J23 |archivedate=15 April 2009}}</ref> Two weeks later, he scored his 12th goal against [[AS Nancy|Nancy]] in a 2\u20130 victory.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nancy v. Lyon Match Report |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2008/2009&code_evt=D1&code_jr_tr=J25&num_ordre=6 |work=Ligue de Football Professionel |date=21 February 2009 |accessdate=25 June 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090505022004/http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2008%2F2009&code_evt=D1&code_jr_tr=J25&num_ordre=6 |archivedate=5 May 2009}}</ref> The next nine matches, both Benzema and Lyon's form dwindled losing four matches, drawing three and winning only two with Benzema scoring only two goals in that stretch, both of them against Le Mans in a 3\u20131 victory.<ref>{{cite news |title=Le Mans v. Lyon Match Report |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2008/2009&code_evt=D1&code_jr_tr=J30&num_ordre=4 |work=Ligue de Football Professionel |date=4 April 2009 |accessdate=25 June 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090523230301/http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2008%2F2009&code_evt=D1&code_jr_tr=J30&num_ordre=4 |archivedate=23 May 2009}}</ref> The bad form resulted in Lyon losing their grip on first-place position and eventually falling out of the title race, thus ending their streak of seven consecutive Ligue 1 titles.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lyon's Karim Benzema tips the title Bordeaux's way |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2009/may/19/bordeaux-marseille-lyon-ligue-1|work=The Guardian |date=19 May 2009 |accessdate=27 August 2009 | location=London | first=Ben | last=Lyttleton}}</ref> Benzema was a part of four of those title runs.\n\nDespite losing the title, Benzema got back on track scoring his 15th and 16th goals of the season on 17 May in a 3\u20131 away victory over rivals [[Olympique de Marseille|Marseille]], the first goal being a penalty.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/match?id=252311&cc=5901 |title=Marseille 1&nbsp;\u2013 5 Lyon |work=ESPN |date=17 May 2009 |accessdate=25 June 2009}}</ref> He scored his 17th goal the following weekend against [[Stade Malherbe Caen|Caen]] in a 3\u20131 victory moving him into third place among Ligue 1 top scorers.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lyon v. Caen Match Report |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2008/2009&code_evt=D1&num_ordre=5&code_jr_tr=J37 |work=Ligue de Football Professionel |date=23 May 2009 |accessdate=25 June 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090625130621/http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2008%2F2009&code_evt=D1&code_jr_tr=J37&num_ordre=5 |archivedate=25 June 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Real Madrid===\n====2009\u201310 season====\nOn 1 July 2009, it was announced that Lyon had reached an agreement with Spanish club [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] for the transfer of Benzema. The transfer fee was priced at \u20ac35&nbsp;million with the fee rising to as much as \u20ac41&nbsp;million based on incentives.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/european/5712487/Karim-Benzema-joins-Real-Madrid-after-snubbing-Manchester-United.html|title = Karim Benzema joins Real Madrid after snubbing Manchester United|date = 1 July 2009|accessdate = 12 March 2015|website = The Telegraph|publisher = |last = Burt|first = Jason}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Transfert de Karim Benzema au Real Madrid |url=http://www.olweb.fr/fr/Accueil/100007/Article/50470/Transfert-de-Karim-Benzema-au-Real-Madrid |work=Olympique Lyonnais |date=1 July 2009 |accessdate=1 July 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20090702111827/http://www.olweb.fr/fr/Accueil/100007/Article/50470/Transfert%2Dde%2DKarim%2DBenzema%2Dau%2DReal%2DMadrid |archivedate=2 July 2009}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.espnfc.com/story/658536/forward-karim-benzema-joins-real-madrid-from-lyon|title = Forward Benzema joins Real Madrid from Lyon|date = 1 July 2009|accessdate = 12 March 2015|website = [[ESPN]] FC|publisher = |last = |first =}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://edition.cnn.com/2009/SPORT/football/07/01/lyon.benzema.real.madrid/index.html?eref=rss_latest|title = Lyon accept Real Madrid offer for Benzema|date = 2 July 2009|accessdate = 12 March 2015|website = CNN|publisher = |last = |first =}}</ref> On 9 July, Benzema successfully passed his medical and signed his contract, a six-year deal, later that afternoon.<ref>{{citation |title=Benzema passes medical at Real Madrid|url=http://metro.co.uk/2009/07/09/benzema-passes-medical-at-real-madrid-265812/|work=Metro|date=9 July 2009 |accessdate=12 March 2015}}</ref> He was presented officially as a Real Madrid player later that night at the [[Santiago Bernab\u00e9u Stadium]], similarly to the previous signings of [[Kak\u00e1]] and Cristiano Ronaldo.<ref>{{citation |title=Karim Benzema Thanks Florentino Perez at Official Real Madrid Presentation|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/12/spain/2009/07/09/1373590/karim-benzema-thanks-florentino-perez-at-official-real|work=GOAL.COM|date=8 July 2009 |accessdate=12 March 2015}}</ref> Benzema made his Real Madrid debut on 20 July in the club's opening [[pre-season]] [[Exhibition game|friendly]] against [[Republic of Ireland|Irish]] club [[Shamrock Rovers F.C.|Shamrock Rovers]] in [[Dublin]], appearing as a half-time substitute.<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema Strikes To Edge Real Madrid Past Spirited Shamrock Rovers|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/1783/club-friendlies/2009/07/20/1393903/benzema-strikes-to-edge-real-madrid-past-spirited-shamrock|work=goal.com|date=20 July 2009 |accessdate=11 February 2011}}</ref> He scored the lone goal in the club's 1\u20130 win, scoring in the 87th minute.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ronaldo quiet as Rovers almost hold off Real |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=661981&sec=europe&cc=5901 |work=ESPN |date=20 July 2009 |accessdate=20 July 2009}}</ref> On 24 August, Benzema netted two goals in Real Madrid's 4\u20130 victory over Norwegian club Rosenborg in an annual friendly tournament organized for the [[Trofeo Santiago Bernab\u00e9u|Santiago Bernabeu Trophy]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Madrid cruises past Rosenborg 4\u20130|url=http://www.thehindu.com/sport/football/madrid-cruises-past-rosenborg-40/article8669.ece|work=thehindu.com|date=25 August 2009 |accessdate=11 February 2011}}</ref> The goals brought his total tally in the pre-season with Real Madrid to five, making him the joint top scorer alongside fellow striker [[Ra\u00fal (footballer)|Ra\u00fal]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Led by Benzema, Real Madrid cruises past Rosenborg 4\u20130 in pre-season |url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/canadianpress/article/ALeqM5grIhuXBvcEANFkEL4nY5BDBW1xiQ |work=The Canadian Press |date=24 August 2009 |accessdate=26 August 2009}}</ref>\n\nBenzema made his league debut for Madrid on 29 August 2009 against [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a|Deportivo La Coru\u00f1a]]. He started the match, but was substituted out in the second half as Madrid won 3\u20132.<ref>{{cite news |title=Real Madrid 3\u20132 Deportivo La Coru\u00f1a |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=275652&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=29 August 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> A month later, he scored his first goal for the club in a 5\u20130 victory against newly promoted [[Xerez CD|Xerez]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Ronaldo nets twice in rout |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=275662&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=20 September 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> After missing the mid-week match against [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]], against [[CD Tenerife|Tenerife]] at the weekend, Benzema scored his first double for Madrid in a 3\u20130 home victory.<ref>{{cite news |title=Madrid maintain winning start |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=275847&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=26 September 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> He made his Champions League debut for the club on 30 September in a group stage tie against Marseille.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ronaldo and Kak\u00e1 see off Marseille |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2010/matches/round=2000028/match=2000385/index.html |work=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |date=30 September 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> In the match, Benzema assisted on a Cristiano Ronaldo goal.<ref>{{cite news |title=Red hot Ronaldo fires double |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=283173&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=30 September 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> After failing to score a goal in the month of October, in the team's first match in November against [[Italy|Italian]] club [[A.C. Milan|Milan]] in the Champions League, Benzema scored the opener to give Madrid a 1\u20130 lead. His goal was later cancelled out by a [[Ronaldinho]] penalty.<ref>{{cite news |title=Honours even for Milan and Madrid |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2010/matches/round=2000028/match=2000424/index.html |work=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |date=3 November 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> On 7 November, in the ''[[El Derbi madrile\u00f1o]]'' against [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]], Benzema assisted on Madrid's second goal, scored by [[Marcelo (footballer, born 1988)|Marcelo]]. Madrid won the match 3\u20132.<ref>{{cite news |title=Real edge five-goal thriller |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=275561&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=7 November 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Benzema - Rodriguez.jpg|thumb|left|Benzema playing against Marseille in a 2009 Champions League match.]]\n\nIn late November, Benzema began appearing mainly as a substitute as manager [[Manuel Pellegrini]] preferred [[Gonzalo Higua\u00edn]] in the lead striker role. To coincide with his benching, the striker was also being criticized by the Spanish media for his under-performance and difficulties settling in the country as he had not yet begun learning the [[Spanish language]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Pellegrini insists Benzema is fitting in at Real |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=709949&sec=uefachampionsleague&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=8 December 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema now Real's trump card |first=Andy |last=Mitten |url=http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/blogs/andy-mitten/benzema-now-real-trump-card-466.html |work=[[Yahoo!]] |date=24 March 2011 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> He was even declared the \"new [[Nicolas Anelka|Anelka]]\" by a Spanish newspaper ''[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]'' blogger, referring to former Real Madrid striker Nicolas Anelka who had a tumultuous year at the club before being sold.<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema, el nuevo Anelka... |url=http://www.marca.com/blogs/balondesastre/2009/12/02/benzema-el-nuevo-anelka.html |work=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]] |date=2 December 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2012 | language = Spanish}}</ref> Benzema was defended by his compatriot Zinedine Zidane, who admitted \"after two months, I was also criticized\" and that Benzema was \"a talented player and talented players in Madrid must win\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Zidane, sobre Kak\u00e1 y Benzema: \"A los dos meses tambi\u00e9n yo fui criticado\" |url=http://www.marca.com/2009/12/01/futbol/equipos/real_madrid/1259698642.html |work=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]] |date=1 December 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2012 | language = Spanish}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 December, Benzema appeared as a substitute for [[Rafael van der Vaart]] and scored the third goal in a 6\u20130 romp of [[UD Almer\u00eda|Almer\u00eda]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Ronaldo endures eventful night |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=275739&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=5 December 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> The day after the match against Almer\u00eda, Benzema responded to the criticism by stating, \"I am totally integrated and very happy at Real Madrid,\" and, \"Yes, I have improved my adaptation. I have a new home and I'm learning Spanish to understand myself better with my teammates.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema: \"Estoy totalmente integrado y muy feliz en el Real Madrid\" |url=http://www.marca.com/2009/12/06/futbol/equipos/real_madrid/1260105750.html |work=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]] |date=6 December 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2012 | language = Spanish}}</ref> After nearly a month coming off of the bench, he started alongside Higua\u00edn away to [[Valencia CF|Valencia]] on 12 December and responded by assisting on one of Higua\u00edn's two goals.<ref>{{cite news |title=Garay header secures Real win |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=275588&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=12 December 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> A week later, Benzema returned to the bench. On his 22nd birthday, he scored in a 6\u20130 home win against [[Real Zaragoza]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Madrid power past Zaragoza |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=275650&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=19 December 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Pellegrini 'regala' a Benzema otra suplencia por su cumplea\u00f1os |url=http://www.marca.com/2009/12/19/futbol/equipos/real_madrid/1261239012.html |work=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]] |date=19 December 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2012 | language = Spanish}}</ref> Following an injury to Higua\u00edn in early January 2010, Pellegrini inserted Benzema back into the starting lineup.<ref>{{cite news |first=Philips-Knight |last=Rob |title=Benzema's chance to shine |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/feature?id=725550&sec=europe&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=15 January 2010 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> After failing to score in his first two starts in the absence of Higua\u00edn, against Deportivo La Coru\u00f1a on 30 January, he scored a double in an important 3\u20131 away win.<ref>{{cite news |title=Primera Liga round-up |url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11827_5901962,00.html |work=Sky Sports |date=31 January 2010 |accessdate=31 January 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Match report: Deportivo La Coru\u00f1a 1\u20133 Real Madrid |url=http://www.realmadridzone.com/match-report-deportivo-la-coruna-1-3-real-madrid/ |work=Real Madrid Zone |date=30 January 2010 |accessdate=2 July 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150713112313/http://www.realmadridzone.com/match-report-deportivo-la-coruna-1-3-real-madrid/ |archive-date=13 July 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Following the return of Higua\u00edn, Benzema was relegated back to a substitute's role and finished the campaign by making eight consecutive appearances off the bench. Included in one of those appearances was his final goal of the season against [[Athletic Bilbao]] in a 5\u20131 win.<ref>{{cite news |title=Real take it to the wire |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=275584&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=8 May 2010 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n====2010\u201311 season====\n[[File:Benzema Villarreal.jpg|thumb|Right|Benzema playing in a league match against Villarreal]]\nAhead of the [[2010\u201311 La Liga|2010\u201311 season]], Benzema switched to the number 9 shirt as Real Madrid were under the tutelage of new incoming manager [[Jos\u00e9 Mourinho]]. The striker immediately drew the ire of Mourinho who declared to reporters during a pre-season media session that \"Benzema must understand that he is extremely talented, but that in itself is not enough\", while also stating that \"[Madrid] need a striker who is sparky, not one that is listless\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Mourinho calls on Benzema to wake up |url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20100823/football/mourinho-calls-on-benzema-to-wake-up.323614 |work=Times of Malta |date=23 August 2010|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> Mourinho sentiments were later echoed by incoming France national team coach [[Laurent Blanc]] who acknowledged that Benzema was \"not used to working\".<ref name=\"Mourinho plans to keep Benzema\">{{cite news |title=Mourinho plans to keep Benzema |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=812674&sec=europe&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=8 August 2010 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> Blanc also stated that the striker needed to shed weight in order to fulfill his potential.<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema finally on glory path |url=http://www.namibiansun.com/content/international-sport/benzema-finally-glory-path |work=Namibian Sun |date=3 May 2012 |accessdate=6 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131026194739/http://www.namibiansun.com/content/international-sport/benzema-finally-glory-path |archivedate=26 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nDue to Mourinho preferring Ronaldo and Higua\u00edn as his forwards,<ref name=\"Mourinho plans to keep Benzema\"/> Benzema began the campaign as a substitute coming off the bench in the team's opening league match of the season against [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Real take it to the wire |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=275584&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=29 August 2010 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> Following the September international break, he made his first start in a 1\u20130 win over [[CA Osasuna|Osasuna]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Carvalho rescues Mourinho |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=301878&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=11 September 2010|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> On 21 September, Benzema made a substitute appearance and scored his first goal of the season in a 3\u20130 home win against [[RCD Espanyol|Espanyol]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Madrid cruise to win |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=301950&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=21 September 2010|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> Afterwards, the striker failed to score a domestic goal for nearly two months. The striker did assist on goals in back-to-back weeks against [[H\u00e9rcules CF|H\u00e9rcules]] in the league and Milan in the Champions League.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ronaldo late show seals Real comeback |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=301910&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=30 October 2010|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Last-ditch Le\u00f3n takes Madrid through in Milan|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2011/matches/round=2000118/match=2002870/index.html |work=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |date=3 November 2010 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:La alegr\u00eda del gol, Benzema.jpg|thumb|left|Benzema [[Goal celebration|celebrating a goal]] against Espanyol in La Liga.]]\n\nOn 10 November, Benzema scored his second goal of the campaign against [[Real Murcia]] in the [[2010\u201311 Copa del Rey|2010\u201311 edition]] of the [[Copa del Rey]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Real Madrid 5\u20131 Murcia |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/match?id=308803&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=10 November 2010|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> In late November, Benzema was inserted into the starting eleven following a severe back injury to Higua\u00edn, along with the team's lack of senior strikers. In his first match since being inserted into the starting lineup permanently, he scored his first Champions League goal of the season in a group stage fixture against [[Netherlands|Dutch]] club [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Masterful Madrid take top spot in style|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2011/matches/round=2000118/match=2002893/index.html |work=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |date=3 November 2010 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> In Madrid's final group stage tie against French outfit [[AJ Auxerre|Auxerre]], Benzema scored his first [[hat trick]] for the club in a 4\u20130 win. The first goal he scored was Real Madrid's 300th goal in the Champions League era.<ref>{{cite news |title=Madrid's Benzema leaves Auxerre rooted to the spot|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2011/matches/round=2000118/match=2002901/index.html |work=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |date=8 December 2010 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Real Madrid 4\u20130 Auxerre |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=307816&cc=5739 |work=[[ESPN]]|date=8 December 2010 |accessdate=8 December 2010}}</ref> Two weeks later, Benzema converted another hat trick, this time in an 8\u20130 thrashing of [[Levante UD|Levante]] in the Copa del Rey.<ref>{{cite news |title=Real Madrid 8\u20130 Levante |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/match?id=311145&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=22 December 2010|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> In the team's first fixture of the 2011 calendar year, he assisted on the game-winning goal scored by Ronaldo in a 3\u20132 win over [[Getafe CF|Getafe]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Kaka makes return |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=302036&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=3 January 2011|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> In late January, for the first time in his Real Madrid career, Benzema scored goals in back-to-back matches. On 23 January, he scored the only goal in a 1\u20130 win at home against Mallorca.<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema nets vital winner |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=301942&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=23 January 2011|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> Three days later, Benzema repeated his efforts scoring the only goal in a win over [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]] in the first leg of the team's Copa del Rey semi-final tie.<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema advantage |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/match?id=312248&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=26 January 2011|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> Real Madrid later advanced to its 37th Copa del Rey final in club history after beating Sevilla 2\u20130 in the second leg.<ref>{{cite news |title=Real into final |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=312205&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=2 February 2011|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the arrival of [[Emmanuel Adebayor]] on loan, Benzema went unused in two consecutive league matches in February 2011. He returned to the starting lineup on 19 February and embarked on a run in which he scored ten goals in eight matches. Included in those ten goals were doubles in three straight matches against [[M\u00e1laga CF|M\u00e1laga]], [[Racing de Santander]] and H\u00e9rcules, as well as a goal in the first leg of Madrid's Round of 16 tie against former club Lyon.<ref>{{cite news |title=Pellegrini endures miserable return |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=301919&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=3 March 2011|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema double keeps Real hopes alive |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=302009&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=6 March 2011|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema bags brace |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=302176&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=12 March 2011|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> The strike against his hometown club was the 100th goal of his professional career, and also the first goal for Real Madrid at the Stade de Gerland in six years, though despite the honours associated with netting the goal, Benzema did not celebrate out of respect for his former club.<ref>{{cite news |title=Gomis goal pegs back Madrid|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2011/matches/round=2000119/match=2003757/index.html |work=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |date=22 February 2011 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Benzema dribbles.jpg|thumb|right|Right|Benzema playing in a league match against Almer\u00eda.]]\n\nOn 19 March, he scored the opener in the ''El Derbi madrile\u00f1o'' as Real Madrid went on to win the match 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite news |title=Real take derby spoils |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=301843&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=19 March 2011|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> Despite his form, Benzema appeared in only one of the four highly anticipated matches against ''[[El Cl\u00e1sico]]'' rivals [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]], in which the two clubs met in the league, the [[2011 Copa del Rey Final]] and the Champions League knockout stage. In between those clashes, on 23 April 2011, Benzema scored a goal and assisted on another in a 6\u20133 win over Valencia.<ref>{{cite news |title=Madrid continue impressive form |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=301882&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=23 April 2011|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> On 30 April, he scored a goal in the team's 3\u20132 loss to Real Zaragoza.<ref>{{cite news |title=Zaragoza dent Real title dream |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=302162&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=30 April 2011|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> It was the only match of the campaign that Real Madrid loss, in which Benzema scored. To close out the campaign, Benzema scored another double in an 8\u20131 win over Almer\u00eda.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ronaldo breaks record in rout |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=302157&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=21 May 2011|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> He finished the campaign second on the team behind Ronaldo with 26 goals as Real Madrid captured the Copa del Rey giving Benzema his first honour with the club.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ronaldo's late goal gives Real Madrid win over Barcelona in Copa del Rey |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2011/apr/21/real-madrid-barcelona-copa-del-rey |work=[[Guardian Media Group]] |date=21 April 2011|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> For his performances during the campaign, particularly during the second half, Benzema was praised by Mourinho, club officials [[Florentino P\u00e9rez]] and [[Emilio Butrague\u00f1o]], as well as national team manager Laurent Blanc.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mourinho's gripes bring Benzema back to life |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/european/mourinhos-gripes-bring-benzema-back-to-life-2242769.html |work=[[The Independent]] |date=16 March 2011|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Butragueno: Benzema 'understands' football|url=http://www.espnstar.com/football/primera-liga/news/detail/item599300/Butragueno:-Benzema-%27understands%27-football/|work=[[ESPN]]|date=21 April 2011|accessdate=6 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110918093407/http://www.espnstar.com/football/primera-liga/news/detail/item599300/Butragueno:-Benzema-'understands'-football/|archive-date=18 September 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Blanc compte sur Benzema |url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/equipe-de-france-de-football/2011/06/02/02016-20110602ARTSPO00355-blanc-compte-sur-benzema.php |work=Le Figaro |date=2 June 2011|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n====2011\u201312 season====\nPrior to the start of the [[2011\u201312 La Liga|2011\u201312 season]], Benzema, taking the advice of compatriots Blanc and Zidane,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://aol.sportingnews.com/soccer/story/2011-08-09/france-looks-to-extend-unbeaten-run-faces-chile-in-friendly|title=France looks to extend unbeaten run, faces Chile in friendly |work=[[Sporting News]] |date=9 August 2011|accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/sport/soccer/fat-chance-20110805-1ifju.html|title=Fat chance |work=The Age |date=6 August 2011|accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> ventured to [[Merano]], Italy, to attend a high performance clinic where he underwent treatment to reduce his weight.<ref name=\"benzema_weight\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.goaledor.com/la-liga-news/premier-league-benzema-gives-key-be-better.html|title=Benzema gives the key to be better|work=Goaledor|date=5 August 2011|accessdate=7 May 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141109165912/http://www.goaledor.com/la-liga-news/premier-league-benzema-gives-key-be-better.html|archivedate=9 November 2014}}</ref> The spell at the clinic was ultimately a success after the striker arrived at pre-season {{convert|8|kg|lb}} lighter.<ref name=\"benzema_weight\"/> While at the clinic, Benzema also underwent physical training to build up his [[muscle mass]].<ref name=\"benzema_weight\"/> The striker was impressive in the pre-season scoring eight goals in seven matches.<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema: European preseason top scorer |url=http://www.realmadrid.com/cs/Satellite/en/1330064116769/noticia/Noticia/Benzema:_European_preseason_top_scorer.htm |work=[[Real Madrid C.F.]] |date=9 August 2011 |accessdate=11 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110915101633/http://www.realmadrid.com/cs/Satellite/en/1330064116769/noticia/Noticia/Benzema:_European_preseason_top_scorer.htm |archivedate=15 September 2011}}</ref> His performances during the pre-season resulted in Mourinho naming him the starting lead striker for the new campaign. Mourinho was later credited with Benzema's transformation,<ref>{{cite news |title=Barcelona rise to El Clasico occasion as Lionel Messi outshines Real Madrid's Cristiano Ronaldo |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/la-liga/8948480/Barcelona-rise-to-El-Clasico-occasion-as-Lionel-Messi-outshines-Real-Madrids-Cristiano-Ronaldo.html |work=[[Daily Telegraph]] |date=10 December 2011 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> but denied full responsibility and, instead, gave credit to the striker himself.<ref name=\"mourinho_benzema\">{{cite news |title=Benzema has confidence to impress Mourinho|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContent/6/55/18130/Sports/World/Benzema-has-confidence-to-impress-Mourinho.aspx|work=english.ahram.org.eg |date=10 September 2011 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nBenzema made his 2011\u201312 competitive debut for Madrid in the first leg of the [[2011 Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a]] against Barcelona. In the match, he started and assisted on the opening goal of the match, scored by [[Mesut \u00d6zil]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Barca hold Real in Supercopa |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=330062&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=14 August 2011 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> In the second leg, with Madrid trailing 4\u20133 on aggregate late in the match, Benzema scored the equalizing goal to even the tie at 4\u20134. However, six minutes later, a [[Lionel Messi]] strike gave Barcelona the supercup.<ref>{{cite news |title=Barcelona 3\u20132 Real Madrid |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/match?id=330063&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=17 August 2011 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> Benzema made his league debut for Madrid in the team's 6\u20130 away win over Real Zaragoza.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ronaldo gets Madrid show underway |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=324018&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=28 August 2011 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> In the team's next league match two weeks later against Getafe, Benzema scored a double in a 4\u20132 victory.<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema at the double |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=324006&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=10 September 2011 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> After going scoreless in three consecutive league matches, he scored his third league goal of the campaign against [[Rayo Vallecano]] in a 4\u20132 win.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ronaldo revels in Rayo rout |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=323980&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=24 September 2011 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> In the team's ensuing match against Ajax in the Champions League, Benzema scored Madrid's third goal in a 3\u20130 home win.<ref>{{cite news |title=Masterful Madrid too much for Ajax |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2012/matches/round=2000263/match=2007592/postmatch/report/index.html |work=[[UEFA|Union of European Associations]] |date=27 September 2011 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> He also assisted on the opener, which was scored by Ronaldo.<ref>{{cite news |title=Clinical Real see off Ajax |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=331232&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=27 September 2011 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> In the club's next Champions League match against Lyon, Benzema scored again netting the opener. He also turned provider for the second consecutive match assisting on a goal by [[Sami Khedira]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Real romp past Lyon |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=331241&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=18 October 2011 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> Madrid won the match 4\u20130.<ref>{{cite news |title=Magnificent Madrid put Lyon to the sword |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2012/matches/round=2000263/match=2007607/postmatch/report/index.html |work=[[UEFA|Union of European Associations]] |date=18 October 2011 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote box | width=30% | align=left | quote= \"Benzema deserves full credit for his transformation. He had some help from me, from his teammates and from ''Zizou'', but he deserves the credit.\" |source= <small>\u2014[[Jos\u00e9 Mourinho]], on Benzema's successful progression in 2011.<ref name=\"mourinho_benzema\"/> </small>}}\n\nIn November 2011, Benzema scored five goals; three in the league and two in Europe. In the league, he converted his three goals in wins over Osasuna and Valencia, while he scored his two Champions League goals in a 6\u20132 group stage win over [[Croatia]]n club [[GNK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Ronaldo hits hat-trick |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=323925&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=6 November 2011 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Real pass Los Che test |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=323920&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=19 November 2011 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Perfect Madrid put six past Dinamo |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2012/matches/round=2000263/match=2007639/postmatch/report/index.html |work=[[UEFA|Union of European Associations]] |date=22 November 2011 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> On 10 December 2011, Benzema scored the opener in Madrid's 3\u20131 defeat to Barcelona in the ''El Cl\u00e1sico''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Barca come back to win Clasico |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=323887&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=10 December 2011 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> The goal, scored just 21 seconds into the match, was the fastest goal ever scored in a match between the two rivals.<ref>{{cite news |title=The five-point European review |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/clubfootball/news/newsid=1556169.html |work=[[FIFA|F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association]] |date=12 December 2011 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> Three days after his record-breaking goal, for his performances during the 2011 calendar year, Benzema was named the ''France Football'' [[France Football#French Player of the Year|French Player of the Year]], beating out Barcelona defender [[Eric Abidal]] and Lyon goalkeeper [[Hugo Lloris]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema \u00e9lu Fran\u00e7ais de l'ann\u00e9e |url=http://www.tf1.fr/telefoot/news-football/benzema-elu-francais-de-l-annee-6873222.html |work=[[TF1]] |date=13 December 2011 |accessdate=7 May 2012 |language=French |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120110143227/http://www.tf1.fr/telefoot/news-football/benzema-elu-francais-de-l-annee-6873222.html |archive-date=10 January 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He became only the second French player based in Spain to win the award, and also the second Real Madrid player to capture it. Zidane was the first to achieve both honorable mentions. Benzema expressed gratitude at winning the award, stating, \"It is a pleasure to win an individual trophy. When I see the previous winners&nbsp;\u2013 Zidane, [[Thierry Henry|Henry]] and other major players&nbsp;\u2013 it makes me proud to join them on the list.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema named France player of the year |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story/_/id/996025/real-madrid%27s-karim-benzema-gets-france-player-of-the-year-award?cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=13 December 2011 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> In the team's next match after winning the award, against Sevilla, Benzema assisted on two goals in a 6\u20132 triumph.<ref>{{cite news |title=Real rout Sevilla |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=323882&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=17 December 2011 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:KarimBenzema.jpg|thumb|180px|upright|Right|Benzema training ahead of a Champions League match in 2012.]]\n\nBenzema opened the 2012 portion of the campaign in positive form. He scored goals against [[Granada CF|Granada]] and M\u00e1laga.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rampant Real extend lead |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=327694&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=7 January 2012 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> Benzema scored against the latter club in the Copa del Rey in each leg of the Round of 16.<ref>{{cite news |title=Real Madrid 3\u20132 M\u00e1laga |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/match?id=335279&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=3 January 2012 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=M\u00e1laga 0\u20131 Real Madrid |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/match?id=334952&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=10 January 2012 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> The 4\u20132 aggregate win advanced Real Madrid to the quarter-finals where the club faced Barcelona. After failing to score in the first leg, which ended 2\u20131 in favour of ''Bar\u00e7a'',<ref>{{cite news |title=Barca fight back at the Bernabeu |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=335877&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=18 January 2012 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> in the second leg on 25 January 2012, Benzema scored his third goal of the season against the ''Blaugrana'', but Madrid failed to win the tie losing 4\u20133 on aggregate.<ref>{{cite news |title=Barca hold on to eliminate holders Real |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=335881&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=25 January 2012 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> On 12 February, Benzema scored his first league goal in over a month against Levante.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ronaldo inspires rampant Real |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=323827&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=12 February 2012 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> A week later, he scored a double in a 4\u20130 shutout of Racing Santander.<ref>{{cite news |title=Real Madrid rout Racing |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=323818&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=18 February 2012 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> On 24 March, Benzema scored two goals in a league win over Real Sociedad.<ref>{{cite news |title=Real return to winning ways |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=323765&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=24 March 2012 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> The two goals made him the top French scorer in La Liga history surpassing Zidane.<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema becomes top scoring Frenchman in La Liga |url=http://www.realmadrid.com/cs/Satellite/en/03_Marzo_Actualidad_11-12/1330092135712/noticia/Noticia/Benzema_joins_Zidane_as_top_scoring_Frenchman_in_La_Liga.htm |work=[[Real Madrid C.F.]] |date=19 March 2012 |accessdate=7 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120422143110/http://www.realmadrid.com/cs/Satellite/en/03_Marzo_Actualidad_11-12/1330092135712/noticia/Noticia/Benzema_joins_Zidane_as_top_scoring_Frenchman_in_La_Liga.htm |archivedate=22 April 2012}}</ref> Three days later, Benzema scored another double in a 3\u20130 first leg away win over [[Cyprus|Cypriot]] club [[APOEL FC|APOEL]] in the Champions League quarter-finals.<ref>{{cite news |title=Kak\u00e1 inspires Madrid to victory at APOEL |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2012/matches/round=2000265/match=2007681/postmatch/report/index.html |work=[[UEFA|Union of European Associations]] |date=27 March 2012 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> On 29 April, Benzema put in a masterpiece performance scoring two goals and assisting on another in a 3\u20130 win over Sevilla. The double was his seventh of the season and allowed Madrid to close in on its first ''Primera Division'' title in four years.<ref>{{cite news |title=Title within Real's reach |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=323712&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=24 March 2012 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> ''Los Blancos'' captured their 32nd league title the following week cruising to a 3\u20130 win over Athletic Bilbao.<ref>{{cite news |title=Real Madrid wins La Liga title |url=http://espn.go.com/sports/soccer/story/_/id/7883524/real-madrid-wraps-32nd-spanish-league-title |work=[[ESPN]] |date=2 May 2012 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> Benzema appeared as a second-half substitute in the match.<ref>{{cite news |title=Real win title in style |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=323856&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=2 May 2012 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n====2012\u201313 season====\nOn the first matchday of the UEFA Champions League, Benzema scored an equalizer against [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in 3\u20132 win at Santiago Bernab\u00e9u. On 4 October 2012, Benzema scored a bicycle kick goal off a cross by Kak\u00e1 in a 4\u20131 win against Ajax in [[Amsterdam]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/football/top-stories/Ronaldo-at-the-treble-as-Real-Madrid-sink-Ajax/articleshow/16662259.cms|title=Ronaldo at the treble as Real Madrid sink Ajax|publisher=The Times of India|accessdate=4 October 2012}}</ref> On 18 December 2012, one day before his 25th birthday, his fine form saw him earn the award for best French footballer of 2012, for the second year running.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.football-espana.net/26941/benzema-france%E2%80%99s-player-2012|title=Benzema, France's Player of 2012|publisher=football-espana.net|accessdate=18 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 March 2013, Benzema opened the scoring against Barcelona in the league game at the Santiago Bernab\u00e9u. Real went on to win the game 2\u20131, the second time they beat Barcelona in a week. On 30 April 2013, Benzema scored one goal and assisted to [[Sergio Ramos]] against Dortmund.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://espnfc.com/en/report/348273/report.html?soccernet=true&cc=null|title=Ramos heads late winner|publisher=ESPN FC|accessdate=26 March 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130316113828/http://espnfc.com/en/report/348273/report.html?soccernet=true&cc=null|archivedate=16 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n====2013\u201314 season====\nBenzema started new season by scoring in a 2\u20131 win over Real Betis at the Santiago Bernab\u00e9u.<ref>{{cite web|title=Real Madrid vs. Real Betis \u2013 18 August 2013 \u2013 Soccerway |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2013/08/18/spain/primera-division/real-madrid-club-de-futbol/real-betis/1517629/ |work=Soccerway.com |date=18 August 2013}}</ref> He scored again one week later in a 1\u20130 away over Granada, assisted by Cristiano Ronaldo.<ref>{{cite web|title=Granada vs. Real Madrid \u2013 26 August 2013 \u2013 Soccerway |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2013/08/26/spain/primera-division/granada-club-de-futbol/real-madrid-club-de-futbol/1517648/ |work=Soccerway.com |date=26 August 2013}}</ref> After four matches without scoring (two with Real Madrid and two with France), he returned to goal-scoring form by netting twice in a 6\u20131 away win over [[Galatasaray S.K. (football)|Galatasaray]] in [[2013\u201314 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Galatasay vs. Real Madrid \u2013 17 September 2013 \u2013 Soccerway |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2013/09/17/europe/uefa-champions-league/galatasaray-sk/real-madrid-club-de-futbol/1584499/ |work=Soccerway.com |date=17 September 2013}}</ref> On 18 January 2014, he scored his 100th goal for Madrid in a 5\u20130 victory at [[Real Betis]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25717692 |title=Real Betis 0\u20135 Real Madrid |publisher=BBC Sport |date=18 January 2014 |accessdate=1 September 2014}}</ref> On 23 March, Benzema scored two goals against fierce rivals Barcelona in ''El Cl\u00e1sico'' at the Bernab\u00e9u from two crosses by [[\u00c1ngel Di Mar\u00eda]], taking his goal tally in La Liga to 17 goals, though Barcelona won the match 4\u20133.<ref>{{cite web|title=Barca tops Real Madrid in Clasico thriller |url=http://www.foxnews.com/sports/2014/03/23/barca-tops-real-madrid-in-clasico-thriller/ |work=Fox News |date=23 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nBenzema was part of Real Madrid's starting eleven in the [[2014 Copa del Rey Final]] on 16 April at the [[Mestalla Stadium]], and assisted Di Mar\u00eda's opening goal before [[Gareth Bale]] hit the winner for Madrid in a 2\u20131 victory.<ref>{{cite web|title=Real Madrid's Gareth Bale gallops past Barcelona to land Copa del Rey |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/apr/16/barcelona-real-madrid-copa-del-rey-match-report-gareth-bale/ |work=The Guardian (London) |date=16 April 2014}}</ref> One week later, Benzema scored the only goal of the game to win the first leg of a Champions League semi-final against Bayern Munich.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ripley|first=Dan|title=Karim Benzema pounces to give hosts semi-final advantage in Champions League|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2610386/Real-Madrid-vs-Bayern-Munich-live-Champions-League.html|accessdate=23 April 2014|newspaper=[[Daily Mail]]|date=23 April 2014}}</ref> The club went on to win the [[2014 UEFA Champions League Final|final]] in May. Real Madrid's attacking trio of Bale, Benzema and Cristiano, dubbed \"BBC\", finished the season with 97 goals.<ref>{{cite news|title=200 goals for the BBC|url=http://www.realmadrid.com/en/news/2015/09/200-goals-by-the-bbc|publisher=RealMadrid.com.|date=24 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n====2014\u201315 season====\n[[File:Karim Benzema vs. FC Schalke 04 (16647992937).jpg|thumb|right|190px|Benzema during the 2014\u201315 season]]\nOn 6 August 2014, Real Madrid announced that Benzema had signed a new five-year deal that will keep him at the club until 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realmadrid.com/en/news/2014/08/official-statement-benzema|title=Official statement: Benzema|work=realmadrid.com|date=6 August 2014}}</ref> On 12 August 2014, Benzema played the whole 90 minutes in Real Madrid's 2\u20130 win against Sevilla in [[Cardiff]] to claim the [[2014 UEFA Super Cup|UEFA Super Cup]].\n\nOn 16 September 2014, Benzema scored Real Madrid's 1,000th goal in [[UEFA competitions|European competition]] after netting a goal in a 5\u20131 victory over [[FC Basel]] in the first match of the [[2014\u201315 UEFA Champions League group stage|Champions League group stage]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Real Madrid 5 \u2013 1 FC Basel|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/29210808|accessdate=18 September 2014|publisher=BBC Sport|date=16 September 2014}}</ref> He scored the winning goal in Real Madrid's 2\u20131 away victory against [[PFC Ludogorets Razgrad|Ludogorets Razgrad]] in the Champions League after coming on as a second-half substitute.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ludogorets 1\u20132 Real Madrid: Karim Benzema delivers winner from the bench as Cristiano Ronaldo and Co survive scare in Sofia|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2777006/Ludogorets-1-2-Real-Madrid-match-report-Karim-Benzema-delivers-winner-bench.html|newspaper=[[Daily Mail]]|date=1 October 2014}}</ref> The next weekend, he scored a brace in the 5\u20130 victory against Athletic Bilbao in La Liga.<ref>{{cite news|title=Real Madrid 5\u20130 Athletic Bilbao: Cristiano Ronaldo hits yet another hat-trick and Karim Benzema bags a brace in BBC production also starring Gareth Bale|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2781553/Real-Madrid-5-0-Athletic-Bilbao-Cristiano-Ronaldo-hits-hat-trick.html|newspaper=[[Daily Mail]]|date=5 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nBenzema was chosen as [[La Liga Player of the Month]] for October 2014, with his manager [[Carlo Ancelotti]] winning [[La Liga Manager of the Month|the equivalent award]]. He scored three of Real Madrid's 13 goals of the month, in which they won three matches and only conceded just one goal.<ref>{{cite news|title=Benzema nets Player of the Month gong|url=http://www.marca.com/en/2014/11/14/en/football/real_madrid/1415969938.html|accessdate=17 November 2014|work=Marca|date=14 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n====2015\u201316 season====\nBenzema scored a hat trick in an 8\u20130 thrashing against [[Malm\u00f6 FF]] on 8 December 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2016/matches/round=2000634/match=2015746/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Ronaldo rampant as Madrid put eight past Malm\u00f6|publisher=[[UEFA]]|date=8 December 2015}}</ref> On 20 December 2015, he scored another hat trick in a 10\u20132 victory over Rayo Vallecano.<ref>{{cite web|title=Real Madrid 10\u20132 Rayo Vallecano|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/35141793|publisher=bbc.com|accessdate=20 December 2015|date=20 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe was a regular starter when the team won the [[2015\u201316 UEFA Champions League]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2016/matches/round=2000638/match=2015789/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Spot-on Real Madrid defeat Atl\u00e9tico in final again|date=28 May 2016|work=uefa.com}}</ref>\n\n====2016\u201317 season====\n[[File:Shahter-Reak M 2015 (15).jpg|thumb|left|180px|Benzema with [[Real Madrid]] in 2015]]\nIn December 2016, Benzema was called up in Real Madrid's [[2016 FIFA Club World Cup squads|squad]] for [[2016 FIFA Club World Cup]] in Japan.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2431480.html|title=Real Madrid prepare for FIFA Club World Cup|publisher=UEFA.com|date=14 December 2016|accessdate=19 December 2016}}</ref> In the semi-final match against [[Club Am\u00e9rica|Am\u00e9rica]] on 15 December, Benzema scored in the last moments of the first half, helping the team to progress in the final by winning 2\u20130.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/match/am%C3%A9rica-vs-real-madrid/2357632/report|title=Club America 0\u20132 Real Madrid: Benzema and Ronaldo fire Blancos to final|publisher=Goal.com|author=Joe Wright|date=15 December 2016|accessdate=19 December 2016}}</ref> In the [[2016 FIFA Club World Cup Final|final]] three days later against [[Kashima Antlers]], Benzema opened the score in the 9th minute, and also assisted Ronaldo's second goal, as Real Madrid won 4\u20132 in extra time after the regular time finished 2\u20132 to claim their second title.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espnfc.com/club/real-madrid/86/blog/post/3022686/cristiano-ronaldo-goals-and-karim-benzema-class-decisive-as-real-madrid-win-club-world-cup|title=Ronaldo's goals, Benzema's class decisive as Real Madrid win Club World Cup|publisher=ESPN FC|author=Rob Train|date=18 December 2016|accessdate=19 December 2016}}</ref> It was Benzema's tenth title with Real Madrid, and finished the competition as joint-second topscorer with two goals in two matches.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.fifa.com/clubworldcup/statistics/players/goal-scored.html|title=FIFA Club World Cup Japan 2016 \u2013 Statistics \u2013 Players \u2013 Top goals|publisher=FIFA.com|date=18 December 2016|accessdate=19 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 February 2017, in the first leg of [[2016\u201317 UEFA Champions League]] [[2016\u201317 UEFA Champions League knockout phase|round of 16]] against [[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]], Benzema scored Real Madrid's first goal in an eventual 3\u20131 home win, which was his 51st goal in this competition, overtaking [[Thierry Henry]] on the list of [[European Cup and UEFA Champions League records and statistics#All-time top scorers|all-time Champions League top scorers]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/8/main/2017/02/15/32720392/benzema-passes-henry-on-champions-league-top-scorers-list|title=Benzema passes Henry on Champions League top scorers list|publisher=Goal.com|date=15 February 2017|accessdate=16 February 2017}}</ref> It was his first goal in six matches and for this performance he was voted Man of the Match.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/sports/football/karim-benzema-ends-drought-with-a-record-breaking-goal-4527687/|title=Karim Benzema ends drought with a record breaking goal|publisher=The Indian Express|date=16 February 2017|accessdate=16 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe was a regular starter, and scored the last goal of the season which gave him eleven for the campaign, when Madrid won the [[2016\u201317 La Liga]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laliga.es/noticias/real-madrid-campeon-de-laliga-santander-2016-17|title=El Real Madrid, campe\u00f3n de LaLiga Santander 2016/17|date=21 May 2017|work=laliga.es}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/39926301|title=Real Madrid win La Liga title with victory at Malaga|date=21 May 2017|work=bbc.com}}</ref> and the [[2016\u201317 UEFA Champions League]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2017/matches/round=2000787/match=2019641/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Majestic Real Madrid win Champions League in Cardiff|date=3 June 2017|work=uefa.com}}</ref>\n\n====2017\u201318 season====\nOn 20 September 2017, Benzema signed a contract extension that will keep him at the club until 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realmadrid.com/en/news/2017/09/ceremony-to-mark-benzemas-contract-renewal|title=Ceremony to mark Benzema's contract renewal|publisher=realmadrid.com|date=20 September 2017|accessdate=20 September 2017}}</ref> Later on 6 March of the following year, Benzema made his 100th UEFA Champions League appearance by playing in the 2\u20131 win at [[Parc des Princes]] against [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]] in the second leg of [[2017\u201318 UEFA Champions League#Round of 16|2017\u201318 UEFA Champions League round of 16]] as Real Madrid progressed to the next round 5\u20132 on aggregate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marca.com/en/football/real-madrid/2018/03/06/5a9dd0b8468aeb466f8b463c.html|title=Benzema is set for his 100th Champions League appearance|publisher=Marca|author1=Pablo Polo|author2=Patricia Terroba|date=6 March 2018|accessdate=7 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/43291900|title=Paris St-Germain 1\u20132 Real Madrid (2\u20135 on aggregate)|publisher=BBC Sport|author=Michael Emons|date=6 March 2018|accessdate=7 March 2018}}</ref> Benzema played his 400th match in all competitions for Real Madrid on 31 March in the 3\u20130 win at [[UD Las Palmas|Las Palmas]], [[Captain (association football)|captaining]] the team and netting the second goal with a penalty.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.as.com/en/2018/03/30/football/1522408901_747803.html|title=Karim Benzema's 400th game overshadowed by goal drought|publisher=AS|author=Manu de Juan|date=31 March 2018|accessdate=31 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 May 2018, Benzema scored the first goal of the match in [[2018 UEFA Champions League Final]] by intercepting [[Loris Karius]]'s throw in a 3\u20131 victory over [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], when Madrid won their third consecutive and 13th overall Champions League title.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2018/matches/round=2000885/match=2021711/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Madrid beat Liverpool to complete hat-trick|date=26 May 2018|work=uefa.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dreamteamfc.com/c/news-gossip/400597/liverpool-real-madrid-champions-league-final-loris-karius-mistake-karim-benzema-goal|title=Shocker Why was Karim Benzema\u2019s goal allowed to stand?|publisher=Dream Team FC|accessdate=27 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2018\u201319 season====\nOn 7 November 2018, Benzema scored a brace in the 5\u20130 win at [[FC Viktoria Plze\u0148|Viktoria Plze\u0148]] in the [[2018\u201319 UEFA Champions League group stage|UEFA Champions League group stage]], reaching the 200th goal milestone with the club.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/benzema-scores-200th-real-madrid-goal-with-viktoria-plzen/1ps8h47w7bqs71n1c9t0li5d16|title=Benzema scores 200th Real Madrid goal with Viktoria Plzen strike|publisher=Goal.com|date=7 November 2018|accessdate=25 January 2019}}</ref> He became only the seventh Real Madrid player to achieve the feat.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.as.com/en/2018/11/07/football/1541628212_557267.html|title=Benzema reaches 200 Real Madrid goals|publisher=AS.com|date=7 November 2018|accessdate=25 January 2019}}</ref> He totaled three goals in six matches, all of them against Viktoria Plze\u0148, helping Real Madrid topping [[2018\u201319 UEFA Champions League#Group G|Group G]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2019/standings/round=2000980/index.html#grp-2006097|title=Group G|publisher=UEFA.com|accessdate=25 January 2019}}</ref> Later on 13 February of the following year, in the first leg of the competition's [[2018\u201319 UEFA Champions League knockout phase|round of 16]], Benzema scored the opener of a 2\u20131 away win over [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en/match/ajax-v-real-madrid/7rum3el4y3tkevzz59s9dapuy|title=Ajax 1 Real Madrid 2: Asensio strikes late after VAR controversy|publisher=Goal.com|author=Joe Wright|date=13 February 2019|accessdate=25 January 2019}}</ref> reaching 60 Champions League goals, becoming only the fourth player to do so.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/benzema-reaches-champions-league-milestone-as-real-madrid/17cgv0b8ve0as1oix8ifju41uo|title=Benzema reaches Champions League milestone as Real Madrid squeeze past Ajax|publisher=Goal.com|date=13 February 2019|accessdate=25 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n====2019\u201320 season====\nBenzema scored Real Madrid's first competitive goal of the [[2019\u201320 Real Madrid CF season|2019\u201320 season]] on 17 August in the 3\u20131 away win over Celta Vigo in the opening [[La Liga]] match.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/celta-vigo-vs-r-madrid/415636|title=Celta Vigo 1-3 Real Madrid: Gareth Bale inspires Zinedine Zidane's side to victory|publisher=Sky Sports|date=19 August 2019|accessdate=9 November 2019}}</ref> Later, on 6 November, he scored a brace in Real Madrid's 6\u20130 crushing of [[Galatasaray S.K. (football)|Galatasaray]], achieving two new milestones: he become the second player after [[Lionel Messi]] to score in 15 consecutive Champions League seasons and also the third Real Madrid player to score 50 goals in the competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://talksport.com/football/626498/real-madrid-karim-benzema-lionel-messi-champions-league/|title=GOAL GETTER Real Madrid ace Karim Benzema equals incredible Lionel Messi record of scoring in 15 consecutive Champions League seasons|publisher=talkSport|author=Daniel Sandford|date=7 November 2019|accessdate=9 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/real-madrid/cronica/2019/11/06/5dc3455f22601d75588b45ad.html|title=Rodrygo takes flight for Real Madrid|publisher=Marca|author=Arch Bell|date=6 November 2019|accessdate=9 November 2019}}</ref> His performances were praised by manager [[Zinedine Zidane]], who called him a legend and also compared him with Cristiano Ronaldo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en-ie/news/benzema-is-like-ronaldo-for-real-madrid-zidane-hails-french/1a9jyhxgqlsh19f3h78lnhm5m|title=\u2018Benzema is like Ronaldo for Real Madrid\u2019 \u2013 Zidane hails French forward after 50th Champions League goal|publisher=Goal.com|author=Chris Burton|date=7 November 2019|accessdate=9 November 2019}}</ref> Three days later, in the next league match, he scored a first-half brace in a 4\u20130 win at [[SD Eibar|Eibar]], overtaking [[Ferenc Pusk\u00e1s]] as the club's 6th all-time goalscorer in La Liga with 157 goals from 323 appearances.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxsportsasia.com/football/la-liga/1196919/karim-benzema-passes-ferenc-puskas-on-all-time-real-madrid-laliga-list/|title=Karim Benzema passes Ferenc Puskas on all-time Real Madrid LaLiga list|publisher=Fox Sports Asia|date=9 November 2019|accessdate=9 November 2019}}</ref> \n\nIn February 2020, Benzema extended his contract with Real Madrid until 2022.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://en.as.com/en/2020/02/26/football/1582745588_563887.html |title=Benzema renews with Real Madrid to 2022 |publisher=AS |date=26 February 2020 |accessdate=3 March 2020 }}</ref> On 1 March, he made his 500th appearance for Real Madrid in a 2\u20130 home win over Barcelona in El Cl\u00e1sico, becoming the fourteenth player in the club's history to achieve this milestone.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://en.as.com/en/2020/03/01/football/1583082236_322148.html |title=Real Madrid: Karim Benzema reaches 500 game milestone |publisher=AS |date=1 March 2020 |accessdate=3 March 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fcbarcelona.com/en/news/1632750/real-madrid-2-0-fc-barcelona-beaten-at-the-bernabeu |title=Real Madrid 2-0 FC Barcelona: Beaten at the Bernab\u00e9u |publisher=FC Barcelona |last1=Roberts |first1=Mike |date=1 March 2020 |accessdate=3 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n===Youth===\nBenzema is a former [[France national youth football team|France youth international]] having earned caps at all levels for which he was eligible, excluding the [[France national under-16 football team|under-16 team]]. He is a member of the group, commonly known in France as the ''G\u00e9n\u00e9ration 1987'', a youth class that produced current internationals [[Hatem Ben Arfa]], [[J\u00e9r\u00e9my M\u00e9nez]] and [[Samir Nasri]], alongside himself.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.football.fr/footballfr/cmc/cm-2010/201019/generation-1987-le-disque-raye_85838.html |title=G\u00e9n\u00e9ration 1987, le disque ray\u00e9 |date=13 May 2010 |accessdate=6 May 2012 |publisher=Football.fr |language=French |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120803182525/http://www.football.fr/footballfr/cmc/cm-2010/201019/generation-1987-le-disque-raye_85838.html |archivedate=3 August 2012}}</ref> Benzema was the last of the four to make his youth international debut under coach [[Philippe Bergeroo]] and officially joined the team ahead of the [[2004 UEFA European Under-17 Championship]] that was played on home soil. In the competition, he appeared in two matches. On his tournament debut, Benzema scored the opening goal in a 3\u20131 win over [[Northern Ireland national under-17 football team|Northern Ireland]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under17/history/season=2004/round=1658/match=75060/index.html |title=France lifted by late goals |date=9 May 2004 |accessdate=6 May 2012 |publisher=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100831172349/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under17/history/season%3D2004/round%3D1658/match%3D75060/index.html |archivedate=31 August 2010 }}</ref> His lone other appearance in the competition was in a 1\u20130 group stage win over [[Spain national under-17 football team|Spain]] as France went on to win the tournament defeated the same team in the final.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under17/history/season=2004/round=1658/match=75062/index.html |title=Spain suffer Mario setback |date=6 May 2004 |accessdate=6 May 2012 |publisher=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131115234030/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under17/history/season=2004/round=1658/match=75062/index.html |archivedate=15 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under17/history/season=2004/round=1661/match=75439/index.html |title=Ch\u00e2teauroux celebrates French win |date=15 May 2004 |accessdate=6 May 2012 |publisher=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131116000441/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under17/history/season%3D2004/round%3D1661/match%3D75439/index.html |archivedate=16 November 2013 }}</ref>\n\nBenzema was a regular starter in the team at [[France national under-18 football team|under-18]] level. He made his debut with the team at a local tournament in the [[Czech Republic]]. Benzema scored his first goal at under-18 level in the competition against [[Poland national under-18 football team|Poland]] in the team's final group stage match.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m19ans/262974.shtml | title = La France bat la Pologne et acc\u00e8de \u00e0 la finale (1\u20130) |date= 27 August 2004 | accessdate =6 May 2012 | publisher=[[French Football Federation]] | language = French}}</ref> In the final against [[Czech Republic national under-18 football team|the hosts]], he scored the opening goal in a 2\u20130 win as France were declared champions of the competition.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m18ans/196188.shtml | title = La France victorieuse en R\u00e9publique Tch\u00e8que (2\u20130) |date= 28 August 2004 | accessdate =6 May 2012 | publisher=[[French Football Federation]] | language = French}}</ref> On 30 September 2004, Benzema was one of three goalscorers in France's 3\u20130 away win over Norway.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m18ans/200924.shtml | title = La France bat la Norv\u00e8ge 3\u20130 |date= 30 September 2004 | accessdate =6 May 2012 | publisher=[[French Football Federation]] | language = French}}</ref> In the team's next match against Russia, he scored a double in a 3\u20131 victory.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m18ans/205004.shtml | title = La France remporte la premi\u00e8re manche (3\u20131) face \u00e0 la Russie |date= 26 October 2004 | accessdate =6 May 2012 | publisher=[[French Football Federation]] | language = French}}</ref> Due to France winning the 2004 U17 European title, the under-18 team was allowed participation in the [[2005 UEFA\u2013CAF Meridian Cup|2005 Meridian Cup]]. Benzema was called up to the team for the competition and played in all four matches, scoring a tournament-high five goals as France were crowned champions of the tournament.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/meridian/news/kind=1/newsid=798075.html |title=2005: Europe extend Meridian domination |date=1 January 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2012 |publisher=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100721123909/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/meridian/news/kind=1/newsid=798075.html |archivedate=21 July 2010}}</ref> He opened the tournament by scoring two goals in a 7\u20130 victory over [[Cameroon national under-17 football team|Cameroon]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m18ans/220492.shtml | title = La France s'impose face au Cameroun (7\u20130) |date= 4 February 2005 | accessdate =6 May 2012 | publisher=[[French Football Federation]] | language = French}}</ref> After going scoreless in the team's next match against [[Sierra Leone national under-17 football team|Sierra Leone]], Benzema responded by scoring a goal in a shutout victory over [[Nigeria national under-17 football team|Nigeria]] and netting another double in a 4\u20131 win against [[Egypt national under-17 football team|Egypt]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m18ans/220996.shtml | title = La France bat le Nigeria (2\u20130) |date= 8 February 2005 | accessdate =6 May 2012 | publisher=[[French Football Federation]] | language = French}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m18ans/221744.shtml | title = La France domine l'Egypte (4\u20131) |date= 11 February 2005 | accessdate =6 May 2012 | publisher=[[French Football Federation]] | language = French}}</ref> On 19 May 2005, in the team's final match of the season against [[Slovakia national under-18 football team|Slovakia]], Benzema scored all four goals in a 4\u20131 victory.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m18ans/239081.shtml | title = La France dominatrice face \u00e0 la Slovaquie (4\u20131) |date= 19 May 2005 | accessdate =6 May 2012 | publisher=[[French Football Federation]] | language = French}}</ref> He finished the under-18 campaign with 18 appearances and a team-high 14 goals and was, subsequently, praised by Bergeroo who, following the campaign, declared that Benzema was \"quite efficient\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m18ans/239226.shtml | title = Philippe Bergeroo: \"Un groupe toujours aussi motiv\u00e9\" |date= 20 May 2005 | accessdate =6 May 2012 | publisher=[[French Football Federation]] | language = French}}</ref>\n\nThe foursome of Benzema, Ben Arfa, M\u00e9nez and Nasri returned to international play together for [[France national under-19 football team|under-19]] duty. The four were joined by [[Issiar Dia]], [[Blaise Matuidi]] and [[Serge Gakp\u00e9]] with the objective of winning the [[2006 UEFA European Under-19 Championship]]. The team opened the campaign with two friendly matches against [[Norway national under-19 football team|Norway]]. Over the course of the two matches, Benzema scored one goal, which came in the first match, a 4\u20130 win.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m19ans/262974.shtml | title = Premi\u00e8re manche r\u00e9ussie face \u00e0 la Norv\u00e8ge (4\u20130) |date= 5 October 2005 | accessdate =6 May 2012 | publisher=[[French Football Federation]] | language = French}}</ref> In the first round of qualification for the UEFA-sanctioned tournament, he scored his only goal in the final group match against [[Austria national under-19 football team|Austria]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m19ans/264062.shtml | title = Troisi\u00e8me succ\u00e8s, face \u00e0 l'Autriche (2\u20130) |date= 28 October 2005 | accessdate =6 May 2012 | publisher=[[French Football Federation]] | language = French}}</ref> France won the match 2\u20130, which resulted in the team progressing to the Elite Round.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under19/history/season=2006/round=2152/match=80906/index.html |title=Austria 0\u20132 France |date=28 October 2005 |accessdate=6 May 2012 |publisher=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131115234926/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under19/history/season%3D2006/round%3D2152/match%3D80906/index.html |archivedate=15 November 2013 }}</ref> In the ensuing round, France were placed in a relatively easy group alongside [[Scotland national under-19 football team|Scotland]], [[Bulgaria national under-19 football team|Bulgaria]], and [[Belarus national under-19 football team|Belarus]]. In the opening group game against Bulgaria, Benzema scored a double converting a penalty and scoring in play as France won 4\u20130.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under19/history/season=2006/round=2225/match=82137/index.html |title=Bulgaria feel Les Bleus power |date=20 May 2006 |accessdate=6 May 2012 |publisher=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |work= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131116004707/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under19/history/season=2006/round=2225/match=82137/index.html |archive-date=16 November 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Both of his goals were scored within a minute of each other.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m19ans/304525.shtml | title = La France bat la Bulgarie (4\u20130) |date= 16 May 2006 | accessdate =6 May 2012 | publisher=[[French Football Federation]] | language = French}}</ref> After surprisingly drawing 0\u20130 with Belarus, France faced Scotland in the final group stage match. Benzema opened the scoring in the 11th minute, but his goal was cancelled out by [[Steven Fletcher (footballer)|Steven Fletcher]] in the second half.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m19ans/305419.shtml | title = La France tenue en \u00e9chec (1\u20131) |date= 20 May 2006 | accessdate =6 May 2012 | publisher=[[French Football Federation]] | language = French}}</ref> The match ultimately finished 1\u20131 and, despite finishing the round undefeated, France were eliminated after being beaten on points by the ''Scots''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under19/history/season=2006/round=2225/match=82141/index.html |title=Fletcher sends Scotland soaring |date=20 May 2006 |accessdate=6 May 2012 |publisher=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |work= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131116003742/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under19/history/season=2006/round=2225/match=82141/index.html |archive-date=16 November 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nBenzema made his [[France national under-21 football team|under-21]] debut for ''Les Espoirs'' under coach [[Ren\u00e9 Girard (footballer)|Ren\u00e9 Girard]] in the team's first match following the [[2006 UEFA European Under-21 Championship]] against [[Belgium national under-21 football team|Belgium]]. He started the match and was replaced at half-time by [[Yoann Gourcuff]].<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.fff.fr/selections/espoirs/actualite/316841.shtml | title = La Belgique s'impose 1\u20130 | date = 15 August 2006 | work=[[French Football Federation]] | accessdate =6 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref> He featured in [[2007 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualification|qualification matches]] for the [[2007 UEFA European Under-21 Championship]] and appeared as a starter and substitute in the first leg and second leg, respectively, of the team's surprising defeat to Israel in the qualifying playoffs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under21/history/season=2007/round=2239/match=84936/index.html |title=Sahar sets Israel up nicely |date=7 October 2006 |accessdate=6 May 2012 |publisher=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131116004520/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under21/history/season%3D2007/round%3D2239/match%3D84936/index.html |archivedate=16 November 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under21/history/season=2007/round=2239/match=84937/index.html |title=Israeli joy after historic win |date=11 October 2006 |accessdate=6 May 2012 |publisher=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131116005616/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under21/history/season%3D2007/round%3D2239/match%3D84937/index.html |archivedate=16 November 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.fff.fr/selections/espoirs/actualite/328651.shtml | title = France et Isra\u00ebl dos \u00e0 dos (1\u20131) | date = 7 October 2006 | work=[[French Football Federation]] | accessdate =20 February 2011 | language = French}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.fff.fr/selections/espoirs/329983.shtml | title = La France \u00e9limin\u00e9e | date = 11 October 2006 | work=[[French Football Federation]] | accessdate =19 March 2011 | language = French}}</ref> Despite still being eligible to represent the under-21 team until 2009, his appearance in the second leg defeat to Israel was Benzema's last with the team and he finished his under-21 career with five appearances and no goals. Prior to representing France at senior international level, Benzema was courted by the [[Algerian Football Federation]] (FAF) who sought for the player to represent [[Algeria national football team|Algeria]] at senior international level. In December 2006, the striker was approached by former federation president Hamid Haddadj and then-national team coach [[Jean-Michel Cavalli]], but turned down the invite citing his desire to continue his international career with France.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.djazairess.com/fr/infosoir/57077 | title = Benzema dit non \u00e0 l'Alg\u00e9rie | date = 12 December 2006 | work=DjaZairess | accessdate =6 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref> Benzema later told French [[radio station]] ''[[Radio Monte Carlo]]'' \"Algeria is my parents' country and it is in my heart, but football-wise, I will only play for the French national team\".<ref>{{cite news | url = http://origin.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11806_2397952,00.html | title = Benzema commits to France | date = 11 December 2006 | work = [[Sky Sports]] | accessdate = 6 May 2012 | language = French | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131029051820/http://origin.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11806_2397952,00.html | archive-date = 29 October 2013 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\n===Senior===\n====Euro 2008====\n[[File:KBenzema.jpg|thumb|upright|Benzema playing for France in April 2008]]\nBenzema was called up for the first time to the senior national team by [[Raymond Domenech]] on 9 November 2006 for the team's friendly match against [[Greece national football team|Greece]] that would be played on 15 November. Benzema described the call-up as \"a reward\", while also stating \"I am pleased, of course, me and my family. A (the senior national team), is the national team's highest honor\".<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.fff.fr/bleus/actu/337825_une-recompense | title = Une r\u00e9compense | date = 9 November 2006 | work=[[French Football Federation]] | accessdate =6 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref> Two days before the match, he was forced to withdraw from the team due to a thigh injury, which he suffered while playing domestically for Lyon.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.fff.fr/bleus/actu/338821_benzema-et-govou-forfaits | title = Benzema et Govou forfaits | date = 13 November 2006 | work=[[French Football Federation]] | accessdate =6 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref> After failing to make the squad for the team's February 2007 match against [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]], Benzema returned to the team in March for a [[UEFA Euro 2008 qualifying]] match against [[Lithuania national football team|Lithuania]] and a friendly against [[Austria national football team|Austria]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=414682&cc=5901 | title=Newcomers Diaby, Diarra earn France call-up | publisher=[[ESPN]]| date = 15 March 2007 | accessdate =3 April 2011}}</ref> After failing to appear in the qualifier, he made his international debut on 28 March 2007 against Austria. Benzema appeared as a half-time substitute for [[Djibril Ciss\u00e9]] and scored the only goal of the match after a free-kick from Samir Nasri.<ref>{{cite news |title=Debutant Benzema gives France win over Austria |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/idUKL2817446120070328?feedType=RSS|agency=Reuters |date=28 March 2007 |accessdate=27 August 2009|author=Vignal, Patrick}}</ref> On 13 October, Benzema scored a double in a 6\u20130 win against the [[Faroe Islands national football team|Faroe Islands]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/euro2012/history/season=2008/round=2241/match=83995/index.html |title=Henry celebrates in France romp |date=13 October 2007 |accessdate=6 May 2012 |publisher=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131116005425/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/euro2012/history/season=2008/round=2241/match=83995/index.html |archivedate=16 November 2013}}</ref> After appearing regularly in the team for the rest of the 2007\u201308 season, he was named to the 23-man squad to participate in [[UEFA Euro 2008]].\n\nBenzema made his debut in the competition on 9 June 2008 in the team's opening match against [[Romania national football team|Romania]]. Benzema started the match, but was substituted out for Nasri in the second half after a frustrating performance.<ref>{{cite news |title=Romania 0\u20130 France |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/euro_2008/7363325.stm |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=11 June 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2009 | first=Chris | last=Whyatt}}</ref> The match finished 0\u20130 and Benzema was, subsequently, criticized by the French media for his performance with newspaper ''[[Le Point]]'' declaring that Benzema was \"unrecognizable\" and that he \"symbolized the impotence of France in the attack\".<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.lepoint.fr/actualites-sport/2008-06-10/l-impuissance-de-benzema/921/0/251859 | title = L'impuissance de Benzema | date = 10 June 2008 | work = [[Le Point]] | accessdate = 6 May 2012 | language = French | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131117005841/http://www.lepoint.fr/actualites-sport/2008-06-10/l-impuissance-de-benzema/921/0/251859 | archive-date = 17 November 2013 | url-status = dead }}</ref> The newspaper also cited his lack of international experience for his subdued performance. In the team's next group game against the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]], Benzema played no part in the 4\u20131 defeat.<ref>{{cite news |title=Netherlands 4\u20131 France: Dutch master class |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=232269&cc=5901 |work=ESPN |date=13 June 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2009}}</ref> He returned to the team in its final group game against [[Italy national football team|Italy]] and was given a place in the starting lineup.<ref>{{cite news |title=Italy expose French frailties |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/international/2303492/Euro-2008-Italy-expose-French-frailties.html |work=The Telegraph | author=Winter, Henry|date=18 June 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2009 |location=London}}</ref> However, France lost 2\u20130 and were eliminated from the competition.<ref>{{Cite news | url = http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/euro2012/history/season=2008/round=15093/match=300703/index.html | title = France sunk as Italy grab lifeline | date = 17 June 2008 | work = [[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] | accessdate = 6 May 2012 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131116004203/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/euro2012/history/season=2008/round=15093/match=300703/index.html | archivedate = 16 November 2013 | df = dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2008, Benzema, among several other young players in the team, was accused of being insolent during the team's campaign at the European Championship. The accusation came from international teammate [[William Gallas]] who inserted the charge in his autobiography. Though most of Gallas' accusations were directed at Nasri,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/outspoken-gallas-loses-captaincy-1029711.html|title=Outspoken Gallas loses captaincy |date=22 November 2008 |work=The Independent |location=UK|accessdate=19 March 2011 |first=Jason |last=Burt}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mirrorfootball.co.uk/news/Arsenal-s-Samir-Nasri-reopens-his-feud-with-William-Gallas-article628345.html|title=Nasri hits back at Gallas \"rubbish\" |date=13 November 2010|work=Daily Mirror |location=UK|accessdate=8 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mirrorfootball.co.uk/opinion/columnists/steve-stammers/Samir-Nasri-s-brilliance-is-spoiled-by-his-petulance-at-spurning-handshake-with-Tottenham-s-William-Gallas-before-North-London-derby-Steve-Stammers-column-article634963.html|title=Why Nasri's brilliance is spoiled by his petulance|date=24 November 2010|work=Daily Mirror |location=UK|accessdate=19 April 2011}}</ref> during the competition, it was reported by newspaper ''[[Le Parisien]]'' that several of the national team players described Benzema as \"arrogant\" and that the striker was scolded by [[midfielder]] [[Claude Makelele]] following the team's loss to the Netherlands.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.eurosport.fr/football/euro-2008/2008/un-malaise-benzema_sto1606114/story.shtml | title = Un malaise Benzema? | date = 16 June 2008 | work=[[Eurosport]] | accessdate =6 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref>\n\n====2010 World Cup====\nDespite the reports from after Euro 2008, Benzema remained a regular in the team and, ahead of [[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification|qualification]] for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]], switched to the number ten shirt after previously wearing the number nine.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.lyoncapitale.fr/Journal/univers/Sport/Football/Bleus-Benzema-pique-le-neme10-a-Govou/%28language%29/fre-FR | archive-url = https://archive.today/20120903125114/http://www.lyoncapitale.fr/Journal/univers/Sport/Football/Bleus-Benzema-pique-le-neme10-a-Govou/(language)/fre-FR | url-status = dead | archive-date = 3 September 2012 | title = Benzema pique le n\u00e8me10 \u00e0 Govou | date = 9 October 2008 | work = Lyon Capitale | accessdate = 7 May 2012 | language = French }}</ref> In the team's first match following its elimination from Euro 2008, Benzema scored a goal in a 3\u20132 friendly win over [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]] in [[Gothenburg]].<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.fff.fr/servfff/fiche_joueur_new/match.php?id_match=1244 | title = Sweden v. France Match Report | date = 20 August 2008 | work=[[French Football Federation]] | accessdate =6 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref> Two months later, he scored another goal in a 3\u20131 victory against [[Tunisia national football team|Tunisia]] at the [[Stade de France]].<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.fff.fr/servfff/fiche_joueur_new/match.php?id_match=1248 | title = France v. Tunisia Match Report | date = 14 October 2008 | work=[[French Football Federation]] | accessdate =6 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref> On 5 June 2009, Benzema converted the only goal of the match, a penalty shot, in a 1\u20130 win over [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]] at the [[Stade de Gerland]], his home stadium.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.fff.fr/servfff/fiche_joueur_new/match.php?id_match=1254 | title = France v. Turkey Match Report | date = 5 June 2009 | work=[[French Football Federation]] | accessdate =6 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref> He scored his first World Cup qualification goals in victories over the Faroe Islands and Austria in October 2009. His cap against Austria would be his last of the Domenech era as he failed to make France's preliminary 30-man squad for the World Cup. Domenech cited Benzema's struggle for form with his new club Real Madrid, rather than his alleged involvement in a sex scandal as his reason for leaving the striker out.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5itJ3Hn0pud8Aw7U5R1rmJcY3Qq_AD9FKS8M00|title=Benzema left out of France's World Cup squad|first=Samuel|last=Petrequin|agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=11 May 2010}}</ref> Prior to the list being unveiled, Benzema informed ''Radio Monte Carlo'' that if he was not selected he would be \"very disappointed, but not killed\" and \"I will support the France team no matter what\".<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.rmcsport.fr/editorial/110654/benzema-decu-mais-pas-abattu-si-je-n-y-suis-pas/ | title = Benzema: \"D\u00e9\u00e7u mais pas abattu si je n\u2019y suis pas\" | date = 11 May 2010 | work=[[Radio Monte Carlo]] | accessdate =6 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref>\n\n====Euro 2012====\n[[File:Karim Benzema Euro 2012 vs Sweden 01.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Benzema playing for France at [[UEFA Euro 2012]].]]\nFollowing the World Cup, Benzema returned to the national team under the reign of new coach [[Laurent Blanc]]. Blanc, an admirer of Benzema, sought to build the attack around the striker and, after going almost a year without representing France, Benzema made his return to the team in its 2\u20131 defeat to [[Norway national football team|Norway]] in [[Oslo]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Laurent Blanc: Benzema is 'not used to working' |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=828433&sec=euro2012&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=30 September 2010 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Norway sink France thanks to Huseklepp double |url=https://af.reuters.com/article/sportsNews/idAFJOE67B04520100812 |work=[[Reuters]] |date=12 August 2010 |accessdate=13 December 2011}}</ref> Alongside Gourcuff, Benzema led the team in scoring in [[UEFA Euro 2012 qualifying Group D|qualifying]] for [[UEFA Euro 2012]] netting three. He scored his three goals in wins over [[Bosnia and Herzegovina national football team|Bosnia and Herzegovina]], [[Luxembourg national football team|Luxembourg]], and [[Albania national football team|Albania]].<ref>{{cite news |title=France and Blanc up and running in Sarajevo |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=2012/matches/round=15171/match=2002090/postmatch/report/index.html |work=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |date=7 September 2010 |accessdate=13 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema and Gourcuff keep France flying |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=2012/matches/round=15171/match=2002084/postmatch/report/index.html |work=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |date=12 October 2010 |accessdate=13 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=France squeeze past Albania to stay top |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=2012/matches/round=15171/match=2002100/postmatch/report/index.html |work=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |date=7 September 2011 |accessdate=13 December 2011}}</ref> On 17 November 2010, Benzema scored the opening goal in France's 2\u20131 win over [[England national football team|England]] at [[Wembley Stadium]].<ref>{{cite news |title=France too good for England in Wembley friendly |url=http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/17112010/2/france-good-england-wembley-friendly.html |work=[[Yahoo! Sports]] |date=17 November 2010 |accessdate=13 December 2011}}</ref> In the team's next match against [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] in February 2011, he scored the only goal for France in a 1\u20130 win.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/international-friendlies/8315057/France-1-Brazil-0-match-report.html | title = France 1 Brazil 0: match report |date= 9 February 2011 | accessdate =13 December 2011 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |location=UK}}</ref> After appearing regularly in qualifying for UEFA Euro 2012, on 29 May 2012, Benzema was named to the squad to participate in the competition.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/international/yoann-gourcuff-omitted-as-france-announce-euro-2012-squad-7800136.html|title=Yoann Gourcuff omitted as France announce Euro 2012 squad|date=29 May 2012 |work=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=3 June 2012}}</ref> On 5 June, in the team's final warm-up friendly ahead of the European Championship, Benzema scored two goals in a 4\u20130 shutout win over [[Estonia national football team|Estonia]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/sns-rt-uk-soccer-friendly-francebre854193-20120605,0,7372040.story|title=Benzema, Ribery shine as France thrashed Estonia|publisher=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=5 June 2012|accessdate=5 June 2012|work=|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130102044447/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-06-05/sports/sns-rt-uk-soccer-friendly-francebre854193-20120605_1_estonia-karim-benzema-laurent-blanc|archive-date=2 January 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> At UEFA Euro 2012, Benzema started the team's opening match against England, which ended in a 1\u20131 draw.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/18076341|title=France 1 England 1|date=11 June 2012|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 June 2012}}</ref> In the team's ensuing group stage match against the Ukraine, he assisted on both team goals in a 2\u20130 win.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/06/16/sports/soccer/euro-2012-after-rain-delay-france-shuts-out-ukraine.html|title=After Rain Delay, France Shuts Out Ukraine|publisher=[[New York Times]] |date= 15 June 2012 |accessdate=17 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n====2014 World Cup====\nOn 11 October 2013, Benzema scored his first goal for the France national team since June 2012 in a friendly against [[Australia national association football team|Australia]], thus ending a scoring drought for his national team which had lasted 1,222 minutes. In that match played at the [[Parc des Princes]] stadium in [[Paris]], which France won 6\u20130, Benzema scored France's sixth and final goal in the 50th minute after turning home [[Franck Rib\u00e9ry]]'s left-wing cross.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-us/match/124721/france-vs-australia/report?|title=France 6\u20130 Australia: Benzema breaks goal drought in friendly drubbing|date=11 October 2013|publisher=www.goal.com}}</ref> In the second leg of the [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification&nbsp;\u2013 UEFA Second Round|2014 World Cup qualification play-off]] against [[Ukraine national football team|Ukraine]] held on 19 November 2013 at the Stade de France, Benzema scored France's second goal in the 34th minute to level the aggregate score at 2\u20132. Benzema scored his goal when he side-footed home after a huge scramble in the Ukrainian penalty box, although he was shown on television replays to be offside by almost one metre when the ball took a final touch off [[Mathieu Valbuena]]'s chest. Benzema had four minutes earlier been denied a legitimate goal, the offside flag wrongly raised when he turned in Rib\u00e9ry's low cross into the net with his torso a metre from the Ukrainian goal-line. Ukraine had won the first leg of the play-off 2\u20130 in [[Kiev]] just four days earlier. France would eventually win the second leg 3\u20130 to advance to the 2014 World Cup finals in [[Brazil]] with a 3\u20132 aggregate scoreline.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/live/match/304251/report|title=World Cup Qualifiers: France revival sinks Ukraine 3\u20130|date=20 November 2013|publisher=Sky Sports}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 June 2014, Benzema was named in France's squad for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]], making his debut in the tournament.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/france/10810384/France-World-Cup-2014-squad.html|title=France World Cup 2014 squad|date=6 June 2014|accessdate=16 June 2014|work=The Telegraph}}</ref> In the team's first match, a 3\u20130 win against [[Honduras national football team|Honduras]] in [[Porto Alegre]] on 15 June, he scored a goal in each half, the first from a [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kick]]. He also assisted the team's second goal when his shot rebounded off the post and was fumbled over the goal-line by Honduran goalkeeper [[Noel Valladares]] for an own goal, the first World Cup goal given by [[goal-line technology]].<ref>{{cite news|title=France 3\u20130 Honduras|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25285092|accessdate=15 June 2014|work=[[BBC Sport]]|date=15 June 2014}}</ref> He later added a third goal sealing France's 3\u20130 victory against Honduras. He was named by [[FIFA]] as man of the match for his performance.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/matches/round=255931/match=300186496/statistics.html|title=France 3\u20130 Honduras|date=16 June 2014|accessdate=16 June 2014|work=FIFA}}</ref> In the second group fixture, he scored and had a penalty saved in a 5\u20132 defeat of [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]], as ''Les Bleus'' all but secured qualification to the [[2014 FIFA World Cup knockout stage|knockout stage]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/25285207|title=Switzerland 2\u20135 France|date=20 June 2014|accessdate=21 June 2014|work=BBC}}</ref> France were later knocked out by [[Germany national football team|Germany]] in the quarter-final stage of the tournament.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/jul/04/france-germany-world-cup-2014-quarter-final-match-report|title = Germany reach World Cup semi-finals as Mats Hummels header sinks France|date = 4 July 2014|accessdate = 18 February 2015|website = The Guardian|publisher = |last = Hytner|first = David}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/world-cup/10940667/France-vs-Germany-World-Cup-2014-live.html|title = France vs Germany, World Cup 2014|date = 4 July 2014|accessdate = 18 February 2015|website = The Telegraph|publisher = |last = Tyers|first = Alan}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/28051800|title = Germany became the first nation to reach four consecutive World Cup semi-finals as Mats Hummels' early header proved enough to see them past France at the Maracana.|date = 4 July 2014|accessdate = 18 February 2015|website = BBC Sport|publisher = |last = Ornstein|first = David}}</ref>\n\n====Euro 2016 and 2018 World Cup====\nOn 13 April 2016, French Football Federation announced that Benzema would not be picked for [[UEFA Euro 2016|Euro 2016]] tournament on home soil.<ref name=\"Benzema axed from France\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2016/04/13/karim-benzema-axed-from-france-euro-2016-squad/|title=Karim Benzema axed from France Euro 2016 squad|work=The Telegraph|date=13 April 2016|accessdate=13 April 2016}}</ref> He responded on 1 June 2016 in ''Marca'', in an interview entitled 'Benzema: \"Deschamps folded due to pressure from France's racist element\"'.<ref>[http://www.marca.com/futbol/real-madrid/2016/06/01/574dfc86e2704e5c1d8b463c.html marca.com: 'Benzema: \"Deschamps se pliega a la presi\u00f3n de una parte racista de Francia\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161202195036/http://www.marca.com/futbol/real-madrid/2016/06/01/574dfc86e2704e5c1d8b463c.html |date=2 December 2016}}, 1 June 2016</ref>\n\nBenzema was also left off the roster for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018 World Cup]] in Russia.<ref>https://the18.com/soccer-news/karim-benzema-france-world-cup-squad</ref> Directing his frustration at FFF president [[No\u00ebl Le Gra\u00ebt]], Benzema later tweeted: \"Mr Le Gra\u00ebt, with all due respect, you've lost an opportunity to remain silent. I've discovered your true face, and this isn't the one that said he appreciated me and wouldn't discuss the subject of team selections!\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.as.com/en/2018/05/31/football/1527758335_120289.html|title=Benzema hits back after FFF president backs World Cup omission|last=AS|first=Diario|date=2018-05-31|website=AS.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-15}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, Benzema replied to Le Gra\u00ebt's comments that his career with France was over, by saying: \"If you think I'm done, let me play with one of the other countries I am eligible for and we'll see\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/real-madrid/2019/11/16/5dd05926268e3eeb4d8b45ff.html|title=Benzema would have to lose French nationality to play for Algeria|website=Marca|date=16 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\nA creative, skillful, quick, agile, and prolific forward, who is good in the air and capable of playing off the shoulders of the last defender,<ref name=\"Karim Benzema to Arsenal\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/arsenal/11796162/Karim-Benzema-to-Arsenal-Why-Real-Madrid-striker-would-be-a-perfect-signing.html|title=Karim Benzema to Arsenal: Why Real Madrid striker would be a perfect signing|publisher=The Telegraph|author1=Alistair Tweedale|date=11 August 2015|accessdate=2 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marca.com/2013/07/24/en/football/real_madrid/1374652949.html|title=Benzema's big break|publisher=Marca|author1=Ulises S\u00e1nchez-Flor|date=24 July 2013|accessdate=2 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/manchester-united-prepare-swoop-real-madrid-striker-karim-benzema-1503074|title=Manchester United prepare swoop for Real Madrid striker Karim Benzema|publisher=International Business Times|author1=Arunava Ray|date=27 May 2015|accessdate=2 May 2016}}</ref> Benzema has been described as an \"immensely talented [[Forward (association football)#Striker|striker]]\" who is \"strong and powerful\" and \"a potent finisher from inside the box\" with either foot, as well as his head, despite being naturally right footed.<ref name=Bio/><ref name=\"Karim Benzema to Arsenal\"/> An atypical [[Squad number (association football)|number 9]], although he is usually deployed as a [[Forward (association football)#Centre-forward|centre forward]], and can operate as an out-and-out striker, Benzema is also capable of playing in several other offensive positions, and has been used on the [[Forward (association football)#Winger|wing]], or even [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|behind the main striker]] as a [[Forward (association football)#Second striker|number 10 or deep-lying forward]]. In addition to his goalscoring, Benzema is known for his willingness and ability to drop into deeper or wider positions, and either link-up play with midfielders, or use his strength and technical ability to hold up the ball with his back to goal to provide [[Assist (football)|assists]] for teammates, courtesy of his vision, creativity, passing, and eye for the final ball; because of his playing style, he has been described as a \"nine and a half\" in the media.<ref name=\"Karim Benzema to Arsenal\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/analysed-karim-benzema-more-important-everybody-thought#:WC7ZOI2ok4fR0A|title=Analysed: Karim Benzema is more important than everybody thought|work=FourFourTwo|author1=Kiyan Sobhani|date=25 February 2016|accessdate=2 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=return>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.us/club/real-madrid/86/blog/post/2581789/real-madrid-karim-benzema-return-to-help-cohesion-of-attack|title=Benzema's return will bring cohesion back to Real Madrid attack|publisher=ESPN FC|author1=Rob Train|date=25 August 2015|accessdate=2 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Karim Benzema is the perfect striker for Real\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.us/spanish-primera-divisi%C3%A3%C2%B3n/15/blog/post/2050897/real-madrid-should-stick-with-karim-benzema-up-front|title=Karim Benzema is the perfect striker for Real, plus praise for Villarreal|publisher=ESPN FC|author1=Graham Hunter|date=23 September 2014|accessdate=2 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marca.com/en/2015/09/17/en/football/real_madrid/1442480053.html|title=Benzema, the silent killer|publisher=Marca|author1=Olivier Mart\u00ednez|date=17 September 2015|accessdate=2 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuttomercatoweb.com/il-volto-nuovo/karim-benzema-l-erede-di-trezeguet-80609|title=Karim Benzema, l'erede di Trezeguet|trans-title=Karim Benzema, Trezeguet's heir|publisher=TuttoMercatoWeb|language=Italian|author1=Giuseppe Di Napoli|date=18 November 2007|accessdate=3 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.marca.com/en/football/real-madrid/2018/08/12/5b6ff5d4e5fdea89608b45e4.html |title=BBA off to impressive start |publisher=Marca |author1=Pablo Polo |date=12 August 2018 |accessdate=2 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.marca.com/en/football/real-madrid/opinion/2018/01/31/5a72335e468aeb9b018b462b.html |title=Benzema, BBC's perfect lubricant |publisher=Marca |author1=Santiago Siguero |date=31 January 2018 |accessdate=2 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nDuring his time at Real Madrid, Benzema has also been praised for his work-rate and tactical intelligence off the ball, as well as his positional sense and attacking movement as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]], which often draws opposition defenders out of position, and in turn he created spaces for [[Cristiano Ronaldo]] to make attacking runs into the centre of the area from the left wing, which essentially sees him acting as a [[Forward (association football)#False 9|false 9]].<ref name=return/><ref name=\"Karim Benzema is the perfect striker for Real\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/players/cristiano-ronaldo/12177090/Cristiano-Ronaldo-takes-aim-at-Real-Madrid-teammates-as-La-Liga-hopes-take-mortal-blow.html|title=Cristiano Ronaldo takes aim at Real Madrid teammates as La Liga hopes take mortal blow|work=The Daily Telegraph|location=London|author1=Ian Hawkey|date=28 February 2016|accessdate=2 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/why-benzema-too-important-leave-real-madrid-season#:rfHxSHexxqfR0A|title=Why Benzema is too important to leave Real Madrid this season|publisher=FourFourTwo|author1=John Robertson|date=28 August 2015|accessdate=2 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.squawka.com/news/karim-benzema-is-the-mvp-of-the-b-b-c/625032|title=Karim Benzema is the real MVP of Real Madrid\u2019s star-studded attack|publisher=www.squawka.com|author1=Muhammad Butt|date=21 March 2016|accessdate=4 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.managingmadrid.com/2018/7/19/17588990/statistical-analysis-should-real-madrid-sign-eden-hazard |title=Statistical Analysis: Should Real Madrid Sign Eden Hazard? |publisher=www.managingmadrid.com |author1=Om Arvind |date=19 July 2018 |accessdate=2 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nKarim Benzema was born in the city of [[Lyon]], France to [[Algerians in France|French nationals of Algerian descent]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema, le ph\u00e9nom\u00e8ne qui r\u00e9veille le foot |url=http://www.lepoint.fr/actualites-societe/2008-02-07/benzema-le-phenomene-qui-reveille-le-foot/920/0/222742 |work=Le Point |date=7 February 2008 |accessdate=14 July 2009 |language=French |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304041607/http://www.lepoint.fr/actualites-societe/2008-02-07/benzema-le-phenomene-qui-reveille-le-foot/920/0/222742 |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title = Benzema, l'arme fatale de l'OL| url = http://www.maxifoot.fr/articles/4383/index.htm| work=Maxifoot| language = French | date = 19 September 2007| accessdate =19 June 2009}}</ref> As a practicing [[Muslim]], he observes fasting during the Islamic holy month of [[Ramadan]].<ref name=\"goal\">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/12/spain/2009/08/22/1454134/ramadan-fasting-for-real-madrid-trio-lassana-benzema-and|title=Ramadan Fasting For Real Madrid Trio Lassana, Benzema and Diarra|publisher= Dadyal Online |date=22 August 2009|accessdate=31 December 2012}}</ref> His grandfather, Da Lakehal Benzema, lived in the village of [[Tigzirt]], located in the northern town of [[Beni Djellil]] in [[Algeria]] before migrating to Lyon, where he eventually settled in the 1950s.<ref name=\"benzema_background\">{{cite news | title = Sur les traces de Karim Benzema | url = http://www.djazairess.com/fr/elwatan/94450 | work=DjaZairess | date = 13 May 2008 | accessdate =6 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref> Benzema's father, Hafid, was born in Tigzirt, while his mother, Wahida Djebbara, was born and raised in Lyon; her family originated from [[Oran]]. Benzema is the third youngest in the family and grew up with eight other siblings in [[Bron]], an eastern suburb of Lyon.<ref name=\"benzema_background\"/> His younger brothers Gressy and Sabri are also footballers.<ref>{{cite news | title = Sur les traces de Karim Benzema | url = http://www.20minutes.fr/article/648150/sports-a-vaulx-en-velin-gressy-benzema-joueur-comme-autre | work=20 Minutes | date = 6 January 2011 | accessdate =6 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref> The former currently plies his trade at the amateur level with Vaulx-le-Velin in the Division d'Honneur, the sixth division of French football, while the latter plays in the youth academy of a club in the family's hometown of Bron.<ref>{{cite news | title = Vaulx-en-Velin&nbsp;\u2013 Gressy, l'autre Benzema | url = http://fr.fifa.com/worldfootball/clubfootball/news/newsid=1368589.html | work = [[FIFA|F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association]] | date = 21 January 2011 | accessdate = 6 May 2012 | language = French | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120213165139/http://fr.fifa.com/worldfootball/clubfootball/news/newsid=1368589.html | archivedate = 13 February 2012 | df = dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Sabri Benzema, plus fort que son fr\u00e8re? | url = http://www.footmercato.net/ligue1/sabri-benzema-plus-fort-que-son-frere_38053 | work=FootMercato| date = 9 August 2009 | accessdate =6 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 February 2014, his daughter M\u00e9lia was born.<ref>{{cite news | title = Karim Benzema le footballeur est devenu papa | url = http://www.public.fr/News/Exclu-Public-Karim-Benzema-le-footballeur-est-devenu-papa-496902 | work=Public | date = 4 February 2014 | accessdate =25 November 2014 | language = French}}</ref> On 5 May 2017, his son Ibrahim was born.<ref>http://www.leparisien.fr/laparisienne/actualites/people/karim-benzema-est-papa-pour-la-deuxieme-fois-26-05-2017-6985572.php</ref>\n\n===Controversies and legal issues===\nOn 6 December 2006, he told [[Radio Monte Carlo|RMC]] about his possible selection for the [[Algeria national football team|Algerian team]]: \"It's my parents' country, it's in my heart. But good after sporting, it's true that I will play in French team. I will be always present for the French team. Then it's more for the sporting side, because Algeria is my country, here, my parents come from there. After, France ... It's more sporty, that's it.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Les citations d\u00e9form\u00e9es de Karim Benzema sur l\u2019\u00e9quipe de France et l\u2019Alg\u00e9rie|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/les-decodeurs/article/2016/06/02/les-citations-deformees-de-karim-benzema_4931167_4355770.html|website=Le Monde.fr|accessdate=20 May 2018|language=fr|date=10 June 2016}}</ref> Benzema drew some criticism for these comments, as well as for his reluctance to sing the French national anthem, \"[[La Marseillaise]]\", before each match with the national team.<ref>{{cite news|language=French|title=Karim Benzema : \"On ne va pas me forcer \u00e0 chanter La Marseillaise\"|newspaper=[[Le Monde]]|date=19 March 2013|issn=1950-6244|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/sport/article/2013/03/19/karim-benzema-on-ne-va-pas-me-forcer-a-chanter-la-marseillaise_1850657_3242.html|accessdate=21 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|language=French|author=Alexandre Boudet|title=Karim Benzema explique pourquoi il ne chantait pas la Marseillaise|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.fr/2018/04/17/karim-benzema-explique-pourquoi-il-ne-chantait-pas-la-marseillaise_a_23413381/|website=[[HuffPost]]|date=17 April 2018|accessdate=17 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 April 2010, it was first reported by French television channel [[M6 (TV channel)|M6]] that four members of the French national team were being investigated for their roles as clients in a prostitute ring operated inside of a Paris nightclub, with some of the women possibly being underage or transgender. The players were eventually revealed to be Franck Rib\u00e9ry, Sidney Govou, Hatem Ben Arfa and Benzema.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.rmc.fr/editorial/108424/quatre-bleus-impliques-dans-une-affaire-de-moeurs/ | title = Quatre Bleus impliqu\u00e9s dans une affaire de moeurs? | date = 18 April 2010 | accessdate =20 April 2010 | publisher=[[Radio Monte Carlo|RMC]] |language = French}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/breves2010/20100418_224418_ribery-parmi-les-temoins-entendus.html | title=Rib\u00e9ry parmi les t\u00e9moins entendus | date=18 April 2010 | accessdate=20 April 2010 | publisher=[[L'Equipe]] | language=French | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100421061245/https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/breves2010/20100418_224418_ribery-parmi-les-temoins-entendus.html | archivedate=21 April 2010 | df=dmy-all}}</ref> Benzema was alleged to have had a sexual rendezvous with a prostitute when she was 16 years of age, an act Benzema denied through his lawyer.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/world-cup/story/_/id/777702/ce/uk/?campaign=rss&source=soccernet&cc=5901&ver=us | title = Lawyer denies Benzema used prostitute | date = 26 April 2010 | accessdate =1 May 2010 | publisher=[[ESPN]] | language = French}}</ref> On 20 July, Benzema was questioned by Paris police and indicted on the charge of \"solicitation of a minor prostitute\".<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/jul/20/franck-ribery-karim-benzema-police | title = Franck Rib\u00e9ry and Karim Benzema held in prostitution investigation | date = 20 July 2010 | accessdate =20 July 2010 |work=The Guardian |location=UK | first=Lizzy | last=Davies}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.francefootball.fr/FF/breves2010/20100720_180924_ribery-mis-en-examen.html | title=Rib\u00e9ry et Benzema mis en examen | date=21 July 2010 | accessdate=20 July 2010 | publisher=France Football | language=French | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100722094516/http://www.francefootball.fr/FF/breves2010/20100720_180924_ribery-mis-en-examen.html | archivedate=22 July 2010 | df=dmy-all}}</ref> In November 2011, prosecutors asked for the cases against Rib\u00e9ry and Benzema to be dropped, saying that the players were not aware that the escort, identified as [[Zahia Dehar]], was 16 years old.<ref>{{cite web|title=French prosecutors accept that Ribery did not know prostitute was a minor |author=|date=19 November 2011|work=France 24|url=http://www.france24.com/en/20111119-football-ribery-prostitute-minor-case-benzema-france-paris-justice}}</ref> However, the case did go on to trial. The first hearing was held in June 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ribery and Benzema on trial on underage prostitute charges in Paris |author=|date=19 June 2013|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2343774/Franck-Ribery-Karim-Benzema-court-underage-prostitute-charges.html}}</ref> In January 2014, the judge in the case dropped the charges against both Ribery and Benzema saying there was lack of sufficient evidence that the pair knew the prostitutes were underaged.<ref>{{cite web|title=French court drops Ribery and Benzema prostitution case |author=|date=30 January 2014|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-25964763}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 November 2015, Benzema was arrested by French police for his alleged part in [[blackmailing]] fellow France international player [[Mathieu Valbuena]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Willsher|first1=Kim|title=Karim Benzema arrested by police in sex-tape blackmail case|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/nov/04/karim-benzema-arrested-sex-tape-blackmail|accessdate=4 November 2015|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=4 November 2015}}</ref> During the investigation over the blackmail plot, French Prime Minister [[Manuel Valls]] stated, \"A great athlete should be exemplary. If he is not, he has no place in the France team. There are so many kids, so many youngsters in our suburbs that relate to great athletes. They wear the blue jersey, the colours of France, which are so important in these moments.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/34974358 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=1 December 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151204081832/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/34974358 |archivedate= 4 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Pour-manuel-valls-karim-benzema-n-a-pas-sa-place-en-equipe-de-france/612424 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=1 December 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161117211727/http://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Pour-manuel-valls-karim-benzema-n-a-pas-sa-place-en-equipe-de-france/612424 |archivedate=17 November 2016}}</ref> On 10 December 2015, the president of the FFF [[No\u00ebl Le Gra\u00ebt]] announced the provisional suspension of the striker from [[France national football team|French team]] until new development of the affair.<ref>{{cite web|language=French|url=http://sport24.lefigaro.fr/football/equipe-de-france/actualites/benzema-n-est-plus-selectionnable-en-equipe-de-france-782864|title=Benzema n'est plus s\u00e9lectionnable en \u00e9quipe de France|author=Romain Schneider|date=10 December 2015|website=[[Le Figaro]]|accessdate=10 December 2015}}</ref> On 17 February 2016, the judicial review was lifted by the investigating judge who allowed Karim Benzema to get in touch again with Mathieu Valbuena. On 11 July 2017, the [[Court of Cassation (France)|Court of Cassation]] issued a judgment in which it invalidated a decision of the Court of Appeal of Versailles, which had validated the procedure by which Benzema had been indicted for complicity of attempted blackmail.<ref>{{cite web|title=Affaire de la \" sextape \" de Valbuena : une victoire judiciaire pour Karim Benzema|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/police-justice/article/2017/07/12/affaire-de-la-sextape-de-valbuena-une-victoire-judiciaire-pour-karim-benzema_5159490_1653578.html|website=Le Monde.fr|accessdate=20 May 2018|language=fr|date=12 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|8 March 2020}}<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=40900 \"Karim Benzema \u2013 Football Stats\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305224416/http://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=40900 |date=5 March 2016}}. Soccer base. Retrieved 10 June 2014</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Division\n!colspan=\"2\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup<sup>1</sup>\n!colspan=\"2\"|Europe<sup>2</sup>\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other<sup>3</sup>\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Olympique Lyonnais Reserves and Academy|Lyon B]]\n|2004\u201305\n|Campionnat National \n|11||10||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||11||10\n|-\n|2005\u201306\n|Campionnat National \n|9||5||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||9||5\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |Total\n!20!!15!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!20!!15\n|-\n|rowspan=\"6\"|[[Olympique Lyonnais|Lyon]]\n|[[2004\u201305 Ligue 1|2004\u201305]]\n|Ligue 1\n|6||0||0||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||6||0\n|-\n|[[2005\u201306 Ligue 1|2005\u201306]]\n|Ligue 1\n|13||1||2||2||1||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||16||4\n|-\n|[[2006\u201307 Olympique Lyonnais season|2006\u201307]]\n|Ligue 1\n|21||5||3||1||3||2||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||27||8\n|-\n|[[2007\u201308 Olympique Lyonnais season|2007\u201308]]\n|Ligue 1\n|36||20||9||7||7||4||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||52||31\n|-\n|[[2008\u201309 Olympique Lyonnais season|2008\u201309]]\n|Ligue 1\n|36||17||3||1||8||5||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||47||23\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |Total\n!112!!43!!17!!11!!19!!12!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!148!!66\n|-\n|rowspan=\"12\"|[[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]]\n|[[2009\u201310 Real Madrid C.F. season|2009\u201310]]\n|La Liga\n|27||8||1||0||5||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||33||9\n|-\n|[[2010\u201311 Real Madrid CF season|2010\u201311]]\n|La Liga\n|33||15||7||5||8||6||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||48||26\n|-\n|[[2011\u201312 Real Madrid CF season|2011\u201312]]\n|La Liga\n|34||21||5||3||11||7||2||1||52||32\n|-\n|[[2012\u201313 Real Madrid CF season|2012\u201313]]\n|La Liga\n|30||11||8||4||10||5||2||0||50||20\n|-\n|[[2013\u201314 Real Madrid CF season|2013\u201314]]\n|La Liga\n|35||17||6||2||11||5||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||52||24\n|-\n|[[2014\u201315 Real Madrid CF season|2014\u201315]]\n|La Liga\n|29||15||3||0||9||6||5||1||46||22\n|-\n|[[2015\u201316 Real Madrid CF season|2015\u201316]]\n|La Liga\n|27||24||0||0||9||4||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||36||28\n|-\n|[[2016\u201317 Real Madrid CF season|2016\u201317]]\n|La Liga\n|29||11||3||1||13||5||3||2||48||19\n|-\n|[[2017\u201318 Real Madrid CF season|2017\u201318]]\n|La Liga\n|32||5||1||1||9||5||5||1||47||12\n|-\n|[[2018\u201319 Real Madrid CF season|2018\u201319]]\n|La Liga\n|36||21||6||4||8||4||3||1||53||30\n|-\n|[[2019\u201320 Real Madrid CF season|2019\u201320]]\n|La Liga\n|26||14||3||1||7||4||0||0||36||19\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |Total\n!338!!162!!43!!21!!100!!52!!20!!6!!501!!241\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" |Career total\n!470!!220!!60!!32!!119!!64!!20!!6!!669!!322\n|}\n\n<small><sup>1</sup>Includes [[Coupe de France]], [[Coupe de la Ligue]], [[Troph\u00e9e des Champions]] and [[Copa del Rey]]</small><br/>\n<small><sup>2</sup>Include [[UEFA Champions League]]</small><br/>\n<small><sup>3</sup>Includes [[Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a]], [[UEFA Super Cup]] and [[FIFA Club World Cup]]</small>\n\n===International===\n<!-- NOTE: when updating stats, update the infobox too! -->\n{{updated|8 October 2015}}<ref name=\"Benzema, Karim NFT\">{{NFT player|id=17409|name=Benzema, Karim|accessdate=10 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! National team!!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"9\" valign=\"center\"|[[France national football team|France]]\n|2007||8||3\n|-\n|2008||11||2\n|-\n|2009||8||3\n|-\n|2010||5||3\n|-\n|2011||10||2\n|-\n|2012||12||2\n|-\n|2013||10||2\n|-\n|2014||13||8\n|-\n|2015||4||2\n|-\n! colspan=2|Total!!81!!27\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n'''Lyon'''<ref name=\"SW\">{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/karim-benzema/1595/|title=K. Benzema|publisher=Soccerway|accessdate=30 May 2016}}</ref>\n*[[Ligue 1]]: [[2004\u201305 Ligue 1|2004\u201305]], [[2005\u201306 Ligue 1|2005\u201306]], [[2006\u201307 Ligue 1|2006\u201307]], [[2007\u201308 Ligue 1|2007\u201308]]\n*[[Coupe de France]]: [[2007\u201308 Coupe de France|2007\u201308]]\n*[[Troph\u00e9e des Champions]]: [[2006 Troph\u00e9e des Champions|2006]], [[2007 Troph\u00e9e des Champions|2007]]\n\n'''Real Madrid'''<ref name=\"SW\"/>\n*[[La Liga]]: [[2011\u201312 La Liga|2011\u201312]], [[2016\u201317 La Liga|2016\u201317]]\n*[[Copa del Rey]]: [[2010\u201311 Copa del Rey|2010\u201311]], [[2013\u201314 Copa del Rey|2013\u201314]]\n*[[Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a]]: [[2012 Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a|2012]], [[2017 Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a|2017]]\n*[[UEFA Champions League]]: [[2013\u201314 UEFA Champions League|2013\u201314]], [[2015\u201316 UEFA Champions League|2015\u201316]], [[2016\u201317 UEFA Champions League|2016\u201317]], [[2017\u201318 UEFA Champions League|2017\u201318]]\n*[[UEFA Super Cup]]: [[2014 UEFA Super Cup|2014]], [[2016 UEFA Super Cup|2016]], [[2017 UEFA Super Cup|2017]]\n*[[FIFA Club World Cup]]: [[2014 FIFA Club World Cup|2014]], [[2016 FIFA Club World Cup|2016]], [[2017 FIFA Club World Cup|2017]], [[2018 FIFA Club World Cup|2018]]\n\n'''France U17'''<ref name=\"Benzema axed from France\"/>\n*[[UEFA European Under-17 Championship]]: [[2004 UEFA European Under-17 Championship|2004]]\n\n'''Individual'''\n* [[Bravo Award]]: 2008<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/bravo-awards.html|title=The \"Bravo\" Award|publisher=RSSSF|author1=Jos\u00e9 Luis Pierrend|date=8 January 2015|accessdate=20 November 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Top goalscorers in Ligue 1|Ligue 1 Top Goalscorer]]: [[2007\u201308 Ligue 1#Top goalscorers|2007\u201308]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/soccer-europe-benzema-idUKL108380120090701|title=FACTBOX-Soccer-Real Madrid signing Karim Benzema|publisher=Reuters|author1=Tom Pilcher|date=1 July 2009|accessdate=30 May 2016}}</ref>\n* [[UNFP Player of the Month|UNFP Ligue 1 Player of the Month]]: January 2008, April 2008\n* [[National Union of Professional Footballers|UNFP]] [[Ligue 1]] [[Troph\u00e9es UNFP du football#Player of the Year|Player of the Year]]: [[Ligue 1 2007-08#Player of the Year|2007\u201308]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurosport.com/football/ligue-1/2007-2008/benzema-wins-award_sto1570187/story.shtml|title=Hotshot Benzema wins award|publisher=Eurosport|date=12 May 2008|accessdate=30 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Oscars\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/franpoy-oscar.html|title=France \u2013 Les Oscars du Football|publisher=RSSSF|author1=Erik Garin|date=20 February 2009|accessdate=30 May 2016}}</ref>\n* [[National Union of Professional Footballers|UNFP]] [[Ligue 1]] [[Troph\u00e9es UNFP du football#2008|Team of the Year]]: [[2007\u201308 Ligue 1#Team of the Year|2007\u201308]]<ref name=\"Oscars\"/>\n* ''\u00c9toile d'Or'': 2007\u201308<ref name=\"RSSSF\">{{cite web|first=Erik |last=Garin |first2=Jos\u00e9 Luis |last2=Pierrend |title=France \u2013 Footballer of the Year |publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation |date=8 January 2015 |url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/franpoy.html |accessdate=13 January 2016}}</ref>\n* [[FIFPro#FIFA FIFPro Men's World11|FIFA FIFPro World11]] nominee: 2009,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifpro.org/news/55-players-on-shortlist-fifa-fifpro-world-xi/en/ |title=55 players on shortlist FIFA/FIFPro WORLD XI |publisher=FIFPro.org |access-date=12 February 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180212142213/https://www.fifpro.org/news/55-players-on-shortlist-fifa-fifpro-world-xi/en/ |archive-date=12 February 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> 2011,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifpro.org/news/fifpro-announces-shortlist-for-fifa-fifpro-world-xi/en/ |title=FIFPro announces shortlist for FIFA FIFPro WORLD XI |publisher=FIFPro.org |access-date=12 February 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180212142218/https://www.fifpro.org/news/fifpro-announces-shortlist-for-fifa-fifpro-world-xi/en/ |archive-date=12 February 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> 2012,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/745/fifa/2012/11/29/3565257/messi-ronaldo-lead-fifa-fifpro-world-xi-shortlist |title=Messi & Ronaldo lead Fifa Fifpro World XI shortlist |publisher=Goal.com |access-date=12 February 2017}}</ref> 2019 (15th forward)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fifpro.org/news/rankings-how-all-55-male-players-finished/en/|title=Rankings: How All 55 Male Players Finished|website=FIFPro World Players' Union|date=23 September 2019}}</ref>\n* FIFA FIFPro World11 3rd team: 2015, 2017<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifpro.org/news/2015-world-xi-the-reserve-teams-2/en/ |title=2015 World XI: the Reserve Teams \u2013 FIFPro World Players' Union |publisher=FIFPro.org |date=11 January 2016 |access-date=1 October 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190409090125/https://fifpro.org/news/2015-world-xi-the-reserve-teams-2/en/ |archive-date=9 April 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifpro.org/news/2016-2017-world-11-the-reserve-teams/en/ |title=2016\u20132017 World 11: the Reserve Teams \u2013 FIFPro World Players' Union |publisher=FIFPro.org |date=23 October 2017 |access-date=23 October 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406020741/https://fifpro.org/news/2016-2017-world-11-the-reserve-teams/en/ |archive-date=6 April 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* FIFA FIFPro World11 4th team: 2014, 2016<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifpro.org/news/fifa-fifpro-world-xi-the-reserve-teams/en/ |title=FIFA FIFPro World XI: the reserve teams \u2013 FIFPro World Players' Union |publisher=FIFPro.org |date=15 January 2015 |access-date=1 October 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190414193942/https://fifpro.org/news/fifa-fifpro-world-xi-the-reserve-teams/en/ |archive-date=14 April 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifpro.org/news/2016-world-11-the-reserve-teams/en/ |title=2016 World 11: the reserve teams \u2013 FIFPro World Players' Union |publisher=FIFPro.org |date=9 January 2017 |access-date=1 October 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190409090134/https://fifpro.org/news/2016-world-11-the-reserve-teams/en/ |archive-date=9 April 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* FIFA FIFPro World11 5th team: 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifpro.org/news/world-11-the-reserve-teams-for-2017-18/en/|title=World 11: The Reserve Team for 2017-18|publisher=FIFPro.org|date=24 September 2018|accessdate=25 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626220246/https://fifpro.org/news/world-11-the-reserve-teams-for-2017-18/en/|archive-date=26 June 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[UEFA Champions League]] top assist provider: [[2011\u201312 UEFA Champions League|2011\u201312]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2012/statistics/index.html |title=UEFA Champions League 2011/12 - History - Statistics \u2013 UEFA.com |publisher=UEFA.com |access-date=25 October 2017}}</ref>\n* [[La Liga Player of the Month]]: October 2014<ref>[http://www.lfp.es/en/news/bbva-awards-for-the-best-of-october BBVA Awards for the best of October]; LFP.es 12 November 2014</ref>\n* [[France Football#French Player of the Year|French Player of the Year]]: 2011, 2012, 2014<ref name=\"RSSSF\"/>\n* Fastest goal in an [[El Cl\u00e1sico]] on 10 December 2011 (21 seconds)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/sports/soccer/barcelona-rallies-to-beat-madrid-in-clasico|title=Barcelona rallies to beat Madrid in Cl\u00e1sico|publisher=The National Post|date=10 December 2011|accessdate=30 May 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Troph\u00e9es UNFP du football#Best French Player playing Abroad|Troph\u00e9es UNFP for Best French Player playing Abroad]]: 2019<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sports.fr/football/ligue-1/articles/trophees-unfp-benzema-meilleur-joueur-francais-de-l-etranger-2476126/|title=Troph\u00e9es UNFP: Benzema meilleur joueur fran\u00e7ais de l\u2019\u00e9tranger|publisher=Sports.fr|date=19 May 2019|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{FFF male player}}\n*{{Official website}} {{in lang|fr}}\n*[http://www.realmadrid.com/en/football/squad/karim-benzema Real Madrid official profile]\n*{{Soccerway}}\n*{{FIFA player}}\n*{{UEFA player}}\n*{{LFP}}\n*{{Lequipe}}\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{Real Madrid CF squad}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = France squads\n| bg = #002395\n| fg = white\n| bordercolor = #ED2939\n| list1 = \n{{France squad UEFA Euro 2008}}\n{{France squad UEFA Euro 2012}}\n{{France squad 2014 FIFA World Cup}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes\n| bg = gold\n| fg = navy\n| title = Awards\n| list1 = \n{{2007\u201308 Ligue 1 UNFP Team of the Year}}\n{{Ligue 1 top scorers}}\n{{Ligue 1 Player of the Year}}\n{{Bravo award winners}}\n{{France Football French Player of the Year}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Benzema, Karim}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:French people of Algerian descent]]\n[[Category:French people of Kabyle descent]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Lyon]]\n[[Category:French Muslims]]\n[[Category:French footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Olympique Lyonnais players]]\n[[Category:Real Madrid CF players]]\n[[Category:Ligue 1 players]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Champions League winning players]]\n[[Category:France youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:France under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:France international footballers]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 2008 players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 2012 players]]\n[[Category:2014 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:French expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:French expatriate sportspeople in Spain]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Spain]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French association football player}}\n{{pp-pc1}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Karim Benzema\n| image = CSKA-RM18 (11).jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Benzema playing for [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] in 2018\n| fullname = Karim Mostafa Benzema<ref>{{cite web |url=http://actas.rfef.es/actas/RFEF_CmpActa1?cod_primaria=1000144&CodActa=33786 |title=Acta del Partido celebrado el 20 de marzo de 2016, en Madrid |trans-title=Minutes of the Match held on 20 March 2016, in Madrid |publisher=Royal Spanish Football Federation |accessdate=15 June 2019 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1987|12|19|df=y}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fifadata.com/documents/FCWC/2017/pdf/FCWC_2017_Squadlists.pdf |title=FIFA Club World Cup UAE 2017: List of players: Real Madrid CF |publisher=FIFA |format=PDF |page=5 |date=16 December 2017 |accessdate=23 December 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Lyon]], France\n| height = 1.85 m<ref>{{cite web|title=Real Madrid C.F.&nbsp;\u2013 Karim Benzema|url=http://www.realmadrid.com/en/football/squad/karim-benzema|publisher=[[Real Madrid]]|accessdate=18 November 2017}}</ref>\n| position = [[Forward (association football)#Striker|Striker]]\n| currentclub = [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]]\n| clubnumber = 9\n| youthyears1 = 1995\u20131997 | youthclubs1 = SC Bron\n| youthyears2 = 1997\u20132005 | youthclubs2 = [[Olympique Lyonnais Reserves and Academy|Lyon]]\n| years1 = 2004\u20132006 | clubs1 = [[Olympique Lyonnais Reserves and Academy|Lyon B]] | caps1 = 20 | goals1 = 15\n| years2 = 2004\u20132009 | clubs2 = [[Olympique Lyonnais|Lyon]] | caps2 = 112 | goals2 = 43\n| years3 = 2009\u2013 | clubs3 = [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] | caps3 = 338 | goals3 = 162\n| nationalyears1 = 2004 | nationalteam1 = [[France national under-17 football team|France U17]] | nationalcaps1 = 4 | nationalgoals1 = 1\n| nationalyears2 = 2004\u20132005 | nationalteam2 = [[France national under-18 football team|France U18]] | nationalcaps2 = 17 | nationalgoals2 = 14\n| nationalyears3 = 2005\u20132006 | nationalteam3 = [[France national under-19 football team|France U19]] | nationalcaps3 = 9 | nationalgoals3 = 5\n| nationalyears4 = 2006 | nationalteam4 = [[France national under-21 football team|France U21]] | nationalcaps4 = 5 | nationalgoals4 = 0\n| nationalyears5 = 2007\u2013 | nationalteam5 = [[France national football team|France]] | nationalcaps5 = 81 | nationalgoals5 = 27\n| pcupdate = 22:55, 8 March 2020 (UTC)\n| ntupdate = 11 October 2015\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport|Men's [[association football|football]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{fb|FRA}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[UEFA European Under-17 Championship]]}}\n{{Medal|W|[[2004 UEFA European Under-17 Championship|2004 France]]|}}\n}}\n'''Karim Mostafa Benzema''' ({{IPA-fr|ka\u0281im b\u025bnzema}}; born 19 December 1987) is a French professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Forward (association football)#Striker|striker]] for Spanish club [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] and the [[France national football team|France national team]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/world-cup/player/bio?id=46858&cc=5901&ver=us|title=Karim Benzema: Overview |publisher=[[ESPN]]|date= |accessdate=29 March 2011}}</ref> He has been described as an \"immensely talented striker\" who is \"strong and powerful\" and \"a potent finisher from inside the box\".<ref name=Bio>{{cite news |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/player/_/id/46858/karim-benzema?cc=5901|title=Karim Benzema ESPN Bio |publisher=[[ESPN]]|date= |accessdate=29 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nBenzema was born in the city of [[Lyon]] and began his football career with local club Bron Terraillon. In 1996, he joined [[Olympique Lyonnais]], and subsequently came through the [[Olympique Lyonnais Reserves and Academy|club's youth academy]]. Benzema made his professional debut in the [[2004\u201305 Ligue 1|2004\u201305 season]] and appeared sporadically in his first three seasons as Lyon won three titles in that span. In the [[2007\u201308 Ligue 1|2007\u201308 season]], Benzema became a starter and had a breakthrough year scoring over 30 goals as Lyon won its seventh straight league title. For his performances, he was named the [[National Union of Professional Footballers]] (UNFP) [[Ligue 1]] [[Troph\u00e9es UNFP du football#Player of the Year|Player of the Year]] and named to the organization's [[Troph\u00e9es UNFP du football#2008|Team of the Year]]. Benzema was also the [[Top goalscorers in Ligue 1|league's top scorer]] and given the [[Bravo Award]] by Italian magazine ''[[Guerin Sportivo]]''. After another season at Lyon, in July 2009, Benzema moved to Real Madrid in a transfer fee worth over \u20ac35&nbsp;million ($50&nbsp;million), and signed a six-year contract.<ref>[http://edition.cnn.com/2009/SPORT/football/07/02/lyon.benzema.real.madrid/index.html?eref=rss_latest \"Benzema agrees six-year deal at Real Madrid\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304232400/http://edition.cnn.com/2009/SPORT/football/07/02/lyon.benzema.real.madrid/index.html?eref=rss_latest |date=4 March 2016}}. CNN. Retrieved 10 June 2014</ref> After struggling to establish himself in his debut season with the club, in the ensuing two seasons, Benzema reached prominence, scoring 32 goals en route to helping Real Madrid win the [[2010\u201311 Copa del Rey|Copa del Rey]] in 2011 and the [[2011\u201312 La Liga|2011\u201312 edition]] of La Liga. He has been named [[France Football#French Player of the Year|French Player of the Year]] three times for his performances in 2011, 2012 and 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.francefootball.fr/#!/news/2011/12/13/095921_le-palmares-francais-2011.html |title=Benzema, Garcia, Martin et Hazard r\u00e9compens\u00e9s |publisher=[[France Football]] |date = 13 December 2011 |accessdate=13 December 2011 | language = French}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.realmadrid.com/en/news/2014/12/benzema-best-french-player-of-the-year|title = Benzema, best French player of the year|date = 15 December 2014|accessdate = 15 February 2015|website = RealMadrid.com|publisher = |last = |first =}}</ref>\n\nBenzema is a former [[France national youth football team|French youth international]] and has represented his nation from [[France national under-17 football team|under-17 level]] onwards. Prior to playing for the senior team, he played on the under-17 team that won the [[2004 UEFA European Under-17 Championship]]. Benzema made his senior international debut in March 2007 in a friendly match against [[Austria national football team|Austria]], scoring in a 1\u20130 win. Benzema has earned over 80 caps and represented France at three major international tournaments: the [[UEFA Euro 2008|2008]] and [[UEFA Euro 2012|2012]] editions of the [[UEFA European Championship]] and the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]]. However, Benzema has been left out of major tournament squads on three occasions: [[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010 World Cup]] due to lack of playing time with Real Madrid, [[UEFA Euro 2016|Euro 2016]] after a publicised scandal involving blackmail, and [[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018 World Cup]] for alleged tactical reasons.<ref>{{cite news |title=World Cup 2010: No place for Patrick Vieira and Karim Benzema in France squad|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/france/7712646/World-Cup-2010-No-place-for-Patrick-Vieira-and-Karim-Benzema-in-France-squad.html|work=The Telegraph |date=11 May 2010 |accessdate=31 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Karim Benzema left out of France squad in wake of sex-tape blackmail case|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/mar/17/karim-benzema-france-sex-tape-squad-real-madrid |work=The Guardian |date=17 March 2016 |accessdate=31 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://en.as.com/en/2018/05/31/football/1527758335_120289.html|title=Benzema hits back after FFF president backs World Cup omission|date=31 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\n===Early career===\n{{Quote box\n| width = 27%\n| align = right\n| quote = \"When I was younger, the way [[Ronaldo (Brazilian footballer)|Ronaldo]] played had an influence on me. For me, he\u2019s the best striker of all-time. I watch videos of him, and try to do what he does, but it\u2019s not easy. It\u2019s impossible to pull off the same moves as he did.\"\n| source = \u2014Benzema on the influence of his idol, Brazilian striker Ronaldo, on his own career.<ref>{{cite news |title=Karim Benzema Names His Idol and Claims Zinedine Zidane Offers a Lot|url=https://www.90min.com/posts/2958310-revealed-karim-benzema-names-his-idol-and-claims-zinedine-zidane-offers-a-lot |agency=90min.com |date=4 July 2018}}</ref>\n}}\nBenzema began his football career at his hometown club Bron Terraillon SC at the age of eight. While at the club, he was nicknamed ''Coco'' by friends and, after scoring two goals in an under-10 match against the [[Olympique Lyonnais Reserves and Academy|Lyon youth academy]], began attracting attention from the biggest club in the city.<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema s'attend \u00e0 un match difficile contre \"son \u00e9quipe\" |url=http://www.lyoncapitale.fr/Journal/univers/Sport/Football-ligue-des-champions/Benzema-s-attend-a-un-match-difficile-contre-son-equipe |work=Lyon Capitale |date=2 November 2011 |accessdate=7 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref><ref name=\"benzema_class\">{{cite news |title=Benzema: la classe internationale |url=http://www.lyoncapitale.fr/Journal/univers/Sport/Football/Benzema-la-classe-internationale/%28language%29/fre-FR |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130107052935/http://www.lyoncapitale.fr/Journal/univers/Sport/Football/Benzema-la-classe-internationale/(language)/fre-FR |url-status=dead |archive-date=7 January 2013 |work=Lyon Capitale |date=18 September 2007 |accessdate=7 May 2012 |language=French }}</ref> According to Serge Santa Cruz, who was president of Bron Terraillon in the 1990s, Lyon officials had visited him directly in an attempt to sign the youngster; however, Santa Cruz refused.<ref name=\"benzema_youth\">{{cite news |title=Benzema, le ph\u00e9nom\u00e8ne qui r\u00e9veille le foot |url=http://www.lepoint.fr/actualites-societe/2008-02-07/benzema-le-phenomene-qui-reveille-le-foot/920/0/222742 |work=Le Point |date=7 February 2008 |accessdate=7 May 2012 |language=French |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304041607/http://www.lepoint.fr/actualites-societe/2008-02-07/benzema-le-phenomene-qui-reveille-le-foot/920/0/222742 |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> After talking with Benzema's father, the club allowed the player to undergo a trial with Lyon.<ref name=\"benzema_youth\"/> Following the trial, Benzema officially joined Lyon and was inserted into the club's academy.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Rise and Rise of Karim Benzema |url=http://www.insidefutbol.com/2008/03/04/the-rise-and-rise-of-karim-benzema/ |work=Inside Futebol |date=19 December 2006 |accessdate=25 June 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Lyon===\nBenzema quickly ascended up the youth categories in the academy. He served as a [[ballboy]] during Lyon senior team matches and performed well in school being described as a student who was \"discreet and respectful\".<ref name=\"benzema_youth\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Karim Benzema |url=http://www.olweb.fr/fr/Accueil/700004/Article/50732/Benzema-Karim |work=[[Olympique Lyonnais]] |accessdate=7 May 2012 |language=French |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091003140811/http://www.olweb.fr/fr/Accueil/700004/Article/50732/Benzema-Karim |archivedate=3 October 2009}}</ref> At under-16 level, Benzema scored 38 goals in the ''Championnat National des 16 ans'', the domestic league for under-16 youth players in France.<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema, un Lyon de Olympique |url=http://fr.uefa.com/footballeurope/news/kind=2/newsid=489158.html |work=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |date=19 December 2006 |accessdate=25 June 2009 | language = French}}</ref> Ahead of the [[2004\u201305 Ligue 1|2004\u201305 season]], Benzema was promoted to the club's reserve team, which was playing in the [[Championnat de France amateur]], the fourth division of [[Football in France|French football]]. Despite only playing with the team during the autumn campaign, he scored a team-high ten goals as the Lyon reserve team finished second in its group.<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema va signer Olympique Lyonnais Reserve Pro: Saison Football 2004/2005 |url=http://www.stat2foot.com/lclubs/lyon20405.htm |work=Stat2Foot |accessdate=7 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref>\n\n====2004\u20132007====\nBenzema was called up to the senior team for the first time under manager [[Paul Le Guen]] during the break leading up to the second half of the season. As is customary with new players arriving at Lyon, the young striker had to stand up and speak to his new teammates, which at that time included the likes of [[Michael Essien]], [[Sylvain Wiltord]], [[Florent Malouda]] and [[Eric Abidal]].<ref name=\"benzema_fifa\">{{cite news |title=Benzema, 20 ans et d\u00e9j\u00e0 tout d'un grand |url=http://fr.fifa.com/worldfootball/clubfootball/news/newsid=604499.html |work=[[FIFA|F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association]] |date=24 September 2007 |accessdate=7 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref> While speaking, Benzema was subjected to jokes and laughter, which prompted the youngster to declare, \"Do not laugh, I'm here to take your place.\"<ref name=\"benzema_fifa\"/> He, subsequently, made his professional debut on 15 January 2005 against [[FC Metz|Metz]], appearing as a substitute for [[Pierre-Alain Frau]]. Lyon won the match 2\u20130 as Benzema provided the assist on the second goal scored by [[Bryan Bergougnoux]].<ref name=\"benzema_class\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Lyon v. Metz Report |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuille_match/49038 |work=[[Ligue de Football Professionnel]] |date=15 January 2005 |accessdate=7 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref> He would subsequently sign his first professional contract, agreeing to a three-year deal.<ref>{{cite news|title=Benzema va signer pro |url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/20050120_114305Dev.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091027013858/http://www.lequipe.fr/Football/20050120_114305Dev.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=27 October 2009 |work=L'Equipe |date=20 January 2005 |accessdate=25 June 2009 |language=French}}</ref> After making three more appearances as a substitute, on 2 April Benzema made his first professional start in a 1\u20130 win over [[RC Lens|Lens]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Lyon v. Lens Report |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuille_match/49122 |work=[[Ligue de Football Professionnel]] |date=2 April 2005 |accessdate=7 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref> He finished the campaign with six appearances as Lyon won its fourth-straight league title.\n\nBenzema began the [[2005\u201306 Ligue 1|2005\u201306 season]] under the tutelage of new manager [[G\u00e9rard Houllier]]. Under Houllier, he struggled for meaningful minutes due to the presence of newly signed Brazilian striker [[Fred (footballer, born 1983)|Fred]], as well as Sylvain Wiltord. Benzema made his season debut on 2 October 2005 in a league win over [[Stade Rennais F.C.|Rennes]], appearing as a substitute.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rennes v. Lyon Report |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuille_match/49743 |work=[[Ligue de Football Professionnel]] |date=2 October 2005 |accessdate=7 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref> On 6 December, he made his [[UEFA Champions League]] debut in Lyon's final group stage match against [[Norway|Norwegian]] club [[Rosenborg BK|Rosenborg]]. On his competition debut, he scored his first professional goal in a 2\u20131 win.<ref>{{cite news|title=Fred leaves Lyon purring |url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/history/season=2005/round=2201/match=1100340/index.html |work=Union of European Football Associations |date=6 December 2005 |accessdate=7 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131115233619/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/history/season%3D2005/round%3D2201/match%3D1100340/index.html |archivedate=15 November 2013 }}</ref> A month later, Benzema scored his first professional double in a 4\u20130 win over [[Grenoble Foot 38|Grenoble]] in the [[Coupe de France]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Grenoble v. Lyon Report |url=http://www.eurosport.fr/football/coupe-de-france/2005-2006/grenoble-lyon_mtc131264/live.shtml |work=[[Eurosport]] |date=8 January 2006 |accessdate=7 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref> On 4 March 2006, Benzema scored his first professional league goal against [[AC Ajaccio|Ajaccio]] in a 3\u20131 win.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ajaccio v. Lyon Report |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuille_match/49906 |work=[[Ligue de Football Professionnel]] |date=4 March 2006 |accessdate=7 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref>\n\nBenzema began earning more playing time in the [[2006\u201307 Ligue 1|2006\u201307 season]] and made his competitive season debut in the [[2006 Troph\u00e9e des Champions]] against [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]]. In the French Supercup, Benzema converted a penalty which drew the match at 1\u20131. Lyon later won the league curtain-raiser 5\u20134 on penalties.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lyon v. Paris Saint-Germain Report |url=http://www.lfp.fr/tropheeChampions/feuille_match/51300 |work=[[Ligue de Football Professionnel]] |date=30 July 2006 |accessdate=7 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref> Benzema opened the league campaign on a quick note scoring in the team's first match of the season against [[FC Nantes|Nantes]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Nantes v. Lyon Report |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuille_match/50498 |work=[[Ligue de Football Professionnel]] |date=4 August 2006 |accessdate=7 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref> Three weeks later, on 26 August 2006, Benzema appeared as a substitute and scored two goals in a 4\u20131 away win over [[OGC Nice|Nice]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Nice v. Lyon Report |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuille_match/50506 |work=[[Ligue de Football Professionnel]] |date=26 August 2006 |accessdate=7 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref> He also converted two goals in the Champions League group stage against [[Romania]]n outfit [[FC Steaua Bucure\u0219ti|Steaua Bucure\u0219ti]] and [[Ukraine|Ukrainian]] club [[FC Dynamo Kyiv|Dynamo Kyiv]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Lyon reprise winning formula |url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/Competitions/ucl/history/season=2006/Round=2357/match=1116339/report=rp.html |work=Union of European Football Associations |date=26 September 2006 |accessdate=7 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131116005122/http://en.archive.uefa.com/Competitions/ucl/history/season=2006/Round=2357/match=1116339/report=rp.html |archive-date=16 November 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema leads Lyon into last 16 |url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/Competitions/ucl/history/season=2006/Round=2357/match=1116371/report=rp.html |work=Union of European Football Associations |date=1 November 2006 |accessdate=7 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131116005646/http://en.archive.uefa.com/Competitions/ucl/history/season=2006/Round=2357/match=1116371/report=rp.html |archive-date=16 November 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> After appearing regularly during the autumn campaign, on 10 November, Benzema suffered a severe thigh injury.<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema bless\u00e9 |url=http://www.football365.fr/france/infos-clubs/lyon/lyon-benzema-blesse-384129.shtml |work=Football365 |date=10 November 2006 |accessdate=7 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref> The injury resulted in the striker missing three months of action before returning in February 2007. Benzema failed to score a goal until the final league match of the season against Nantes as Lyon recorded its sixth consecutive league title.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lyon v. Nantes Report |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuille_match/50845 |work=[[Ligue de Football Professionnel]] |date=26 May 2007 |accessdate=7 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref>\n\n====2007\u201308 season====\nFor the [[2007\u201308 Ligue 1|2007\u201308 season]], with the likes of Florent Malouda, [[John Carew]] and Sylvain Wiltord all departing from the club, Benzema switched to the number 10 shirt and was inserted into the lead striker role. After forming a special relationship with new manager [[Alain Perrin]], he responded with 31 goals in 51 games. He topped the league with 20 goals, scored four goals in the Champions League, one in the [[Coupe de la Ligue]] and totaled six goals in six Coupe de France matches, helping Lyon win their first ever [[Double (association football)|double]].<ref>{{cite news |title=The Goal.com 50: Karim Benzema (14) |url=http://www.goal.com/en-india/news/483/france/2009/01/08/1050859/the-goalcom-50-karim-benzema-14 |work=Goal.com |date=8 January 2009 |accessdate=25 June 2009}}</ref> Some of his more dazzling performances that season included a [[hat-trick]] against Metz on 15 September,<ref>{{cite news |title=Metz v. Lyon Match Report |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2007/2008&code_evt=D1&code_jr_tr=J08&num_ordre=7 |work=Ligue de Football Professionel |date=15 September 2007 |accessdate=25 June 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001070032/http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2007%2F2008&code_evt=D1&num_ordre=7&code_jr_tr=J08 |archivedate=1 October 2007}}</ref> an [[Equaliser (sports)|equalizing goal]] in the 90th minute from a [[Direct free kick|free kick]] against [[Derby du Rh\u00f4ne]] rivals [[AS Saint-\u00c9tienne|Saint-\u00c9tienne]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema coup franc contre Saint-Etienne |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KrbJcPs5kM4 |publisher=YouTube |date=7 February 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2009}}</ref> and a goal against Lens that was nominated for goal of the season by fans.\n\nIn the Champions League, Benzema scored an important double against [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] at [[Ibrox Stadium]] on the last match day of the [[2007\u201308 UEFA Champions League#Group stage|group stage]]. The 3\u20130 victory assured Lyon progression to the knockout rounds.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lyon seal revival as Rangers slump |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/history/season=2008/round=15105/match=301239/index.html |work=Union of European Football Associations |date=12 December 2007 |accessdate=25 June 2009}}</ref> In the [[UEFA Champions League 2007\u201308#Knockout stage|knockout rounds]], Lyon faced [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] and Benzema continued to score, this time it was from outside the [[Penalty area|penalty box]] in the first leg match which ended in a 1\u20131 draw<ref>{{cite news |title=Late Tevez goal gives United important draw against Lyon |url=http://www.inthenews.co.uk/sports/football/sports/football/autocodes/premiership-teams-2006-2007/manchester-united/late-tevez-goal-gives-united-important-draw-against-lyon-$1206147.htm |work=In The News |date=23 February 2008 |accessdate=27 August 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120329121917/http://www.inthenews.co.uk/sports/football/sports/football/autocodes/premiership-teams-2006-2007/manchester-united/late-tevez-goal-gives-united-important-draw-against-lyon-$1206147.htm |archivedate=29 March 2012}}</ref> and United eventually won the tie 1\u20132 on aggregate. Manchester United manager [[Alex Ferguson|Sir Alex Ferguson]] and players praised Benzema for his performance.<ref>{{cite news |title=United like the look of Benzema and begin their homework on Lyon's \u00a345m striker |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2008/feb/22/newsstory.lyon |work=The Guardian |date=28 February 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2009 | location=London | first=Daniel | last=Taylor}}</ref> Lyon club president [[Jean-Michel Aulas]] later accused Ferguson of [[tapping-up]] Benzema.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lyon chairman slams Fergie over Benzema interest |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-521768/Lyon-chairman-slams-Fergie-Benzema-interest.html;jsessionid=4DAD0645D0E04282BE71FE2E4699427B |work=The Guardian |date=28 February 2008 |accessdate=28 July 2009 | location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Ferguson questions 'balance' of Wenger's transfer policy|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/feb/23/sir-alex-ferguson-arsene-wenger-internazionale-manchester-united-arsenal-champions-premier-league |work=The Guardian |date=23 February 2009 |accessdate=28 July 2009 | location=London}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote box | width=30% | align=right | quote= \"It's a compliment to be compared to [[Zinedine Zidane]], but we are different players.\"|source= <small>\u2014Benzema in 2008 after being compared to his French compatriot Zidane.<ref>{{cite news |title=Karim Benzema keeps feet on the Lyon ground |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2291940/Karim-Benzema-keeps-feet-on-the-Lyon-ground.html |work=The Telegraph |date=17 February 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2009 | location=London | first=Ben | last=Lyttleton}}</ref> </small>}}\n\nOn 13 March 2008, Benzema extended his contract with Lyon until 2013 with a one-year extension option.<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema extends Lyon contract until 2013 |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=516330&cc=5901 |work=ESPN |date=13 March 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2009}}</ref> After signing his new contract, Benzema became one of the highest paid footballers in France.<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema becomes one of the highest paid footballers in France |url=http://en.afrik.com/article12840.html |work=Afrik |date=14 March 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100524051221/http://en.afrik.com/article12840.html |archive-date=24 May 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> For his efforts that season, he was named the Ligue 1 [[Troph\u00e9es UNFP du football#Player of the Year|Player of the Year]], selected to the [[Troph\u00e9es UNFP du football#2009|Team of the Year]] and awarded the Troph\u00e9e du Meilleur Buteur for being the league's top scorer.<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema lands Ligue 1 award |url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11800_3555834,00.html |work=Sky Sports |date=12 May 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema meilleur buteur |url=http://www.football365.fr/la-une/article_239022_L1-Benzema-meilleur-buteur.shtml |work=Football365 |date=18 May 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2009}}</ref> He was also shortlisted by French magazine ''[[France Football]]'' for the [[2008 Ballon d'Or]] award,<ref>{{cite news |title=Messi, Ronaldo lead Ballon d'Or short list |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2008/soccer/10/20/ballon.dor/index.html?eref=si_soccer |publisher=Cable News Network |date=20 October 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2009}}</ref> eventually won by [[Cristiano Ronaldo]].\n\n====2008\u201309 season====\nBenzema got off to a good start for the [[2008\u201309 Ligue 1|2008\u201309 season]], scoring twice in Lyon's opening league match against [[Toulouse FC|Toulouse]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Lyon v. Toulouse Match Report |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2008/2009&code_evt=D1&code_jr_tr=J01&num_ordre=5 |work=Ligue de Football Professionel |date=10 August 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090430165321/http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2008%2F2009&code_evt=D1&code_jr_tr=J01&num_ordre=5 |archivedate=30 April 2009 }}</ref> The following three weeks, he scored goals against [[Rh\u00f4ne-Alpes]] rivals [[Grenoble Foot 38|Grenoble]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Lyon v. Grenoble Match Report |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2008/2009&code_evt=D1&code_jr_tr=J03&num_ordre=5 |work=Ligue de Football Professionel |date=23 August 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090425063446/http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2008%2F2009&code_evt=D1&num_ordre=5&code_jr_tr=J03 |archivedate=25 April 2009}}</ref> and Saint-\u00c9tienne<ref>{{cite news |title=Saint-Etienne v. Lyon Match Report |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2008/2009&code_evt=D1&code_jr_tr=J04&num_ordre=9 |work=Ligue de Football Professionel |date=31 August 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090430165113/http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2008%2F2009&code_evt=D1&code_jr_tr=J04&num_ordre=9 |archivedate=30 April 2009}}</ref> and scored a goal against Nice, converting a [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty]] in the dying seconds.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lyon v. Nice Match Report |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2008/2009&code_evt=D1&code_jr_tr=J05&num_ordre=5 |work=Ligue de Football Professionel |date=13 September 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090423060551/http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2008%2F2009&code_evt=D1&num_ordre=5&code_jr_tr=J05 |archivedate=23 April 2009}}</ref> Lyon won all three matches. As a result of his early goals, Lyon club president Jean-Michel Aulas quelled the many transfer rumors surrounding Benzema by placing a \u20ac100&nbsp;million price tag on the striker. He was also nominated alongside [[Franck Rib\u00e9ry]] to be featured on the French cover of the video game ''[[FIFA 09]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.411mania.com/games/news/86471/%5BMulti%5D-FIFA-2009-Cover-Players.htm|title=The players to appear on FIFA 2009 game covers are revealed.|work=411Mania|date=29 September 2008|accessdate=25 June 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081005022615/http://www.411mania.com/games/news/86471/%5BMulti%5D-FIFA-2009-Cover-Players.htm|archivedate=5 October 2008}}</ref>\n[[Image:Karim Benzema 17586.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Benzema during a training session with Lyon]]\nHe scored his seventh goal of the league on 29 October, scoring in the 2\u20130 win over [[FC Sochaux-Montb\u00e9liard|Sochaux]]. Benzema scored again the following weekend in a 2\u20130 win over [[Le Mans FC|Le Mans]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://soccernet-assets.espn.go.com/match?id=252159&league=FRA.1&cc=5901 |title=Lyon 2&nbsp;\u2013 0 Le Mans |work=ESPN |date=2 November 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120324054345/http://soccernet-assets.espn.go.com/match?id=252159&league=FRA.1&cc=5901 |archive-date=24 March 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He was among the top scorers in the [[2008\u201309 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] group stage, scoring five goals,<ref>{{cite news |title=Top scorers |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/statistics/players/typestat=gs/index.html |work=Union of European Football Associations |date=17 June 2009 |accessdate=25 June 2009}}</ref> a double against Steaua Bucure\u0219ti,<ref>{{cite news |title=Lyon prove too strong for valiant Steaua |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/fixturesresults/round=15276/match=302732/report=rp.html|work=Union of European Football Associations |date=21 October 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2009}}</ref> two goals in two matches against [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Lyon fight back denies Fiorentina |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/fixturesresults/round=15276/match=302692/report=rp.html|work=Union of European Football Associations |date=17 September 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema leads Lyon onwards |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/fixturesresults/round=15276/match=302764/report=rp.html|work=Union of European Football Associations |date=25 November 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2009}}</ref> and a goal against the eventual group winners [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] on the final match day.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bayern hold on to edge past Lyon |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/fixturesresults/round=15276/match=302772/report=rp.html|work=Union of European Football Associations |date=10 December 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2009}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[Christmas and holiday season|winter break]], Benzema endured a rough patch going scoreless the first three games before recording his 11th goal of the season against Nice in a 3\u20131 victory.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nice v. Lyon Match Report |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2008/2009&code_evt=D1&code_jr_tr=J23&num_ordre=8 |work=Ligue de Football Professionel |date=8 February 2009 |accessdate=25 June 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090415115050/http://lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2008%2F2009&code_evt=D1&num_ordre=8&code_jr_tr=J23 |archivedate=15 April 2009}}</ref> Two weeks later, he scored his 12th goal against [[AS Nancy|Nancy]] in a 2\u20130 victory.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nancy v. Lyon Match Report |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2008/2009&code_evt=D1&code_jr_tr=J25&num_ordre=6 |work=Ligue de Football Professionel |date=21 February 2009 |accessdate=25 June 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090505022004/http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2008%2F2009&code_evt=D1&code_jr_tr=J25&num_ordre=6 |archivedate=5 May 2009}}</ref> The next nine matches, both Benzema and Lyon's form dwindled losing four matches, drawing three and winning only two with Benzema scoring only two goals in that stretch, both of them against Le Mans in a 3\u20131 victory.<ref>{{cite news |title=Le Mans v. Lyon Match Report |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2008/2009&code_evt=D1&code_jr_tr=J30&num_ordre=4 |work=Ligue de Football Professionel |date=4 April 2009 |accessdate=25 June 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090523230301/http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2008%2F2009&code_evt=D1&code_jr_tr=J30&num_ordre=4 |archivedate=23 May 2009}}</ref> The bad form resulted in Lyon losing their grip on first-place position and eventually falling out of the title race, thus ending their streak of seven consecutive Ligue 1 titles.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lyon's Karim Benzema tips the title Bordeaux's way |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2009/may/19/bordeaux-marseille-lyon-ligue-1|work=The Guardian |date=19 May 2009 |accessdate=27 August 2009 | location=London | first=Ben | last=Lyttleton}}</ref> Benzema was a part of four of those title runs.\n\nDespite losing the title, Benzema got back on track scoring his 15th and 16th goals of the season on 17 May in a 3\u20131 away victory over rivals [[Olympique de Marseille|Marseille]], the first goal being a penalty.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/match?id=252311&cc=5901 |title=Marseille 1&nbsp;\u2013 5 Lyon |work=ESPN |date=17 May 2009 |accessdate=25 June 2009}}</ref> He scored his 17th goal the following weekend against [[Stade Malherbe Caen|Caen]] in a 3\u20131 victory moving him into third place among Ligue 1 top scorers.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lyon v. Caen Match Report |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2008/2009&code_evt=D1&num_ordre=5&code_jr_tr=J37 |work=Ligue de Football Professionel |date=23 May 2009 |accessdate=25 June 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090625130621/http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2008%2F2009&code_evt=D1&code_jr_tr=J37&num_ordre=5 |archivedate=25 June 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Real Madrid===\n====2009\u201310 season====\nOn 1 July 2009, it was announced that Lyon had reached an agreement with Spanish club [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] for the transfer of Benzema. The transfer fee was priced at \u20ac35&nbsp;million with the fee rising to as much as \u20ac41&nbsp;million based on incentives.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/european/5712487/Karim-Benzema-joins-Real-Madrid-after-snubbing-Manchester-United.html|title = Karim Benzema joins Real Madrid after snubbing Manchester United|date = 1 July 2009|accessdate = 12 March 2015|website = The Telegraph|publisher = |last = Burt|first = Jason}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Transfert de Karim Benzema au Real Madrid |url=http://www.olweb.fr/fr/Accueil/100007/Article/50470/Transfert-de-Karim-Benzema-au-Real-Madrid |work=Olympique Lyonnais |date=1 July 2009 |accessdate=1 July 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20090702111827/http://www.olweb.fr/fr/Accueil/100007/Article/50470/Transfert%2Dde%2DKarim%2DBenzema%2Dau%2DReal%2DMadrid |archivedate=2 July 2009}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.espnfc.com/story/658536/forward-karim-benzema-joins-real-madrid-from-lyon|title = Forward Benzema joins Real Madrid from Lyon|date = 1 July 2009|accessdate = 12 March 2015|website = [[ESPN]] FC|publisher = |last = |first =}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://edition.cnn.com/2009/SPORT/football/07/01/lyon.benzema.real.madrid/index.html?eref=rss_latest|title = Lyon accept Real Madrid offer for Benzema|date = 2 July 2009|accessdate = 12 March 2015|website = CNN|publisher = |last = |first =}}</ref> On 9 July, Benzema successfully passed his medical and signed his contract, a six-year deal, later that afternoon.<ref>{{citation |title=Benzema passes medical at Real Madrid|url=http://metro.co.uk/2009/07/09/benzema-passes-medical-at-real-madrid-265812/|work=Metro|date=9 July 2009 |accessdate=12 March 2015}}</ref> He was presented officially as a Real Madrid player later that night at the [[Santiago Bernab\u00e9u Stadium]], similarly to the previous signings of [[Kak\u00e1]] and Cristiano Ronaldo.<ref>{{citation |title=Karim Benzema Thanks Florentino Perez at Official Real Madrid Presentation|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/12/spain/2009/07/09/1373590/karim-benzema-thanks-florentino-perez-at-official-real|work=GOAL.COM|date=8 July 2009 |accessdate=12 March 2015}}</ref> Benzema made his Real Madrid debut on 20 July in the club's opening [[pre-season]] [[Exhibition game|friendly]] against [[Republic of Ireland|Irish]] club [[Shamrock Rovers F.C.|Shamrock Rovers]] in [[Dublin]], appearing as a half-time substitute.<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema Strikes To Edge Real Madrid Past Spirited Shamrock Rovers|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/1783/club-friendlies/2009/07/20/1393903/benzema-strikes-to-edge-real-madrid-past-spirited-shamrock|work=goal.com|date=20 July 2009 |accessdate=11 February 2011}}</ref> He scored the lone goal in the club's 1\u20130 win, scoring in the 87th minute.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ronaldo quiet as Rovers almost hold off Real |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=661981&sec=europe&cc=5901 |work=ESPN |date=20 July 2009 |accessdate=20 July 2009}}</ref> On 24 August, Benzema netted two goals in Real Madrid's 4\u20130 victory over Norwegian club Rosenborg in an annual friendly tournament organized for the [[Trofeo Santiago Bernab\u00e9u|Santiago Bernabeu Trophy]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Madrid cruises past Rosenborg 4\u20130|url=http://www.thehindu.com/sport/football/madrid-cruises-past-rosenborg-40/article8669.ece|work=thehindu.com|date=25 August 2009 |accessdate=11 February 2011}}</ref> The goals brought his total tally in the pre-season with Real Madrid to five, making him the joint top scorer alongside fellow striker [[Ra\u00fal (footballer)|Ra\u00fal]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Led by Benzema, Real Madrid cruises past Rosenborg 4\u20130 in pre-season |url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/canadianpress/article/ALeqM5grIhuXBvcEANFkEL4nY5BDBW1xiQ |work=The Canadian Press |date=24 August 2009 |accessdate=26 August 2009}}</ref>\n\nBenzema made his league debut for Madrid on 29 August 2009 against [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a|Deportivo La Coru\u00f1a]]. He started the match, but was substituted out in the second half as Madrid won 3\u20132.<ref>{{cite news |title=Real Madrid 3\u20132 Deportivo La Coru\u00f1a |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=275652&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=29 August 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> A month later, he scored his first goal for the club in a 5\u20130 victory against newly promoted [[Xerez CD|Xerez]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Ronaldo nets twice in rout |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=275662&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=20 September 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> After missing the mid-week match against [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]], against [[CD Tenerife|Tenerife]] at the weekend, Benzema scored his first double for Madrid in a 3\u20130 home victory.<ref>{{cite news |title=Madrid maintain winning start |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=275847&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=26 September 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> He made his Champions League debut for the club on 30 September in a group stage tie against Marseille.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ronaldo and Kak\u00e1 see off Marseille |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2010/matches/round=2000028/match=2000385/index.html |work=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |date=30 September 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> In the match, Benzema assisted on a Cristiano Ronaldo goal.<ref>{{cite news |title=Red hot Ronaldo fires double |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=283173&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=30 September 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> After failing to score a goal in the month of October, in the team's first match in November against [[Italy|Italian]] club [[A.C. Milan|Milan]] in the Champions League, Benzema scored the opener to give Madrid a 1\u20130 lead. His goal was later cancelled out by a [[Ronaldinho]] penalty.<ref>{{cite news |title=Honours even for Milan and Madrid |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2010/matches/round=2000028/match=2000424/index.html |work=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |date=3 November 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> On 7 November, in the ''[[El Derbi madrile\u00f1o]]'' against [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]], Benzema assisted on Madrid's second goal, scored by [[Marcelo (footballer, born 1988)|Marcelo]]. Madrid won the match 3\u20132.<ref>{{cite news |title=Real edge five-goal thriller |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=275561&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=7 November 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Benzema - Rodriguez.jpg|thumb|left|Benzema playing against Marseille in a 2009 Champions League match.]]\n\nIn late November, Benzema began appearing mainly as a substitute as manager [[Manuel Pellegrini]] preferred [[Gonzalo Higua\u00edn]] in the lead striker role. To coincide with his benching, the striker was also being criticized by the Spanish media for his under-performance and difficulties settling in the country as he had not yet begun learning the [[Spanish language]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Pellegrini insists Benzema is fitting in at Real |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=709949&sec=uefachampionsleague&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=8 December 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema now Real's trump card |first=Andy |last=Mitten |url=http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/blogs/andy-mitten/benzema-now-real-trump-card-466.html |work=[[Yahoo!]] |date=24 March 2011 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> He was even declared the \"new [[Nicolas Anelka|Anelka]]\" by a Spanish newspaper ''[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]'' blogger, referring to former Real Madrid striker Nicolas Anelka who had a tumultuous year at the club before being sold.<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema, el nuevo Anelka... |url=http://www.marca.com/blogs/balondesastre/2009/12/02/benzema-el-nuevo-anelka.html |work=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]] |date=2 December 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2012 | language = Spanish}}</ref> Benzema was defended by his compatriot Zinedine Zidane, who admitted \"after two months, I was also criticized\" and that Benzema was \"a talented player and talented players in Madrid must win\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Zidane, sobre Kak\u00e1 y Benzema: \"A los dos meses tambi\u00e9n yo fui criticado\" |url=http://www.marca.com/2009/12/01/futbol/equipos/real_madrid/1259698642.html |work=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]] |date=1 December 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2012 | language = Spanish}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 December, Benzema appeared as a substitute for [[Rafael van der Vaart]] and scored the third goal in a 6\u20130 romp of [[UD Almer\u00eda|Almer\u00eda]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Ronaldo endures eventful night |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=275739&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=5 December 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> The day after the match against Almer\u00eda, Benzema responded to the criticism by stating, \"I am totally integrated and very happy at Real Madrid,\" and, \"Yes, I have improved my adaptation. I have a new home and I'm learning Spanish to understand myself better with my teammates.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema: \"Estoy totalmente integrado y muy feliz en el Real Madrid\" |url=http://www.marca.com/2009/12/06/futbol/equipos/real_madrid/1260105750.html |work=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]] |date=6 December 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2012 | language = Spanish}}</ref> After nearly a month coming off of the bench, he started alongside Higua\u00edn away to [[Valencia CF|Valencia]] on 12 December and responded by assisting on one of Higua\u00edn's two goals.<ref>{{cite news |title=Garay header secures Real win |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=275588&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=12 December 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> A week later, Benzema returned to the bench. On his 22nd birthday, he scored in a 6\u20130 home win against [[Real Zaragoza]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Madrid power past Zaragoza |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=275650&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=19 December 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Pellegrini 'regala' a Benzema otra suplencia por su cumplea\u00f1os |url=http://www.marca.com/2009/12/19/futbol/equipos/real_madrid/1261239012.html |work=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]] |date=19 December 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2012 | language = Spanish}}</ref> Following an injury to Higua\u00edn in early January 2010, Pellegrini inserted Benzema back into the starting lineup.<ref>{{cite news |first=Philips-Knight |last=Rob |title=Benzema's chance to shine |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/feature?id=725550&sec=europe&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=15 January 2010 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> After failing to score in his first two starts in the absence of Higua\u00edn, against Deportivo La Coru\u00f1a on 30 January, he scored a double in an important 3\u20131 away win.<ref>{{cite news |title=Primera Liga round-up |url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11827_5901962,00.html |work=Sky Sports |date=31 January 2010 |accessdate=31 January 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Match report: Deportivo La Coru\u00f1a 1\u20133 Real Madrid |url=http://www.realmadridzone.com/match-report-deportivo-la-coruna-1-3-real-madrid/ |work=Real Madrid Zone |date=30 January 2010 |accessdate=2 July 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150713112313/http://www.realmadridzone.com/match-report-deportivo-la-coruna-1-3-real-madrid/ |archive-date=13 July 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Following the return of Higua\u00edn, Benzema was relegated back to a substitute's role and finished the campaign by making eight consecutive appearances off the bench. Included in one of those appearances was his final goal of the season against [[Athletic Bilbao]] in a 5\u20131 win.<ref>{{cite news |title=Real take it to the wire |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=275584&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=8 May 2010 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n====2010\u201311 season====\n[[File:Benzema Villarreal.jpg|thumb|Right|Benzema playing in a league match against Villarreal]]\nAhead of the [[2010\u201311 La Liga|2010\u201311 season]], Benzema switched to the number 9 shirt as Real Madrid were under the tutelage of new incoming manager [[Jos\u00e9 Mourinho]]. The striker immediately drew the ire of Mourinho who declared to reporters during a pre-season media session that \"Benzema must understand that he is extremely talented, but that in itself is not enough\", while also stating that \"[Madrid] need a striker who is sparky, not one that is listless\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Mourinho calls on Benzema to wake up |url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20100823/football/mourinho-calls-on-benzema-to-wake-up.323614 |work=Times of Malta |date=23 August 2010|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> Mourinho sentiments were later echoed by incoming France national team coach [[Laurent Blanc]] who acknowledged that Benzema was \"not used to working\".<ref name=\"Mourinho plans to keep Benzema\">{{cite news |title=Mourinho plans to keep Benzema |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=812674&sec=europe&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=8 August 2010 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> Blanc also stated that the striker needed to shed weight in order to fulfill his potential.<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema finally on glory path |url=http://www.namibiansun.com/content/international-sport/benzema-finally-glory-path |work=Namibian Sun |date=3 May 2012 |accessdate=6 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131026194739/http://www.namibiansun.com/content/international-sport/benzema-finally-glory-path |archivedate=26 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nDue to Mourinho preferring Ronaldo and Higua\u00edn as his forwards,<ref name=\"Mourinho plans to keep Benzema\"/> Benzema began the campaign as a substitute coming off the bench in the team's opening league match of the season against [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Real take it to the wire |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=275584&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=29 August 2010 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> Following the September international break, he made his first start in a 1\u20130 win over [[CA Osasuna|Osasuna]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Carvalho rescues Mourinho |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=301878&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=11 September 2010|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> On 21 September, Benzema made a substitute appearance and scored his first goal of the season in a 3\u20130 home win against [[RCD Espanyol|Espanyol]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Madrid cruise to win |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=301950&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=21 September 2010|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> Afterwards, the striker failed to score a domestic goal for nearly two months. The striker did assist on goals in back-to-back weeks against [[H\u00e9rcules CF|H\u00e9rcules]] in the league and Milan in the Champions League.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ronaldo late show seals Real comeback |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=301910&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=30 October 2010|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Last-ditch Le\u00f3n takes Madrid through in Milan|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2011/matches/round=2000118/match=2002870/index.html |work=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |date=3 November 2010 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:La alegr\u00eda del gol, Benzema.jpg|thumb|left|Benzema [[Goal celebration|celebrating a goal]] against Espanyol in La Liga.]]\n\nOn 10 November, Benzema scored his second goal of the campaign against [[Real Murcia]] in the [[2010\u201311 Copa del Rey|2010\u201311 edition]] of the [[Copa del Rey]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Real Madrid 5\u20131 Murcia |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/match?id=308803&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=10 November 2010|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> In late November, Benzema was inserted into the starting eleven following a severe back injury to Higua\u00edn, along with the team's lack of senior strikers. In his first match since being inserted into the starting lineup permanently, he scored his first Champions League goal of the season in a group stage fixture against [[Netherlands|Dutch]] club [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Masterful Madrid take top spot in style|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2011/matches/round=2000118/match=2002893/index.html |work=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |date=3 November 2010 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> In Madrid's final group stage tie against French outfit [[AJ Auxerre|Auxerre]], Benzema scored his first [[hat trick]] for the club in a 4\u20130 win. The first goal he scored was Real Madrid's 300th goal in the Champions League era.<ref>{{cite news |title=Madrid's Benzema leaves Auxerre rooted to the spot|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2011/matches/round=2000118/match=2002901/index.html |work=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |date=8 December 2010 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Real Madrid 4\u20130 Auxerre |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=307816&cc=5739 |work=[[ESPN]]|date=8 December 2010 |accessdate=8 December 2010}}</ref> Two weeks later, Benzema converted another hat trick, this time in an 8\u20130 thrashing of [[Levante UD|Levante]] in the Copa del Rey.<ref>{{cite news |title=Real Madrid 8\u20130 Levante |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/match?id=311145&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=22 December 2010|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> In the team's first fixture of the 2011 calendar year, he assisted on the game-winning goal scored by Ronaldo in a 3\u20132 win over [[Getafe CF|Getafe]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Kaka makes return |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=302036&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=3 January 2011|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> In late January, for the first time in his Real Madrid career, Benzema scored goals in back-to-back matches. On 23 January, he scored the only goal in a 1\u20130 win at home against Mallorca.<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema nets vital winner |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=301942&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=23 January 2011|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> Three days later, Benzema repeated his efforts scoring the only goal in a win over [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]] in the first leg of the team's Copa del Rey semi-final tie.<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema advantage |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/match?id=312248&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=26 January 2011|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> Real Madrid later advanced to its 37th Copa del Rey final in club history after beating Sevilla 2\u20130 in the second leg.<ref>{{cite news |title=Real into final |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=312205&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=2 February 2011|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the arrival of [[Emmanuel Adebayor]] on loan, Benzema went unused in two consecutive league matches in February 2011. He returned to the starting lineup on 19 February and embarked on a run in which he scored ten goals in eight matches. Included in those ten goals were doubles in three straight matches against [[M\u00e1laga CF|M\u00e1laga]], [[Racing de Santander]] and H\u00e9rcules, as well as a goal in the first leg of Madrid's Round of 16 tie against former club Lyon.<ref>{{cite news |title=Pellegrini endures miserable return |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=301919&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=3 March 2011|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema double keeps Real hopes alive |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=302009&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=6 March 2011|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema bags brace |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=302176&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=12 March 2011|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> The strike against his hometown club was the 100th goal of his professional career, and also the first goal for Real Madrid at the Stade de Gerland in six years, though despite the honours associated with netting the goal, Benzema did not celebrate out of respect for his former club.<ref>{{cite news |title=Gomis goal pegs back Madrid|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2011/matches/round=2000119/match=2003757/index.html |work=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |date=22 February 2011 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Benzema dribbles.jpg|thumb|right|Right|Benzema playing in a league match against Almer\u00eda.]]\n\nOn 19 March, he scored the opener in the ''El Derbi madrile\u00f1o'' as Real Madrid went on to win the match 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite news |title=Real take derby spoils |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=301843&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=19 March 2011|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> Despite his form, Benzema appeared in only one of the four highly anticipated matches against ''[[El Cl\u00e1sico]]'' rivals [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]], in which the two clubs met in the league, the [[2011 Copa del Rey Final]] and the Champions League knockout stage. In between those clashes, on 23 April 2011, Benzema scored a goal and assisted on another in a 6\u20133 win over Valencia.<ref>{{cite news |title=Madrid continue impressive form |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=301882&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=23 April 2011|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> On 30 April, he scored a goal in the team's 3\u20132 loss to Real Zaragoza.<ref>{{cite news |title=Zaragoza dent Real title dream |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=302162&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=30 April 2011|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> It was the only match of the campaign that Real Madrid loss, in which Benzema scored. To close out the campaign, Benzema scored another double in an 8\u20131 win over Almer\u00eda.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ronaldo breaks record in rout |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=302157&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=21 May 2011|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> He finished the campaign second on the team behind Ronaldo with 26 goals as Real Madrid captured the Copa del Rey giving Benzema his first honour with the club.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ronaldo's late goal gives Real Madrid win over Barcelona in Copa del Rey |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2011/apr/21/real-madrid-barcelona-copa-del-rey |work=[[Guardian Media Group]] |date=21 April 2011|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> For his performances during the campaign, particularly during the second half, Benzema was praised by Mourinho, club officials [[Florentino P\u00e9rez]] and [[Emilio Butrague\u00f1o]], as well as national team manager Laurent Blanc.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mourinho's gripes bring Benzema back to life |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/european/mourinhos-gripes-bring-benzema-back-to-life-2242769.html |work=[[The Independent]] |date=16 March 2011|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Butragueno: Benzema 'understands' football|url=http://www.espnstar.com/football/primera-liga/news/detail/item599300/Butragueno:-Benzema-%27understands%27-football/|work=[[ESPN]]|date=21 April 2011|accessdate=6 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110918093407/http://www.espnstar.com/football/primera-liga/news/detail/item599300/Butragueno:-Benzema-'understands'-football/|archive-date=18 September 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Blanc compte sur Benzema |url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/equipe-de-france-de-football/2011/06/02/02016-20110602ARTSPO00355-blanc-compte-sur-benzema.php |work=Le Figaro |date=2 June 2011|accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n====2011\u201312 season====\nPrior to the start of the [[2011\u201312 La Liga|2011\u201312 season]], Benzema, taking the advice of compatriots Blanc and Zidane,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://aol.sportingnews.com/soccer/story/2011-08-09/france-looks-to-extend-unbeaten-run-faces-chile-in-friendly|title=France looks to extend unbeaten run, faces Chile in friendly |work=[[Sporting News]] |date=9 August 2011|accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/sport/soccer/fat-chance-20110805-1ifju.html|title=Fat chance |work=The Age |date=6 August 2011|accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> ventured to [[Merano]], Italy, to attend a high performance clinic where he underwent treatment to reduce his weight.<ref name=\"benzema_weight\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.goaledor.com/la-liga-news/premier-league-benzema-gives-key-be-better.html|title=Benzema gives the key to be better|work=Goaledor|date=5 August 2011|accessdate=7 May 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141109165912/http://www.goaledor.com/la-liga-news/premier-league-benzema-gives-key-be-better.html|archivedate=9 November 2014}}</ref> The spell at the clinic was ultimately a success after the striker arrived at pre-season {{convert|8|kg|lb}} lighter.<ref name=\"benzema_weight\"/> While at the clinic, Benzema also underwent physical training to build up his [[muscle mass]].<ref name=\"benzema_weight\"/> The striker was impressive in the pre-season scoring eight goals in seven matches.<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema: European preseason top scorer |url=http://www.realmadrid.com/cs/Satellite/en/1330064116769/noticia/Noticia/Benzema:_European_preseason_top_scorer.htm |work=[[Real Madrid C.F.]] |date=9 August 2011 |accessdate=11 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110915101633/http://www.realmadrid.com/cs/Satellite/en/1330064116769/noticia/Noticia/Benzema:_European_preseason_top_scorer.htm |archivedate=15 September 2011}}</ref> His performances during the pre-season resulted in Mourinho naming him the starting lead striker for the new campaign. Mourinho was later credited with Benzema's transformation,<ref>{{cite news |title=Barcelona rise to El Clasico occasion as Lionel Messi outshines Real Madrid's Cristiano Ronaldo |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/la-liga/8948480/Barcelona-rise-to-El-Clasico-occasion-as-Lionel-Messi-outshines-Real-Madrids-Cristiano-Ronaldo.html |work=[[Daily Telegraph]] |date=10 December 2011 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> but denied full responsibility and, instead, gave credit to the striker himself.<ref name=\"mourinho_benzema\">{{cite news |title=Benzema has confidence to impress Mourinho|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContent/6/55/18130/Sports/World/Benzema-has-confidence-to-impress-Mourinho.aspx|work=english.ahram.org.eg |date=10 September 2011 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nBenzema made his 2011\u201312 competitive debut for Madrid in the first leg of the [[2011 Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a]] against Barcelona. In the match, he started and assisted on the opening goal of the match, scored by [[Mesut \u00d6zil]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Barca hold Real in Supercopa |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=330062&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=14 August 2011 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> In the second leg, with Madrid trailing 4\u20133 on aggregate late in the match, Benzema scored the equalizing goal to even the tie at 4\u20134. However, six minutes later, a [[Lionel Messi]] strike gave Barcelona the supercup.<ref>{{cite news |title=Barcelona 3\u20132 Real Madrid |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/match?id=330063&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=17 August 2011 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> Benzema made his league debut for Madrid in the team's 6\u20130 away win over Real Zaragoza.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ronaldo gets Madrid show underway |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=324018&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=28 August 2011 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> In the team's next league match two weeks later against Getafe, Benzema scored a double in a 4\u20132 victory.<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema at the double |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=324006&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=10 September 2011 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> After going scoreless in three consecutive league matches, he scored his third league goal of the campaign against [[Rayo Vallecano]] in a 4\u20132 win.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ronaldo revels in Rayo rout |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=323980&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=24 September 2011 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> In the team's ensuing match against Ajax in the Champions League, Benzema scored Madrid's third goal in a 3\u20130 home win.<ref>{{cite news |title=Masterful Madrid too much for Ajax |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2012/matches/round=2000263/match=2007592/postmatch/report/index.html |work=[[UEFA|Union of European Associations]] |date=27 September 2011 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> He also assisted on the opener, which was scored by Ronaldo.<ref>{{cite news |title=Clinical Real see off Ajax |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=331232&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=27 September 2011 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> In the club's next Champions League match against Lyon, Benzema scored again netting the opener. He also turned provider for the second consecutive match assisting on a goal by [[Sami Khedira]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Real romp past Lyon |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=331241&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=18 October 2011 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> Madrid won the match 4\u20130.<ref>{{cite news |title=Magnificent Madrid put Lyon to the sword |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2012/matches/round=2000263/match=2007607/postmatch/report/index.html |work=[[UEFA|Union of European Associations]] |date=18 October 2011 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote box | width=30% | align=left | quote= \"Benzema deserves full credit for his transformation. He had some help from me, from his teammates and from ''Zizou'', but he deserves the credit.\" |source= <small>\u2014[[Jos\u00e9 Mourinho]], on Benzema's successful progression in 2011.<ref name=\"mourinho_benzema\"/> </small>}}\n\nIn November 2011, Benzema scored five goals; three in the league and two in Europe. In the league, he converted his three goals in wins over Osasuna and Valencia, while he scored his two Champions League goals in a 6\u20132 group stage win over [[Croatia]]n club [[GNK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Ronaldo hits hat-trick |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=323925&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=6 November 2011 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Real pass Los Che test |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=323920&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=19 November 2011 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Perfect Madrid put six past Dinamo |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2012/matches/round=2000263/match=2007639/postmatch/report/index.html |work=[[UEFA|Union of European Associations]] |date=22 November 2011 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> On 10 December 2011, Benzema scored the opener in Madrid's 3\u20131 defeat to Barcelona in the ''El Cl\u00e1sico''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Barca come back to win Clasico |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=323887&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=10 December 2011 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> The goal, scored just 21 seconds into the match, was the fastest goal ever scored in a match between the two rivals.<ref>{{cite news |title=The five-point European review |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/clubfootball/news/newsid=1556169.html |work=[[FIFA|F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association]] |date=12 December 2011 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> Three days after his record-breaking goal, for his performances during the 2011 calendar year, Benzema was named the ''France Football'' [[France Football#French Player of the Year|French Player of the Year]], beating out Barcelona defender [[Eric Abidal]] and Lyon goalkeeper [[Hugo Lloris]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema \u00e9lu Fran\u00e7ais de l'ann\u00e9e |url=http://www.tf1.fr/telefoot/news-football/benzema-elu-francais-de-l-annee-6873222.html |work=[[TF1]] |date=13 December 2011 |accessdate=7 May 2012 |language=French |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120110143227/http://www.tf1.fr/telefoot/news-football/benzema-elu-francais-de-l-annee-6873222.html |archive-date=10 January 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He became only the second French player based in Spain to win the award, and also the second Real Madrid player to capture it. Zidane was the first to achieve both honorable mentions. Benzema expressed gratitude at winning the award, stating, \"It is a pleasure to win an individual trophy. When I see the previous winners&nbsp;\u2013 Zidane, [[Thierry Henry|Henry]] and other major players&nbsp;\u2013 it makes me proud to join them on the list.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema named France player of the year |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story/_/id/996025/real-madrid%27s-karim-benzema-gets-france-player-of-the-year-award?cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=13 December 2011 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> In the team's next match after winning the award, against Sevilla, Benzema assisted on two goals in a 6\u20132 triumph.<ref>{{cite news |title=Real rout Sevilla |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=323882&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=17 December 2011 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:KarimBenzema.jpg|thumb|180px|upright|Right|Benzema training ahead of a Champions League match in 2012.]]\n\nBenzema opened the 2012 portion of the campaign in positive form. He scored goals against [[Granada CF|Granada]] and M\u00e1laga.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rampant Real extend lead |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=327694&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=7 January 2012 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> Benzema scored against the latter club in the Copa del Rey in each leg of the Round of 16.<ref>{{cite news |title=Real Madrid 3\u20132 M\u00e1laga |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/match?id=335279&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=3 January 2012 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=M\u00e1laga 0\u20131 Real Madrid |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/match?id=334952&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=10 January 2012 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> The 4\u20132 aggregate win advanced Real Madrid to the quarter-finals where the club faced Barcelona. After failing to score in the first leg, which ended 2\u20131 in favour of ''Bar\u00e7a'',<ref>{{cite news |title=Barca fight back at the Bernabeu |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=335877&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=18 January 2012 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> in the second leg on 25 January 2012, Benzema scored his third goal of the season against the ''Blaugrana'', but Madrid failed to win the tie losing 4\u20133 on aggregate.<ref>{{cite news |title=Barca hold on to eliminate holders Real |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=335881&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=25 January 2012 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> On 12 February, Benzema scored his first league goal in over a month against Levante.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ronaldo inspires rampant Real |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=323827&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=12 February 2012 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> A week later, he scored a double in a 4\u20130 shutout of Racing Santander.<ref>{{cite news |title=Real Madrid rout Racing |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=323818&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=18 February 2012 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> On 24 March, Benzema scored two goals in a league win over Real Sociedad.<ref>{{cite news |title=Real return to winning ways |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=323765&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=24 March 2012 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> The two goals made him the top French scorer in La Liga history surpassing Zidane.<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema becomes top scoring Frenchman in La Liga |url=http://www.realmadrid.com/cs/Satellite/en/03_Marzo_Actualidad_11-12/1330092135712/noticia/Noticia/Benzema_joins_Zidane_as_top_scoring_Frenchman_in_La_Liga.htm |work=[[Real Madrid C.F.]] |date=19 March 2012 |accessdate=7 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120422143110/http://www.realmadrid.com/cs/Satellite/en/03_Marzo_Actualidad_11-12/1330092135712/noticia/Noticia/Benzema_joins_Zidane_as_top_scoring_Frenchman_in_La_Liga.htm |archivedate=22 April 2012}}</ref> Three days later, Benzema scored another double in a 3\u20130 first leg away win over [[Cyprus|Cypriot]] club [[APOEL FC|APOEL]] in the Champions League quarter-finals.<ref>{{cite news |title=Kak\u00e1 inspires Madrid to victory at APOEL |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2012/matches/round=2000265/match=2007681/postmatch/report/index.html |work=[[UEFA|Union of European Associations]] |date=27 March 2012 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> On 29 April, Benzema put in a masterpiece performance scoring two goals and assisting on another in a 3\u20130 win over Sevilla. The double was his seventh of the season and allowed Madrid to close in on its first ''Primera Division'' title in four years.<ref>{{cite news |title=Title within Real's reach |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=323712&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=24 March 2012 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> ''Los Blancos'' captured their 32nd league title the following week cruising to a 3\u20130 win over Athletic Bilbao.<ref>{{cite news |title=Real Madrid wins La Liga title |url=http://espn.go.com/sports/soccer/story/_/id/7883524/real-madrid-wraps-32nd-spanish-league-title |work=[[ESPN]] |date=2 May 2012 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref> Benzema appeared as a second-half substitute in the match.<ref>{{cite news |title=Real win title in style |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=323856&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=2 May 2012 |accessdate=7 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n====2012\u201313 season====\nOn the first matchday of the UEFA Champions League, Benzema scored an equalizer against [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in 3\u20132 win at Santiago Bernab\u00e9u. On 4 October 2012, Benzema scored a bicycle kick goal off a cross by Kak\u00e1 in a 4\u20131 win against Ajax in [[Amsterdam]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/football/top-stories/Ronaldo-at-the-treble-as-Real-Madrid-sink-Ajax/articleshow/16662259.cms|title=Ronaldo at the treble as Real Madrid sink Ajax|publisher=The Times of India|accessdate=4 October 2012}}</ref> On 18 December 2012, one day before his 25th birthday, his fine form saw him earn the award for best French footballer of 2012, for the second year running.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.football-espana.net/26941/benzema-france%E2%80%99s-player-2012|title=Benzema, France's Player of 2012|publisher=football-espana.net|accessdate=18 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 March 2013, Benzema opened the scoring against Barcelona in the league game at the Santiago Bernab\u00e9u. Real went on to win the game 2\u20131, the second time they beat Barcelona in a week. On 30 April 2013, Benzema scored one goal and assisted to [[Sergio Ramos]] against Dortmund.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://espnfc.com/en/report/348273/report.html?soccernet=true&cc=null|title=Ramos heads late winner|publisher=ESPN FC|accessdate=26 March 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130316113828/http://espnfc.com/en/report/348273/report.html?soccernet=true&cc=null|archivedate=16 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n====2013\u201314 season====\nBenzema started new season by scoring in a 2\u20131 win over Real Betis at the Santiago Bernab\u00e9u.<ref>{{cite web|title=Real Madrid vs. Real Betis \u2013 18 August 2013 \u2013 Soccerway |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2013/08/18/spain/primera-division/real-madrid-club-de-futbol/real-betis/1517629/ |work=Soccerway.com |date=18 August 2013}}</ref> He scored again one week later in a 1\u20130 away over Granada, assisted by Cristiano Ronaldo.<ref>{{cite web|title=Granada vs. Real Madrid \u2013 26 August 2013 \u2013 Soccerway |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2013/08/26/spain/primera-division/granada-club-de-futbol/real-madrid-club-de-futbol/1517648/ |work=Soccerway.com |date=26 August 2013}}</ref> After four matches without scoring (two with Real Madrid and two with France), he returned to goal-scoring form by netting twice in a 6\u20131 away win over [[Galatasaray S.K. (football)|Galatasaray]] in [[2013\u201314 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Galatasay vs. Real Madrid \u2013 17 September 2013 \u2013 Soccerway |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2013/09/17/europe/uefa-champions-league/galatasaray-sk/real-madrid-club-de-futbol/1584499/ |work=Soccerway.com |date=17 September 2013}}</ref> On 18 January 2014, he scored his 100th goal for Madrid in a 5\u20130 victory at [[Real Betis]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25717692 |title=Real Betis 0\u20135 Real Madrid |publisher=BBC Sport |date=18 January 2014 |accessdate=1 September 2014}}</ref> On 23 March, Benzema scored two goals against fierce rivals Barcelona in ''El Cl\u00e1sico'' at the Bernab\u00e9u from two crosses by [[\u00c1ngel Di Mar\u00eda]], taking his goal tally in La Liga to 17 goals, though Barcelona won the match 4\u20133.<ref>{{cite web|title=Barca tops Real Madrid in Clasico thriller |url=http://www.foxnews.com/sports/2014/03/23/barca-tops-real-madrid-in-clasico-thriller/ |work=Fox News |date=23 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nBenzema was part of Real Madrid's starting eleven in the [[2014 Copa del Rey Final]] on 16 April at the [[Mestalla Stadium]], and assisted Di Mar\u00eda's opening goal before [[Gareth Bale]] hit the winner for Madrid in a 2\u20131 victory.<ref>{{cite web|title=Real Madrid's Gareth Bale gallops past Barcelona to land Copa del Rey |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/apr/16/barcelona-real-madrid-copa-del-rey-match-report-gareth-bale/ |work=The Guardian (London) |date=16 April 2014}}</ref> One week later, Benzema scored the only goal of the game to win the first leg of a Champions League semi-final against Bayern Munich.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ripley|first=Dan|title=Karim Benzema pounces to give hosts semi-final advantage in Champions League|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2610386/Real-Madrid-vs-Bayern-Munich-live-Champions-League.html|accessdate=23 April 2014|newspaper=[[Daily Mail]]|date=23 April 2014}}</ref> The club went on to win the [[2014 UEFA Champions League Final|final]] in May. Real Madrid's attacking trio of Bale, Benzema and Cristiano, dubbed \"BBC\", finished the season with 97 goals.<ref>{{cite news|title=200 goals for the BBC|url=http://www.realmadrid.com/en/news/2015/09/200-goals-by-the-bbc|publisher=RealMadrid.com.|date=24 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n====2014\u201315 season====\n[[File:Karim Benzema vs. FC Schalke 04 (16647992937).jpg|thumb|right|190px|Benzema during the 2014\u201315 season]]\nOn 6 August 2014, Real Madrid announced that Benzema had signed a new five-year deal that will keep him at the club until 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realmadrid.com/en/news/2014/08/official-statement-benzema|title=Official statement: Benzema|work=realmadrid.com|date=6 August 2014}}</ref> On 12 August 2014, Benzema played the whole 90 minutes in Real Madrid's 2\u20130 win against Sevilla in [[Cardiff]] to claim the [[2014 UEFA Super Cup|UEFA Super Cup]].\n\nOn 16 September 2014, Benzema scored Real Madrid's 1,000th goal in [[UEFA competitions|European competition]] after netting a goal in a 5\u20131 victory over [[FC Basel]] in the first match of the [[2014\u201315 UEFA Champions League group stage|Champions League group stage]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Real Madrid 5 \u2013 1 FC Basel|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/29210808|accessdate=18 September 2014|publisher=BBC Sport|date=16 September 2014}}</ref> He scored the winning goal in Real Madrid's 2\u20131 away victory against [[PFC Ludogorets Razgrad|Ludogorets Razgrad]] in the Champions League after coming on as a second-half substitute.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ludogorets 1\u20132 Real Madrid: Karim Benzema delivers winner from the bench as Cristiano Ronaldo and Co survive scare in Sofia|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2777006/Ludogorets-1-2-Real-Madrid-match-report-Karim-Benzema-delivers-winner-bench.html|newspaper=[[Daily Mail]]|date=1 October 2014}}</ref> The next weekend, he scored a brace in the 5\u20130 victory against Athletic Bilbao in La Liga.<ref>{{cite news|title=Real Madrid 5\u20130 Athletic Bilbao: Cristiano Ronaldo hits yet another hat-trick and Karim Benzema bags a brace in BBC production also starring Gareth Bale|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2781553/Real-Madrid-5-0-Athletic-Bilbao-Cristiano-Ronaldo-hits-hat-trick.html|newspaper=[[Daily Mail]]|date=5 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nBenzema was chosen as [[La Liga Player of the Month]] for October 2014, with his manager [[Carlo Ancelotti]] winning [[La Liga Manager of the Month|the equivalent award]]. He scored three of Real Madrid's 13 goals of the month, in which they won three matches and only conceded just one goal.<ref>{{cite news|title=Benzema nets Player of the Month gong|url=http://www.marca.com/en/2014/11/14/en/football/real_madrid/1415969938.html|accessdate=17 November 2014|work=Marca|date=14 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n====2015\u201316 season====\nBenzema scored a hat trick in an 8\u20130 thrashing against [[Malm\u00f6 FF]] on 8 December 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2016/matches/round=2000634/match=2015746/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Ronaldo rampant as Madrid put eight past Malm\u00f6|publisher=[[UEFA]]|date=8 December 2015}}</ref> On 20 December 2015, he scored another hat trick in a 10\u20132 victory over Rayo Vallecano.<ref>{{cite web|title=Real Madrid 10\u20132 Rayo Vallecano|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/35141793|publisher=bbc.com|accessdate=20 December 2015|date=20 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe was a regular starter when the team won the [[2015\u201316 UEFA Champions League]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2016/matches/round=2000638/match=2015789/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Spot-on Real Madrid defeat Atl\u00e9tico in final again|date=28 May 2016|work=uefa.com}}</ref>\n\n====2016\u201317 season====\n[[File:Shahter-Reak M 2015 (15).jpg|thumb|left|180px|Benzema with [[Real Madrid]] in 2015]]\nIn December 2016, Benzema was called up in Real Madrid's [[2016 FIFA Club World Cup squads|squad]] for [[2016 FIFA Club World Cup]] in Japan.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2431480.html|title=Real Madrid prepare for FIFA Club World Cup|publisher=UEFA.com|date=14 December 2016|accessdate=19 December 2016}}</ref> In the semi-final match against [[Club Am\u00e9rica|Am\u00e9rica]] on 15 December, Benzema scored in the last moments of the first half, helping the team to progress in the final by winning 2\u20130.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/match/am%C3%A9rica-vs-real-madrid/2357632/report|title=Club America 0\u20132 Real Madrid: Benzema and Ronaldo fire Blancos to final|publisher=Goal.com|author=Joe Wright|date=15 December 2016|accessdate=19 December 2016}}</ref> In the [[2016 FIFA Club World Cup Final|final]] three days later against [[Kashima Antlers]], Benzema opened the score in the 9th minute, and also assisted Ronaldo's second goal, as Real Madrid won 4\u20132 in extra time after the regular time finished 2\u20132 to claim their second title.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espnfc.com/club/real-madrid/86/blog/post/3022686/cristiano-ronaldo-goals-and-karim-benzema-class-decisive-as-real-madrid-win-club-world-cup|title=Ronaldo's goals, Benzema's class decisive as Real Madrid win Club World Cup|publisher=ESPN FC|author=Rob Train|date=18 December 2016|accessdate=19 December 2016}}</ref> It was Benzema's tenth title with Real Madrid, and finished the competition as joint-second topscorer with two goals in two matches.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.fifa.com/clubworldcup/statistics/players/goal-scored.html|title=FIFA Club World Cup Japan 2016 \u2013 Statistics \u2013 Players \u2013 Top goals|publisher=FIFA.com|date=18 December 2016|accessdate=19 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 February 2017, in the first leg of [[2016\u201317 UEFA Champions League]] [[2016\u201317 UEFA Champions League knockout phase|round of 16]] against [[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]], Benzema scored Real Madrid's first goal in an eventual 3\u20131 home win, which was his 51st goal in this competition, overtaking [[Thierry Henry]] on the list of [[European Cup and UEFA Champions League records and statistics#All-time top scorers|all-time Champions League top scorers]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/8/main/2017/02/15/32720392/benzema-passes-henry-on-champions-league-top-scorers-list|title=Benzema passes Henry on Champions League top scorers list|publisher=Goal.com|date=15 February 2017|accessdate=16 February 2017}}</ref> It was his first goal in six matches and for this performance he was voted Man of the Match.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/sports/football/karim-benzema-ends-drought-with-a-record-breaking-goal-4527687/|title=Karim Benzema ends drought with a record breaking goal|publisher=The Indian Express|date=16 February 2017|accessdate=16 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe was a regular starter, and scored the last goal of the season which gave him eleven for the campaign, when Madrid won the [[2016\u201317 La Liga]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laliga.es/noticias/real-madrid-campeon-de-laliga-santander-2016-17|title=El Real Madrid, campe\u00f3n de LaLiga Santander 2016/17|date=21 May 2017|work=laliga.es}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/39926301|title=Real Madrid win La Liga title with victory at Malaga|date=21 May 2017|work=bbc.com}}</ref> and the [[2016\u201317 UEFA Champions League]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2017/matches/round=2000787/match=2019641/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Majestic Real Madrid win Champions League in Cardiff|date=3 June 2017|work=uefa.com}}</ref>\n\n====2017\u201318 season====\nOn 20 September 2017, Benzema signed a contract extension that will keep him at the club until 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realmadrid.com/en/news/2017/09/ceremony-to-mark-benzemas-contract-renewal|title=Ceremony to mark Benzema's contract renewal|publisher=realmadrid.com|date=20 September 2017|accessdate=20 September 2017}}</ref> Later on 6 March of the following year, Benzema made his 100th UEFA Champions League appearance by playing in the 2\u20131 win at [[Parc des Princes]] against [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]] in the second leg of [[2017\u201318 UEFA Champions League#Round of 16|2017\u201318 UEFA Champions League round of 16]] as Real Madrid progressed to the next round 5\u20132 on aggregate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marca.com/en/football/real-madrid/2018/03/06/5a9dd0b8468aeb466f8b463c.html|title=Benzema is set for his 100th Champions League appearance|publisher=Marca|author1=Pablo Polo|author2=Patricia Terroba|date=6 March 2018|accessdate=7 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/43291900|title=Paris St-Germain 1\u20132 Real Madrid (2\u20135 on aggregate)|publisher=BBC Sport|author=Michael Emons|date=6 March 2018|accessdate=7 March 2018}}</ref> Benzema played his 400th match in all competitions for Real Madrid on 31 March in the 3\u20130 win at [[UD Las Palmas|Las Palmas]], [[Captain (association football)|captaining]] the team and netting the second goal with a penalty.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.as.com/en/2018/03/30/football/1522408901_747803.html|title=Karim Benzema's 400th game overshadowed by goal drought|publisher=AS|author=Manu de Juan|date=31 March 2018|accessdate=31 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 May 2018, Benzema scored the first goal of the match in [[2018 UEFA Champions League Final]] by intercepting [[Loris Karius]]'s throw in a 3\u20131 victory over [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], when Madrid won their third consecutive and 13th overall Champions League title.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2018/matches/round=2000885/match=2021711/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Madrid beat Liverpool to complete hat-trick|date=26 May 2018|work=uefa.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dreamteamfc.com/c/news-gossip/400597/liverpool-real-madrid-champions-league-final-loris-karius-mistake-karim-benzema-goal|title=Shocker Why was Karim Benzema\u2019s goal allowed to stand?|publisher=Dream Team FC|accessdate=27 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2018\u201319 season====\nOn 7 November 2018, Benzema scored a brace in the 5\u20130 win at [[FC Viktoria Plze\u0148|Viktoria Plze\u0148]] in the [[2018\u201319 UEFA Champions League group stage|UEFA Champions League group stage]], reaching the 200th goal milestone with the club.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/benzema-scores-200th-real-madrid-goal-with-viktoria-plzen/1ps8h47w7bqs71n1c9t0li5d16|title=Benzema scores 200th Real Madrid goal with Viktoria Plzen strike|publisher=Goal.com|date=7 November 2018|accessdate=25 January 2019}}</ref> He became only the seventh Real Madrid player to achieve the feat.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.as.com/en/2018/11/07/football/1541628212_557267.html|title=Benzema reaches 200 Real Madrid goals|publisher=AS.com|date=7 November 2018|accessdate=25 January 2019}}</ref> He totaled three goals in six matches, all of them against Viktoria Plze\u0148, helping Real Madrid topping [[2018\u201319 UEFA Champions League#Group G|Group G]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2019/standings/round=2000980/index.html#grp-2006097|title=Group G|publisher=UEFA.com|accessdate=25 January 2019}}</ref> Later on 13 February of the following year, in the first leg of the competition's [[2018\u201319 UEFA Champions League knockout phase|round of 16]], Benzema scored the opener of a 2\u20131 away win over [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en/match/ajax-v-real-madrid/7rum3el4y3tkevzz59s9dapuy|title=Ajax 1 Real Madrid 2: Asensio strikes late after VAR controversy|publisher=Goal.com|author=Joe Wright|date=13 February 2019|accessdate=25 January 2019}}</ref> reaching 60 Champions League goals, becoming only the fourth player to do so.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/benzema-reaches-champions-league-milestone-as-real-madrid/17cgv0b8ve0as1oix8ifju41uo|title=Benzema reaches Champions League milestone as Real Madrid squeeze past Ajax|publisher=Goal.com|date=13 February 2019|accessdate=25 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n====2019\u201320 season====\nBenzema scored Real Madrid's first competitive goal of the [[2019\u201320 Real Madrid CF season|2019\u201320 season]] on 17 August in the 3\u20131 away win over Celta Vigo in the opening [[La Liga]] match.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/celta-vigo-vs-r-madrid/415636|title=Celta Vigo 1-3 Real Madrid: Gareth Bale inspires Zinedine Zidane's side to victory|publisher=Sky Sports|date=19 August 2019|accessdate=9 November 2019}}</ref> Later, on 6 November, he scored a brace in Real Madrid's 6\u20130 crushing of [[Galatasaray S.K. (football)|Galatasaray]], achieving two new milestones: he become the second player after [[Lionel Messi]] to score in 15 consecutive Champions League seasons and also the third Real Madrid player to score 50 goals in the competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://talksport.com/football/626498/real-madrid-karim-benzema-lionel-messi-champions-league/|title=GOAL GETTER Real Madrid ace Karim Benzema equals incredible Lionel Messi record of scoring in 15 consecutive Champions League seasons|publisher=talkSport|author=Daniel Sandford|date=7 November 2019|accessdate=9 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/real-madrid/cronica/2019/11/06/5dc3455f22601d75588b45ad.html|title=Rodrygo takes flight for Real Madrid|publisher=Marca|author=Arch Bell|date=6 November 2019|accessdate=9 November 2019}}</ref> His performances were praised by manager [[Zinedine Zidane]], who called him a legend and also compared him with Cristiano Ronaldo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en-ie/news/benzema-is-like-ronaldo-for-real-madrid-zidane-hails-french/1a9jyhxgqlsh19f3h78lnhm5m|title=\u2018Benzema is like Ronaldo for Real Madrid\u2019 \u2013 Zidane hails French forward after 50th Champions League goal|publisher=Goal.com|author=Chris Burton|date=7 November 2019|accessdate=9 November 2019}}</ref> Three days later, in the next league match, he scored a first-half brace in a 4\u20130 win at [[SD Eibar|Eibar]], overtaking [[Ferenc Pusk\u00e1s]] as the club's 6th all-time goalscorer in La Liga with 157 goals from 323 appearances.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxsportsasia.com/football/la-liga/1196919/karim-benzema-passes-ferenc-puskas-on-all-time-real-madrid-laliga-list/|title=Karim Benzema passes Ferenc Puskas on all-time Real Madrid LaLiga list|publisher=Fox Sports Asia|date=9 November 2019|accessdate=9 November 2019}}</ref> \n\nIn February 2020, Benzema extended his contract with Real Madrid until 2022.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://en.as.com/en/2020/02/26/football/1582745588_563887.html |title=Benzema renews with Real Madrid to 2022 |publisher=AS |date=26 February 2020 |accessdate=3 March 2020 }}</ref> On 1 March, he made his 500th appearance for Real Madrid in a 2\u20130 home win over Barcelona in El Cl\u00e1sico, becoming the fourteenth player in the club's history to achieve this milestone.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://en.as.com/en/2020/03/01/football/1583082236_322148.html |title=Real Madrid: Karim Benzema reaches 500 game milestone |publisher=AS |date=1 March 2020 |accessdate=3 March 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fcbarcelona.com/en/news/1632750/real-madrid-2-0-fc-barcelona-beaten-at-the-bernabeu |title=Real Madrid 2-0 FC Barcelona: Beaten at the Bernab\u00e9u |publisher=FC Barcelona |last1=Roberts |first1=Mike |date=1 March 2020 |accessdate=3 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n===Youth===\nBenzema is a former [[France national youth football team|France youth international]] having earned caps at all levels for which he was eligible, excluding the [[France national under-16 football team|under-16 team]]. He is a member of the group, commonly known in France as the ''G\u00e9n\u00e9ration 1987'', a youth class that produced current internationals [[Hatem Ben Arfa]], [[J\u00e9r\u00e9my M\u00e9nez]] and [[Samir Nasri]], alongside himself.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.football.fr/footballfr/cmc/cm-2010/201019/generation-1987-le-disque-raye_85838.html |title=G\u00e9n\u00e9ration 1987, le disque ray\u00e9 |date=13 May 2010 |accessdate=6 May 2012 |publisher=Football.fr |language=French |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120803182525/http://www.football.fr/footballfr/cmc/cm-2010/201019/generation-1987-le-disque-raye_85838.html |archivedate=3 August 2012}}</ref> Benzema was the last of the four to make his youth international debut under coach [[Philippe Bergeroo]] and officially joined the team ahead of the [[2004 UEFA European Under-17 Championship]] that was played on home soil. In the competition, he appeared in two matches. On his tournament debut, Benzema scored the opening goal in a 3\u20131 win over [[Northern Ireland national under-17 football team|Northern Ireland]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under17/history/season=2004/round=1658/match=75060/index.html |title=France lifted by late goals |date=9 May 2004 |accessdate=6 May 2012 |publisher=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100831172349/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under17/history/season%3D2004/round%3D1658/match%3D75060/index.html |archivedate=31 August 2010 }}</ref> His lone other appearance in the competition was in a 1\u20130 group stage win over [[Spain national under-17 football team|Spain]] as France went on to win the tournament defeated the same team in the final.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under17/history/season=2004/round=1658/match=75062/index.html |title=Spain suffer Mario setback |date=6 May 2004 |accessdate=6 May 2012 |publisher=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131115234030/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under17/history/season=2004/round=1658/match=75062/index.html |archivedate=15 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under17/history/season=2004/round=1661/match=75439/index.html |title=Ch\u00e2teauroux celebrates French win |date=15 May 2004 |accessdate=6 May 2012 |publisher=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131116000441/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under17/history/season%3D2004/round%3D1661/match%3D75439/index.html |archivedate=16 November 2013 }}</ref>\n\nBenzema was a regular starter in the team at [[France national under-18 football team|under-18]] level. He made his debut with the team at a local tournament in the [[Czech Republic]]. Benzema scored his first goal at under-18 level in the competition against [[Poland national under-18 football team|Poland]] in the team's final group stage match.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m19ans/262974.shtml | title = La France bat la Pologne et acc\u00e8de \u00e0 la finale (1\u20130) |date= 27 August 2004 | accessdate =6 May 2012 | publisher=[[French Football Federation]] | language = French}}</ref> In the final against [[Czech Republic national under-18 football team|the hosts]], he scored the opening goal in a 2\u20130 win as France were declared champions of the competition.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m18ans/196188.shtml | title = La France victorieuse en R\u00e9publique Tch\u00e8que (2\u20130) |date= 28 August 2004 | accessdate =6 May 2012 | publisher=[[French Football Federation]] | language = French}}</ref> On 30 September 2004, Benzema was one of three goalscorers in France's 3\u20130 away win over Norway.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m18ans/200924.shtml | title = La France bat la Norv\u00e8ge 3\u20130 |date= 30 September 2004 | accessdate =6 May 2012 | publisher=[[French Football Federation]] | language = French}}</ref> In the team's next match against Russia, he scored a double in a 3\u20131 victory.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m18ans/205004.shtml | title = La France remporte la premi\u00e8re manche (3\u20131) face \u00e0 la Russie |date= 26 October 2004 | accessdate =6 May 2012 | publisher=[[French Football Federation]] | language = French}}</ref> Due to France winning the 2004 U17 European title, the under-18 team was allowed participation in the [[2005 UEFA\u2013CAF Meridian Cup|2005 Meridian Cup]]. Benzema was called up to the team for the competition and played in all four matches, scoring a tournament-high five goals as France were crowned champions of the tournament.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/meridian/news/kind=1/newsid=798075.html |title=2005: Europe extend Meridian domination |date=1 January 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2012 |publisher=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100721123909/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/meridian/news/kind=1/newsid=798075.html |archivedate=21 July 2010}}</ref> He opened the tournament by scoring two goals in a 7\u20130 victory over [[Cameroon national under-17 football team|Cameroon]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m18ans/220492.shtml | title = La France s'impose face au Cameroun (7\u20130) |date= 4 February 2005 | accessdate =6 May 2012 | publisher=[[French Football Federation]] | language = French}}</ref> After going scoreless in the team's next match against [[Sierra Leone national under-17 football team|Sierra Leone]], Benzema responded by scoring a goal in a shutout victory over [[Nigeria national under-17 football team|Nigeria]] and netting another double in a 4\u20131 win against [[Egypt national under-17 football team|Egypt]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m18ans/220996.shtml | title = La France bat le Nigeria (2\u20130) |date= 8 February 2005 | accessdate =6 May 2012 | publisher=[[French Football Federation]] | language = French}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m18ans/221744.shtml | title = La France domine l'Egypte (4\u20131) |date= 11 February 2005 | accessdate =6 May 2012 | publisher=[[French Football Federation]] | language = French}}</ref> On 19 May 2005, in the team's final match of the season against [[Slovakia national under-18 football team|Slovakia]], Benzema scored all four goals in a 4\u20131 victory.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m18ans/239081.shtml | title = La France dominatrice face \u00e0 la Slovaquie (4\u20131) |date= 19 May 2005 | accessdate =6 May 2012 | publisher=[[French Football Federation]] | language = French}}</ref> He finished the under-18 campaign with 18 appearances and a team-high 14 goals and was, subsequently, praised by Bergeroo who, following the campaign, declared that Benzema was \"quite efficient\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m18ans/239226.shtml | title = Philippe Bergeroo: \"Un groupe toujours aussi motiv\u00e9\" |date= 20 May 2005 | accessdate =6 May 2012 | publisher=[[French Football Federation]] | language = French}}</ref>\n\nThe foursome of Benzema, Ben Arfa, M\u00e9nez and Nasri returned to international play together for [[France national under-19 football team|under-19]] duty. The four were joined by [[Issiar Dia]], [[Blaise Matuidi]] and [[Serge Gakp\u00e9]] with the objective of winning the [[2006 UEFA European Under-19 Championship]]. The team opened the campaign with two friendly matches against [[Norway national under-19 football team|Norway]]. Over the course of the two matches, Benzema scored one goal, which came in the first match, a 4\u20130 win.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m19ans/262974.shtml | title = Premi\u00e8re manche r\u00e9ussie face \u00e0 la Norv\u00e8ge (4\u20130) |date= 5 October 2005 | accessdate =6 May 2012 | publisher=[[French Football Federation]] | language = French}}</ref> In the first round of qualification for the UEFA-sanctioned tournament, he scored his only goal in the final group match against [[Austria national under-19 football team|Austria]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m19ans/264062.shtml | title = Troisi\u00e8me succ\u00e8s, face \u00e0 l'Autriche (2\u20130) |date= 28 October 2005 | accessdate =6 May 2012 | publisher=[[French Football Federation]] | language = French}}</ref> France won the match 2\u20130, which resulted in the team progressing to the Elite Round.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under19/history/season=2006/round=2152/match=80906/index.html |title=Austria 0\u20132 France |date=28 October 2005 |accessdate=6 May 2012 |publisher=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131115234926/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under19/history/season%3D2006/round%3D2152/match%3D80906/index.html |archivedate=15 November 2013 }}</ref> In the ensuing round, France were placed in a relatively easy group alongside [[Scotland national under-19 football team|Scotland]], [[Bulgaria national under-19 football team|Bulgaria]], and [[Belarus national under-19 football team|Belarus]]. In the opening group game against Bulgaria, Benzema scored a double converting a penalty and scoring in play as France won 4\u20130.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under19/history/season=2006/round=2225/match=82137/index.html |title=Bulgaria feel Les Bleus power |date=20 May 2006 |accessdate=6 May 2012 |publisher=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |work= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131116004707/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under19/history/season=2006/round=2225/match=82137/index.html |archive-date=16 November 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Both of his goals were scored within a minute of each other.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m19ans/304525.shtml | title = La France bat la Bulgarie (4\u20130) |date= 16 May 2006 | accessdate =6 May 2012 | publisher=[[French Football Federation]] | language = French}}</ref> After surprisingly drawing 0\u20130 with Belarus, France faced Scotland in the final group stage match. Benzema opened the scoring in the 11th minute, but his goal was cancelled out by [[Steven Fletcher (footballer)|Steven Fletcher]] in the second half.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m19ans/305419.shtml | title = La France tenue en \u00e9chec (1\u20131) |date= 20 May 2006 | accessdate =6 May 2012 | publisher=[[French Football Federation]] | language = French}}</ref> The match ultimately finished 1\u20131 and, despite finishing the round undefeated, France were eliminated after being beaten on points by the ''Scots''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under19/history/season=2006/round=2225/match=82141/index.html |title=Fletcher sends Scotland soaring |date=20 May 2006 |accessdate=6 May 2012 |publisher=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |work= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131116003742/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under19/history/season=2006/round=2225/match=82141/index.html |archive-date=16 November 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nBenzema made his [[France national under-21 football team|under-21]] debut for ''Les Espoirs'' under coach [[Ren\u00e9 Girard (footballer)|Ren\u00e9 Girard]] in the team's first match following the [[2006 UEFA European Under-21 Championship]] against [[Belgium national under-21 football team|Belgium]]. He started the match and was replaced at half-time by [[Yoann Gourcuff]].<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.fff.fr/selections/espoirs/actualite/316841.shtml | title = La Belgique s'impose 1\u20130 | date = 15 August 2006 | work=[[French Football Federation]] | accessdate =6 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref> He featured in [[2007 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualification|qualification matches]] for the [[2007 UEFA European Under-21 Championship]] and appeared as a starter and substitute in the first leg and second leg, respectively, of the team's surprising defeat to Israel in the qualifying playoffs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under21/history/season=2007/round=2239/match=84936/index.html |title=Sahar sets Israel up nicely |date=7 October 2006 |accessdate=6 May 2012 |publisher=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131116004520/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under21/history/season%3D2007/round%3D2239/match%3D84936/index.html |archivedate=16 November 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under21/history/season=2007/round=2239/match=84937/index.html |title=Israeli joy after historic win |date=11 October 2006 |accessdate=6 May 2012 |publisher=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131116005616/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under21/history/season%3D2007/round%3D2239/match%3D84937/index.html |archivedate=16 November 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.fff.fr/selections/espoirs/actualite/328651.shtml | title = France et Isra\u00ebl dos \u00e0 dos (1\u20131) | date = 7 October 2006 | work=[[French Football Federation]] | accessdate =20 February 2011 | language = French}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.fff.fr/selections/espoirs/329983.shtml | title = La France \u00e9limin\u00e9e | date = 11 October 2006 | work=[[French Football Federation]] | accessdate =19 March 2011 | language = French}}</ref> Despite still being eligible to represent the under-21 team until 2009, his appearance in the second leg defeat to Israel was Benzema's last with the team and he finished his under-21 career with five appearances and no goals. Prior to representing France at senior international level, Benzema was courted by the [[Algerian Football Federation]] (FAF) who sought for the player to represent [[Algeria national football team|Algeria]] at senior international level. In December 2006, the striker was approached by former federation president Hamid Haddadj and then-national team coach [[Jean-Michel Cavalli]], but turned down the invite citing his desire to continue his international career with France.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.djazairess.com/fr/infosoir/57077 | title = Benzema dit non \u00e0 l'Alg\u00e9rie | date = 12 December 2006 | work=DjaZairess | accessdate =6 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref> Benzema later told French [[radio station]] ''[[Radio Monte Carlo]]'' \"Algeria is my parents' country and it is in my heart, but football-wise, I will only play for the French national team\".<ref>{{cite news | url = http://origin.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11806_2397952,00.html | title = Benzema commits to France | date = 11 December 2006 | work = [[Sky Sports]] | accessdate = 6 May 2012 | language = French | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131029051820/http://origin.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11806_2397952,00.html | archive-date = 29 October 2013 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\n===Senior===\n====Euro 2008====\n[[File:KBenzema.jpg|thumb|upright|Benzema playing for France in April 2008]]\nBenzema was called up for the first time to the senior national team by [[Raymond Domenech]] on 9 November 2006 for the team's friendly match against [[Greece national football team|Greece]] that would be played on 15 November. Benzema described the call-up as \"a reward\", while also stating \"I am pleased, of course, me and my family. A (the senior national team), is the national team's highest honor\".<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.fff.fr/bleus/actu/337825_une-recompense | title = Une r\u00e9compense | date = 9 November 2006 | work=[[French Football Federation]] | accessdate =6 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref> Two days before the match, he was forced to withdraw from the team due to a thigh injury, which he suffered while playing domestically for Lyon.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.fff.fr/bleus/actu/338821_benzema-et-govou-forfaits | title = Benzema et Govou forfaits | date = 13 November 2006 | work=[[French Football Federation]] | accessdate =6 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref> After failing to make the squad for the team's February 2007 match against [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]], Benzema returned to the team in March for a [[UEFA Euro 2008 qualifying]] match against [[Lithuania national football team|Lithuania]] and a friendly against [[Austria national football team|Austria]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=414682&cc=5901 | title=Newcomers Diaby, Diarra earn France call-up | publisher=[[ESPN]]| date = 15 March 2007 | accessdate =3 April 2011}}</ref> After failing to appear in the qualifier, he made his international debut on 28 March 2007 against Austria. Benzema appeared as a half-time substitute for [[Djibril Ciss\u00e9]] and scored the only goal of the match after a free-kick from Samir Nasri.<ref>{{cite news |title=Debutant Benzema gives France win over Austria |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/idUKL2817446120070328?feedType=RSS|agency=Reuters |date=28 March 2007 |accessdate=27 August 2009|author=Vignal, Patrick}}</ref> On 13 October, Benzema scored a double in a 6\u20130 win against the [[Faroe Islands national football team|Faroe Islands]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/euro2012/history/season=2008/round=2241/match=83995/index.html |title=Henry celebrates in France romp |date=13 October 2007 |accessdate=6 May 2012 |publisher=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131116005425/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/euro2012/history/season=2008/round=2241/match=83995/index.html |archivedate=16 November 2013}}</ref> After appearing regularly in the team for the rest of the 2007\u201308 season, he was named to the 23-man squad to participate in [[UEFA Euro 2008]].\n\nBenzema made his debut in the competition on 9 June 2008 in the team's opening match against [[Romania national football team|Romania]]. Benzema started the match, but was substituted out for Nasri in the second half after a frustrating performance.<ref>{{cite news |title=Romania 0\u20130 France |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/euro_2008/7363325.stm |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=11 June 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2009 | first=Chris | last=Whyatt}}</ref> The match finished 0\u20130 and Benzema was, subsequently, criticized by the French media for his performance with newspaper ''[[Le Point]]'' declaring that Benzema was \"unrecognizable\" and that he \"symbolized the impotence of France in the attack\".<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.lepoint.fr/actualites-sport/2008-06-10/l-impuissance-de-benzema/921/0/251859 | title = L'impuissance de Benzema | date = 10 June 2008 | work = [[Le Point]] | accessdate = 6 May 2012 | language = French | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131117005841/http://www.lepoint.fr/actualites-sport/2008-06-10/l-impuissance-de-benzema/921/0/251859 | archive-date = 17 November 2013 | url-status = dead }}</ref> The newspaper also cited his lack of international experience for his subdued performance. In the team's next group game against the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]], Benzema played no part in the 4\u20131 defeat.<ref>{{cite news |title=Netherlands 4\u20131 France: Dutch master class |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=232269&cc=5901 |work=ESPN |date=13 June 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2009}}</ref> He returned to the team in its final group game against [[Italy national football team|Italy]] and was given a place in the starting lineup.<ref>{{cite news |title=Italy expose French frailties |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/international/2303492/Euro-2008-Italy-expose-French-frailties.html |work=The Telegraph | author=Winter, Henry|date=18 June 2008 |accessdate=25 June 2009 |location=London}}</ref> However, France lost 2\u20130 and were eliminated from the competition.<ref>{{Cite news | url = http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/euro2012/history/season=2008/round=15093/match=300703/index.html | title = France sunk as Italy grab lifeline | date = 17 June 2008 | work = [[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] | accessdate = 6 May 2012 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131116004203/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/euro2012/history/season=2008/round=15093/match=300703/index.html | archivedate = 16 November 2013 | df = dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2008, Benzema, among several other young players in the team, was accused of being insolent during the team's campaign at the European Championship. The accusation came from international teammate [[William Gallas]] who inserted the charge in his autobiography. Though most of Gallas' accusations were directed at Nasri,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/outspoken-gallas-loses-captaincy-1029711.html|title=Outspoken Gallas loses captaincy |date=22 November 2008 |work=The Independent |location=UK|accessdate=19 March 2011 |first=Jason |last=Burt}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mirrorfootball.co.uk/news/Arsenal-s-Samir-Nasri-reopens-his-feud-with-William-Gallas-article628345.html|title=Nasri hits back at Gallas \"rubbish\" |date=13 November 2010|work=Daily Mirror |location=UK|accessdate=8 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mirrorfootball.co.uk/opinion/columnists/steve-stammers/Samir-Nasri-s-brilliance-is-spoiled-by-his-petulance-at-spurning-handshake-with-Tottenham-s-William-Gallas-before-North-London-derby-Steve-Stammers-column-article634963.html|title=Why Nasri's brilliance is spoiled by his petulance|date=24 November 2010|work=Daily Mirror |location=UK|accessdate=19 April 2011}}</ref> during the competition, it was reported by newspaper ''[[Le Parisien]]'' that several of the national team players described Benzema as \"arrogant\" and that the striker was scolded by [[midfielder]] [[Claude Makelele]] following the team's loss to the Netherlands.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.eurosport.fr/football/euro-2008/2008/un-malaise-benzema_sto1606114/story.shtml | title = Un malaise Benzema? | date = 16 June 2008 | work=[[Eurosport]] | accessdate =6 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref>\n\n====2010 World Cup====\nDespite the reports from after Euro 2008, Benzema remained a regular in the team and, ahead of [[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification|qualification]] for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]], switched to the number ten shirt after previously wearing the number nine.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.lyoncapitale.fr/Journal/univers/Sport/Football/Bleus-Benzema-pique-le-neme10-a-Govou/%28language%29/fre-FR | archive-url = https://archive.today/20120903125114/http://www.lyoncapitale.fr/Journal/univers/Sport/Football/Bleus-Benzema-pique-le-neme10-a-Govou/(language)/fre-FR | url-status = dead | archive-date = 3 September 2012 | title = Benzema pique le n\u00e8me10 \u00e0 Govou | date = 9 October 2008 | work = Lyon Capitale | accessdate = 7 May 2012 | language = French }}</ref> In the team's first match following its elimination from Euro 2008, Benzema scored a goal in a 3\u20132 friendly win over [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]] in [[Gothenburg]].<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.fff.fr/servfff/fiche_joueur_new/match.php?id_match=1244 | title = Sweden v. France Match Report | date = 20 August 2008 | work=[[French Football Federation]] | accessdate =6 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref> Two months later, he scored another goal in a 3\u20131 victory against [[Tunisia national football team|Tunisia]] at the [[Stade de France]].<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.fff.fr/servfff/fiche_joueur_new/match.php?id_match=1248 | title = France v. Tunisia Match Report | date = 14 October 2008 | work=[[French Football Federation]] | accessdate =6 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref> On 5 June 2009, Benzema converted the only goal of the match, a penalty shot, in a 1\u20130 win over [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]] at the [[Stade de Gerland]], his home stadium.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.fff.fr/servfff/fiche_joueur_new/match.php?id_match=1254 | title = France v. Turkey Match Report | date = 5 June 2009 | work=[[French Football Federation]] | accessdate =6 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref> He scored his first World Cup qualification goals in victories over the Faroe Islands and Austria in October 2009. His cap against Austria would be his last of the Domenech era as he failed to make France's preliminary 30-man squad for the World Cup. Domenech cited Benzema's struggle for form with his new club Real Madrid, rather than his alleged involvement in a sex scandal as his reason for leaving the striker out.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5itJ3Hn0pud8Aw7U5R1rmJcY3Qq_AD9FKS8M00|title=Benzema left out of France's World Cup squad|first=Samuel|last=Petrequin|agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=11 May 2010}}</ref> Prior to the list being unveiled, Benzema informed ''Radio Monte Carlo'' that if he was not selected he would be \"very disappointed, but not killed\" and \"I will support the France team no matter what\".<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.rmcsport.fr/editorial/110654/benzema-decu-mais-pas-abattu-si-je-n-y-suis-pas/ | title = Benzema: \"D\u00e9\u00e7u mais pas abattu si je n\u2019y suis pas\" | date = 11 May 2010 | work=[[Radio Monte Carlo]] | accessdate =6 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref>\n\n====Euro 2012====\n[[File:Karim Benzema Euro 2012 vs Sweden 01.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Benzema playing for France at [[UEFA Euro 2012]].]]\nFollowing the World Cup, Benzema returned to the national team under the reign of new coach [[Laurent Blanc]]. Blanc, an admirer of Benzema, sought to build the attack around the striker and, after going almost a year without representing France, Benzema made his return to the team in its 2\u20131 defeat to [[Norway national football team|Norway]] in [[Oslo]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Laurent Blanc: Benzema is 'not used to working' |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=828433&sec=euro2012&cc=5901 |work=[[ESPN]] |date=30 September 2010 |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Norway sink France thanks to Huseklepp double |url=https://af.reuters.com/article/sportsNews/idAFJOE67B04520100812 |work=[[Reuters]] |date=12 August 2010 |accessdate=13 December 2011}}</ref> Alongside Gourcuff, Benzema led the team in scoring in [[UEFA Euro 2012 qualifying Group D|qualifying]] for [[UEFA Euro 2012]] netting three. He scored his three goals in wins over [[Bosnia and Herzegovina national football team|Bosnia and Herzegovina]], [[Luxembourg national football team|Luxembourg]], and [[Albania national football team|Albania]].<ref>{{cite news |title=France and Blanc up and running in Sarajevo |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=2012/matches/round=15171/match=2002090/postmatch/report/index.html |work=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |date=7 September 2010 |accessdate=13 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema and Gourcuff keep France flying |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=2012/matches/round=15171/match=2002084/postmatch/report/index.html |work=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |date=12 October 2010 |accessdate=13 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=France squeeze past Albania to stay top |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=2012/matches/round=15171/match=2002100/postmatch/report/index.html |work=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] |date=7 September 2011 |accessdate=13 December 2011}}</ref> On 17 November 2010, Benzema scored the opening goal in France's 2\u20131 win over [[England national football team|England]] at [[Wembley Stadium]].<ref>{{cite news |title=France too good for England in Wembley friendly |url=http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/17112010/2/france-good-england-wembley-friendly.html |work=[[Yahoo! Sports]] |date=17 November 2010 |accessdate=13 December 2011}}</ref> In the team's next match against [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] in February 2011, he scored the only goal for France in a 1\u20130 win.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/international-friendlies/8315057/France-1-Brazil-0-match-report.html | title = France 1 Brazil 0: match report |date= 9 February 2011 | accessdate =13 December 2011 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |location=UK}}</ref> After appearing regularly in qualifying for UEFA Euro 2012, on 29 May 2012, Benzema was named to the squad to participate in the competition.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/international/yoann-gourcuff-omitted-as-france-announce-euro-2012-squad-7800136.html|title=Yoann Gourcuff omitted as France announce Euro 2012 squad|date=29 May 2012 |work=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=3 June 2012}}</ref> On 5 June, in the team's final warm-up friendly ahead of the European Championship, Benzema scored two goals in a 4\u20130 shutout win over [[Estonia national football team|Estonia]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/sns-rt-uk-soccer-friendly-francebre854193-20120605,0,7372040.story|title=Benzema, Ribery shine as France thrashed Estonia|publisher=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=5 June 2012|accessdate=5 June 2012|work=|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130102044447/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-06-05/sports/sns-rt-uk-soccer-friendly-francebre854193-20120605_1_estonia-karim-benzema-laurent-blanc|archive-date=2 January 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> At UEFA Euro 2012, Benzema started the team's opening match against England, which ended in a 1\u20131 draw.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/18076341|title=France 1 England 1|date=11 June 2012|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 June 2012}}</ref> In the team's ensuing group stage match against the Ukraine, he assisted on both team goals in a 2\u20130 win.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/06/16/sports/soccer/euro-2012-after-rain-delay-france-shuts-out-ukraine.html|title=After Rain Delay, France Shuts Out Ukraine|publisher=[[New York Times]] |date= 15 June 2012 |accessdate=17 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n====2014 World Cup====\nOn 11 October 2013, Benzema scored his first goal for the France national team since June 2012 in a friendly against [[Australia national association football team|Australia]], thus ending a scoring drought for his national team which had lasted 1,222 minutes. In that match played at the [[Parc des Princes]] stadium in [[Paris]], which France won 6\u20130, Benzema scored France's sixth and final goal in the 50th minute after turning home [[Franck Rib\u00e9ry]]'s left-wing cross.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-us/match/124721/france-vs-australia/report?|title=France 6\u20130 Australia: Benzema breaks goal drought in friendly drubbing|date=11 October 2013|publisher=www.goal.com}}</ref> In the second leg of the [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification&nbsp;\u2013 UEFA Second Round|2014 World Cup qualification play-off]] against [[Ukraine national football team|Ukraine]] held on 19 November 2013 at the Stade de France, Benzema scored France's second goal in the 34th minute to level the aggregate score at 2\u20132. Benzema scored his goal when he side-footed home after a huge scramble in the Ukrainian penalty box, although he was shown on television replays to be offside by almost one metre when the ball took a final touch off [[Mathieu Valbuena]]'s chest. Benzema had four minutes earlier been denied a legitimate goal, the offside flag wrongly raised when he turned in Rib\u00e9ry's low cross into the net with his torso a metre from the Ukrainian goal-line. Ukraine had won the first leg of the play-off 2\u20130 in [[Kiev]] just four days earlier. France would eventually win the second leg 3\u20130 to advance to the 2014 World Cup finals in [[Brazil]] with a 3\u20132 aggregate scoreline.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/live/match/304251/report|title=World Cup Qualifiers: France revival sinks Ukraine 3\u20130|date=20 November 2013|publisher=Sky Sports}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 June 2014, Benzema was named in France's squad for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]], making his debut in the tournament.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/france/10810384/France-World-Cup-2014-squad.html|title=France World Cup 2014 squad|date=6 June 2014|accessdate=16 June 2014|work=The Telegraph}}</ref> In the team's first match, a 3\u20130 win against [[Honduras national football team|Honduras]] in [[Porto Alegre]] on 15 June, he scored a goal in each half, the first from a [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kick]]. He also assisted the team's second goal when his shot rebounded off the post and was fumbled over the goal-line by Honduran goalkeeper [[Noel Valladares]] for an own goal, the first World Cup goal given by [[goal-line technology]].<ref>{{cite news|title=France 3\u20130 Honduras|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25285092|accessdate=15 June 2014|work=[[BBC Sport]]|date=15 June 2014}}</ref> He later added a third goal sealing France's 3\u20130 victory against Honduras. He was named by [[FIFA]] as man of the match for his performance.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/matches/round=255931/match=300186496/statistics.html|title=France 3\u20130 Honduras|date=16 June 2014|accessdate=16 June 2014|work=FIFA}}</ref> In the second group fixture, he scored and had a penalty saved in a 5\u20132 defeat of [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]], as ''Les Bleus'' all but secured qualification to the [[2014 FIFA World Cup knockout stage|knockout stage]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/25285207|title=Switzerland 2\u20135 France|date=20 June 2014|accessdate=21 June 2014|work=BBC}}</ref> France were later knocked out by [[Germany national football team|Germany]] in the quarter-final stage of the tournament.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/jul/04/france-germany-world-cup-2014-quarter-final-match-report|title = Germany reach World Cup semi-finals as Mats Hummels header sinks France|date = 4 July 2014|accessdate = 18 February 2015|website = The Guardian|publisher = |last = Hytner|first = David}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/world-cup/10940667/France-vs-Germany-World-Cup-2014-live.html|title = France vs Germany, World Cup 2014|date = 4 July 2014|accessdate = 18 February 2015|website = The Telegraph|publisher = |last = Tyers|first = Alan}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/28051800|title = Germany became the first nation to reach four consecutive World Cup semi-finals as Mats Hummels' early header proved enough to see them past France at the Maracana.|date = 4 July 2014|accessdate = 18 February 2015|website = BBC Sport|publisher = |last = Ornstein|first = David}}</ref>\n\n====Euro 2016 and 2018 World Cup====\nOn 13 April 2016, French Football Federation announced that Benzema would not be picked for [[UEFA Euro 2016|Euro 2016]] tournament on home soil.<ref name=\"Benzema axed from France\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2016/04/13/karim-benzema-axed-from-france-euro-2016-squad/|title=Karim Benzema axed from France Euro 2016 squad|work=The Telegraph|date=13 April 2016|accessdate=13 April 2016}}</ref> He responded on 1 June 2016 in ''Marca'', in an interview entitled 'Benzema: \"Deschamps folded due to pressure from France's racist element\"'.<ref>[http://www.marca.com/futbol/real-madrid/2016/06/01/574dfc86e2704e5c1d8b463c.html marca.com: 'Benzema: \"Deschamps se pliega a la presi\u00f3n de una parte racista de Francia\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161202195036/http://www.marca.com/futbol/real-madrid/2016/06/01/574dfc86e2704e5c1d8b463c.html |date=2 December 2016}}, 1 June 2016</ref>\n\nBenzema was also left off the roster for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018 World Cup]] in Russia.<ref>https://the18.com/soccer-news/karim-benzema-france-world-cup-squad</ref> Directing his frustration at FFF president [[No\u00ebl Le Gra\u00ebt]], Benzema later tweeted: \"Mr Le Gra\u00ebt, with all due respect, you've lost an opportunity to remain silent. I've discovered your true face, and this isn't the one that said he appreciated me and wouldn't discuss the subject of team selections!\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.as.com/en/2018/05/31/football/1527758335_120289.html|title=Benzema hits back after FFF president backs World Cup omission|last=AS|first=Diario|date=2018-05-31|website=AS.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-15}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, Benzema replied to Le Gra\u00ebt's comments that his career with France was over, by saying: \"If you think I'm done, let me play with one of the other countries I am eligible for and we'll see\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/real-madrid/2019/11/16/5dd05926268e3eeb4d8b45ff.html|title=Benzema would have to lose French nationality to play for Algeria|website=Marca|date=16 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\nA creative, skillful, quick, agile, and prolific forward, who is good in the air and capable of playing off the shoulders of the last defender,<ref name=\"Karim Benzema to Arsenal\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/arsenal/11796162/Karim-Benzema-to-Arsenal-Why-Real-Madrid-striker-would-be-a-perfect-signing.html|title=Karim Benzema to Arsenal: Why Real Madrid striker would be a perfect signing|publisher=The Telegraph|author1=Alistair Tweedale|date=11 August 2015|accessdate=2 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marca.com/2013/07/24/en/football/real_madrid/1374652949.html|title=Benzema's big break|publisher=Marca|author1=Ulises S\u00e1nchez-Flor|date=24 July 2013|accessdate=2 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/manchester-united-prepare-swoop-real-madrid-striker-karim-benzema-1503074|title=Manchester United prepare swoop for Real Madrid striker Karim Benzema|publisher=International Business Times|author1=Arunava Ray|date=27 May 2015|accessdate=2 May 2016}}</ref> Benzema has been described as an \"immensely talented [[Forward (association football)#Striker|striker]]\" who is \"strong and powerful\" and \"a potent finisher from inside the box\" with either foot, as well as his head, despite being naturally right footed.<ref name=Bio/><ref name=\"Karim Benzema to Arsenal\"/> An atypical [[Squad number (association football)|number 9]], although he is usually deployed as a [[Forward (association football)#Centre-forward|centre forward]], and can operate as an out-and-out striker, Benzema is also capable of playing in several other offensive positions, and has been used on the [[Forward (association football)#Winger|wing]], or even [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|behind the main striker]] as a [[Forward (association football)#Second striker|number 10 or deep-lying forward]]. In addition to his goalscoring, Benzema is known for his willingness and ability to drop into deeper or wider positions, and either link-up play with midfielders, or use his strength and technical ability to hold up the ball with his back to goal to provide [[Assist (football)|assists]] for teammates, courtesy of his vision, creativity, passing, and eye for the final ball; because of his playing style, he has been described as a \"nine and a half\" in the media.<ref name=\"Karim Benzema to Arsenal\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/analysed-karim-benzema-more-important-everybody-thought#:WC7ZOI2ok4fR0A|title=Analysed: Karim Benzema is more important than everybody thought|work=FourFourTwo|author1=Kiyan Sobhani|date=25 February 2016|accessdate=2 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=return>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.us/club/real-madrid/86/blog/post/2581789/real-madrid-karim-benzema-return-to-help-cohesion-of-attack|title=Benzema's return will bring cohesion back to Real Madrid attack|publisher=ESPN FC|author1=Rob Train|date=25 August 2015|accessdate=2 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Karim Benzema is the perfect striker for Real\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.us/spanish-primera-divisi%C3%A3%C2%B3n/15/blog/post/2050897/real-madrid-should-stick-with-karim-benzema-up-front|title=Karim Benzema is the perfect striker for Real, plus praise for Villarreal|publisher=ESPN FC|author1=Graham Hunter|date=23 September 2014|accessdate=2 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marca.com/en/2015/09/17/en/football/real_madrid/1442480053.html|title=Benzema, the silent killer|publisher=Marca|author1=Olivier Mart\u00ednez|date=17 September 2015|accessdate=2 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuttomercatoweb.com/il-volto-nuovo/karim-benzema-l-erede-di-trezeguet-80609|title=Karim Benzema, l'erede di Trezeguet|trans-title=Karim Benzema, Trezeguet's heir|publisher=TuttoMercatoWeb|language=Italian|author1=Giuseppe Di Napoli|date=18 November 2007|accessdate=3 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.marca.com/en/football/real-madrid/2018/08/12/5b6ff5d4e5fdea89608b45e4.html |title=BBA off to impressive start |publisher=Marca |author1=Pablo Polo |date=12 August 2018 |accessdate=2 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.marca.com/en/football/real-madrid/opinion/2018/01/31/5a72335e468aeb9b018b462b.html |title=Benzema, BBC's perfect lubricant |publisher=Marca |author1=Santiago Siguero |date=31 January 2018 |accessdate=2 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nDuring his time at Real Madrid, Benzema has also been praised for his work-rate and tactical intelligence off the ball, as well as his positional sense and attacking movement as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]], which often draws opposition defenders out of position, and in turn he created spaces for [[Cristiano Ronaldo]] to make attacking runs into the centre of the area from the left wing, which essentially sees him acting as a [[Forward (association football)#False 9|false 9]].<ref name=return/><ref name=\"Karim Benzema is the perfect striker for Real\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/players/cristiano-ronaldo/12177090/Cristiano-Ronaldo-takes-aim-at-Real-Madrid-teammates-as-La-Liga-hopes-take-mortal-blow.html|title=Cristiano Ronaldo takes aim at Real Madrid teammates as La Liga hopes take mortal blow|work=The Daily Telegraph|location=London|author1=Ian Hawkey|date=28 February 2016|accessdate=2 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/why-benzema-too-important-leave-real-madrid-season#:rfHxSHexxqfR0A|title=Why Benzema is too important to leave Real Madrid this season|publisher=FourFourTwo|author1=John Robertson|date=28 August 2015|accessdate=2 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.squawka.com/news/karim-benzema-is-the-mvp-of-the-b-b-c/625032|title=Karim Benzema is the real MVP of Real Madrid\u2019s star-studded attack|publisher=www.squawka.com|author1=Muhammad Butt|date=21 March 2016|accessdate=4 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.managingmadrid.com/2018/7/19/17588990/statistical-analysis-should-real-madrid-sign-eden-hazard |title=Statistical Analysis: Should Real Madrid Sign Eden Hazard? |publisher=www.managingmadrid.com |author1=Om Arvind |date=19 July 2018 |accessdate=2 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nKarim Benzema was born in the city of [[Lyon]], France to [[Algerians in France|French nationals of Algerian descent]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Benzema, le ph\u00e9nom\u00e8ne qui r\u00e9veille le foot |url=http://www.lepoint.fr/actualites-societe/2008-02-07/benzema-le-phenomene-qui-reveille-le-foot/920/0/222742 |work=Le Point |date=7 February 2008 |accessdate=14 July 2009 |language=French |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304041607/http://www.lepoint.fr/actualites-societe/2008-02-07/benzema-le-phenomene-qui-reveille-le-foot/920/0/222742 |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title = Benzema, l'arme fatale de l'OL| url = http://www.maxifoot.fr/articles/4383/index.htm| work=Maxifoot| language = French | date = 19 September 2007| accessdate =19 June 2009}}</ref> As a practicing [[Muslim]], he observes fasting during the Islamic holy month of [[Ramadan]].<ref name=\"goal\">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/12/spain/2009/08/22/1454134/ramadan-fasting-for-real-madrid-trio-lassana-benzema-and|title=Ramadan Fasting For Real Madrid Trio Lassana, Benzema and Diarra|publisher= Dadyal Online |date=22 August 2009|accessdate=31 December 2012}}</ref> His grandfather, Da Lakehal Benzema, lived in the village of [[Tigzirt]], located in the northern town of [[Beni Djellil]] in [[Algeria]] before migrating to Lyon, where he eventually settled in the 1950s.<ref name=\"benzema_background\">{{cite news | title = Sur les traces de Karim Benzema | url = http://www.djazairess.com/fr/elwatan/94450 | work=DjaZairess | date = 13 May 2008 | accessdate =6 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref> Benzema's father, Hafid, was born in Tigzirt, while his mother, Wahida Djebbara, was born and raised in Lyon; her family originated from [[Oran]]. Benzema is the third youngest in the family and grew up with eight other siblings in [[Bron]], an eastern suburb of Lyon.<ref name=\"benzema_background\"/> His younger brothers Gressy and Sabri are also footballers.<ref>{{cite news | title = Sur les traces de Karim Benzema | url = http://www.20minutes.fr/article/648150/sports-a-vaulx-en-velin-gressy-benzema-joueur-comme-autre | work=20 Minutes | date = 6 January 2011 | accessdate =6 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref> The former currently plies his trade at the amateur level with Vaulx-le-Velin in the Division d'Honneur, the sixth division of French football, while the latter plays in the youth academy of a club in the family's hometown of Bron.<ref>{{cite news | title = Vaulx-en-Velin&nbsp;\u2013 Gressy, l'autre Benzema | url = http://fr.fifa.com/worldfootball/clubfootball/news/newsid=1368589.html | work = [[FIFA|F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association]] | date = 21 January 2011 | accessdate = 6 May 2012 | language = French | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120213165139/http://fr.fifa.com/worldfootball/clubfootball/news/newsid=1368589.html | archivedate = 13 February 2012 | df = dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Sabri Benzema, plus fort que son fr\u00e8re? | url = http://www.footmercato.net/ligue1/sabri-benzema-plus-fort-que-son-frere_38053 | work=FootMercato| date = 9 August 2009 | accessdate =6 May 2012 | language = French}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 February 2014, his daughter M\u00e9lia was born.<ref>{{cite news | title = Karim Benzema le footballeur est devenu papa | url = http://www.public.fr/News/Exclu-Public-Karim-Benzema-le-footballeur-est-devenu-papa-496902 | work=Public | date = 4 February 2014 | accessdate =25 November 2014 | language = French}}</ref> On 5 May 2017, his son Ibrahim was born.<ref>http://www.leparisien.fr/laparisienne/actualites/people/karim-benzema-est-papa-pour-la-deuxieme-fois-26-05-2017-6985572.php</ref>\n\n===Controversies and legal issues===\nOn 6 December 2006, he told [[Radio Monte Carlo|RMC]] about his possible selection for the [[Algeria national football team|Algerian team]]: \"It's my parents' country, it's in my heart. But good after sporting, it's true that I will play in French team. I will be always present for the French team. Then it's more for the sporting side, because Algeria is my country, here, my parents come from there. After, France ... It's more sporty, that's it.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Les citations d\u00e9form\u00e9es de Karim Benzema sur l\u2019\u00e9quipe de France et l\u2019Alg\u00e9rie|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/les-decodeurs/article/2016/06/02/les-citations-deformees-de-karim-benzema_4931167_4355770.html|website=Le Monde.fr|accessdate=20 May 2018|language=fr|date=10 June 2016}}</ref> Benzema drew some criticism for these comments, as well as for his reluctance to sing the French national anthem, \"[[La Marseillaise]]\", before each match with the national team.<ref>{{cite news|language=French|title=Karim Benzema : \"On ne va pas me forcer \u00e0 chanter La Marseillaise\"|newspaper=[[Le Monde]]|date=19 March 2013|issn=1950-6244|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/sport/article/2013/03/19/karim-benzema-on-ne-va-pas-me-forcer-a-chanter-la-marseillaise_1850657_3242.html|accessdate=21 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|language=French|author=Alexandre Boudet|title=Karim Benzema explique pourquoi il ne chantait pas la Marseillaise|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.fr/2018/04/17/karim-benzema-explique-pourquoi-il-ne-chantait-pas-la-marseillaise_a_23413381/|website=[[HuffPost]]|date=17 April 2018|accessdate=17 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 April 2010, it was first reported by French television channel [[M6 (TV channel)|M6]] that four members of the French national team were being investigated for their roles as clients in a prostitute ring operated inside of a Paris nightclub, with some of the women possibly being underage or transgender. The players were eventually revealed to be Franck Rib\u00e9ry, Sidney Govou, Hatem Ben Arfa and Benzema.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.rmc.fr/editorial/108424/quatre-bleus-impliques-dans-une-affaire-de-moeurs/ | title = Quatre Bleus impliqu\u00e9s dans une affaire de moeurs? | date = 18 April 2010 | accessdate =20 April 2010 | publisher=[[Radio Monte Carlo|RMC]] |language = French}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/breves2010/20100418_224418_ribery-parmi-les-temoins-entendus.html | title=Rib\u00e9ry parmi les t\u00e9moins entendus | date=18 April 2010 | accessdate=20 April 2010 | publisher=[[L'Equipe]] | language=French | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100421061245/https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/breves2010/20100418_224418_ribery-parmi-les-temoins-entendus.html | archivedate=21 April 2010 | df=dmy-all}}</ref> Benzema was alleged to have had a sexual rendezvous with a prostitute when she was 16 years of age, an act Benzema denied through his lawyer.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/world-cup/story/_/id/777702/ce/uk/?campaign=rss&source=soccernet&cc=5901&ver=us | title = Lawyer denies Benzema used prostitute | date = 26 April 2010 | accessdate =1 May 2010 | publisher=[[ESPN]] | language = French}}</ref> On 20 July, Benzema was questioned by Paris police and indicted on the charge of \"solicitation of a minor prostitute\".<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/jul/20/franck-ribery-karim-benzema-police | title = Franck Rib\u00e9ry and Karim Benzema held in prostitution investigation | date = 20 July 2010 | accessdate =20 July 2010 |work=The Guardian |location=UK | first=Lizzy | last=Davies}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.francefootball.fr/FF/breves2010/20100720_180924_ribery-mis-en-examen.html | title=Rib\u00e9ry et Benzema mis en examen | date=21 July 2010 | accessdate=20 July 2010 | publisher=France Football | language=French | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100722094516/http://www.francefootball.fr/FF/breves2010/20100720_180924_ribery-mis-en-examen.html | archivedate=22 July 2010 | df=dmy-all}}</ref> In November 2011, prosecutors asked for the cases against Rib\u00e9ry and Benzema to be dropped, saying that the players were not aware that the escort, identified as [[Zahia Dehar]], was 16 years old.<ref>{{cite web|title=French prosecutors accept that Ribery did not know prostitute was a minor |author=|date=19 November 2011|work=France 24|url=http://www.france24.com/en/20111119-football-ribery-prostitute-minor-case-benzema-france-paris-justice}}</ref> However, the case did go on to trial. The first hearing was held in June 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ribery and Benzema on trial on underage prostitute charges in Paris |author=|date=19 June 2013|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2343774/Franck-Ribery-Karim-Benzema-court-underage-prostitute-charges.html}}</ref> In January 2014, the judge in the case dropped the charges against both Ribery and Benzema saying there was lack of sufficient evidence that the pair knew the prostitutes were underaged.<ref>{{cite web|title=French court drops Ribery and Benzema prostitution case |author=|date=30 January 2014|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-25964763}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 November 2015, Benzema was arrested by French police for his alleged part in [[blackmailing]] fellow France international player [[Mathieu Valbuena]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Willsher|first1=Kim|title=Karim Benzema arrested by police in sex-tape blackmail case|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/nov/04/karim-benzema-arrested-sex-tape-blackmail|accessdate=4 November 2015|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=4 November 2015}}</ref> During the investigation over the blackmail plot, French Prime Minister [[Manuel Valls]] stated, \"A great athlete should be exemplary. If he is not, he has no place in the France team. There are so many kids, so many youngsters in our suburbs that relate to great athletes. They wear the blue jersey, the colours of France, which are so important in these moments.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/34974358 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=1 December 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151204081832/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/34974358 |archivedate= 4 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Pour-manuel-valls-karim-benzema-n-a-pas-sa-place-en-equipe-de-france/612424 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=1 December 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161117211727/http://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Pour-manuel-valls-karim-benzema-n-a-pas-sa-place-en-equipe-de-france/612424 |archivedate=17 November 2016}}</ref> On 10 December 2015, the president of the FFF [[No\u00ebl Le Gra\u00ebt]] announced the provisional suspension of the striker from [[France national football team|French team]] until new development of the affair.<ref>{{cite web|language=French|url=http://sport24.lefigaro.fr/football/equipe-de-france/actualites/benzema-n-est-plus-selectionnable-en-equipe-de-france-782864|title=Benzema n'est plus s\u00e9lectionnable en \u00e9quipe de France|author=Romain Schneider|date=10 December 2015|website=[[Le Figaro]]|accessdate=10 December 2015}}</ref> On 17 February 2016, the judicial review was lifted by the investigating judge who allowed Karim Benzema to get in touch again with Mathieu Valbuena. On 11 July 2017, the [[Court of Cassation (France)|Court of Cassation]] issued a judgment in which it invalidated a decision of the Court of Appeal of Versailles, which had validated the procedure by which Benzema had been indicted for complicity of attempted blackmail.<ref>{{cite web|title=Affaire de la \" sextape \" de Valbuena : une victoire judiciaire pour Karim Benzema|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/police-justice/article/2017/07/12/affaire-de-la-sextape-de-valbuena-une-victoire-judiciaire-pour-karim-benzema_5159490_1653578.html|website=Le Monde.fr|accessdate=20 May 2018|language=fr|date=12 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|8 March 2020}}<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=40900 \"Karim Benzema \u2013 Football Stats\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305224416/http://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=40900 |date=5 March 2016}}. Soccer base. Retrieved 10 June 2014</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Division\n!colspan=\"2\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup<sup>1</sup>\n!colspan=\"2\"|Europe<sup>2</sup>\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other<sup>3</sup>\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Olympique Lyonnais Reserves and Academy|Lyon B]]\n|2004\u201305\n|Campionnat National \n|11||10||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||11||10\n|-\n|2005\u201306\n|Campionnat National \n|9||5||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||9||5\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |Total\n!20!!15!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!20!!15\n|-\n|rowspan=\"6\"|[[Olympique Lyonnais|Lyon]]\n|[[2004\u201305 Ligue 1|2004\u201305]]\n|Ligue 1\n|6||0||0||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||6||0\n|-\n|[[2005\u201306 Ligue 1|2005\u201306]]\n|Ligue 1\n|13||1||2||2||1||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||16||4\n|-\n|[[2006\u201307 Olympique Lyonnais season|2006\u201307]]\n|Ligue 1\n|21||5||3||1||3||2||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||27||8\n|-\n|[[2007\u201308 Olympique Lyonnais season|2007\u201308]]\n|Ligue 1\n|36||20||9||7||7||4||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||52||31\n|-\n|[[2008\u201309 Olympique Lyonnais season|2008\u201309]]\n|Ligue 1\n|36||17||3||1||8||5||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||47||23\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |Total\n!112!!43!!17!!11!!19!!12!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!148!!66\n|-\n|rowspan=\"12\"|[[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]]\n|[[2009\u201310 Real Madrid C.F. season|2009\u201310]]\n|La Liga\n|27||8||1||0||5||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u