12 players]]\n[[Category:2014 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:French expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:French expatriate sportspeople in Spain]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Spain]]\n", "name_user": "109.79.171.134", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Fixed vandalism)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karim_Benzema"}
{"title_page": "Pharmakos", "text_new": "{{more footnotes|date=October 2014}}\n{{Ancient Greek religion|expanded=practices}}\nA '''pharmak\u00f3s''' ({{lang-el|\u03c6\u03b1\u03c1\u03bc\u03b1\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2}}, plural '''''pharmakoi''''') in [[Ancient Greek religion]] was the ritualistic sacrifice or exile of a human [[scapegoat]] or victim.\n\n==Ritual==\nA slave, a cripple or a criminal was chosen and expelled from the community at times of disaster (famine, invasion or plague) or at times of calendrical crisis. It was believed that this would bring about purification. On the first day of the [[Thargelia]], a festival of [[Apollo]] at Athens, two men, the ''Pharmakoi'', were led out as if to be sacrificed as an expiation.\n\nSome scholia state that ''pharmakoi'' were actually sacrificed (thrown from a cliff or burned), but many modern scholars reject this, arguing that the earliest source for the ''pharmakos'' (the iambic satirist [[Hipponax]]) shows the ''pharmakoi'' being beaten and stoned, but not executed. A more plausible explanation would be that sometimes they were executed and sometimes not, depending on the attitude of the victim. For instance, a deliberate unrepentant murderer would most likely be put to death.{{citation needed|date=June 2014}}\n\nIn ''Aesop in Delphi'' (1961), Anton Wiechers discussed the parallels between the legendary biography of [[Aesop]] (in which he is unjustly tried and executed by the Delphians) and the ''pharmakos'' ritual. For example, Aesop is grotesquely deformed, as was the ''pharmakos'' in some traditions; and Aesop was thrown from a cliff, as was the pharmakos in some traditions.\n\nGregory Nagy, in ''Best of the Achaeans'' (1979), compared Aesop's ''pharmakos'' death to the \"worst\" of the Achaeans in the ''[[Iliad]]'', Thersites. More recently, both Daniel Ogden, ''The Crooked Kings of Ancient Greece'' (1997) and [[Todd Compton]], ''Victim of the Muses: Poet as Scapegoat, Warrior and Hero'' (2006) examine poet ''pharmakoi''. Compton surveys important poets who were exiled, executed or suffered unjust trials, either in history, legend or Greek or [[Indo-European myth]].\n\n==Modern interpretations<!--'Plato's Pharmacy' redirects here-->==\n[[Walter Burkert]] and [[Ren\u00e9 Girard]] have written influential modern interpretations of the ''pharmakos'' rite. Burkert shows that humans were sacrificed or expelled after being fed well, and, according to some sources, their ashes were scattered to the ocean. This was a purification ritual, a form of societal [[catharsis]].<ref>Walter Burkert. ''Greek Religion'', p. 82.</ref> Girard likewise discusses the connection between catharsis, sacrifice, and purification.<ref>Ren\u00e9 Girard. ''I See Satan Fall Like Lightning'', pp. 37\u201338, 51, 78, 131</ref> Some scholars have connected the practice of [[ostracism]], in which a prominent politician was exiled from Athens after a vote using pottery pieces, with the ''pharmakos'' custom. However, the ostracism exile was only for a fixed time, as opposed to the finality of the ''pharmakos'' execution or expulsion.\n\nPharmakos is also used as a vital term in Derridean [[deconstruction]]. In his essay \"'''Plato's Pharmacy'''\"<!--boldface per WP:R#PLA-->,<ref>''Dissemination'', translated by Barbara Johnson, Chicago, University of Chicago Press, 1981</ref> [[Derrida]] deconstructs several texts by [[Plato]], such as ''[[Phaedrus (dialogue)|Phaedrus]]'', and reveals the inter-connection between the word chain ''pharmakeia\u2013pharmakon\u2013pharmakeus'' and the notably absent word ''pharmakos''. In doing so, he attacks the boundary between inside and outside, declaring that the outside (pharmakos, never uttered by Plato) is always-already present right behind the inside (''pharmakeia\u2013pharmakon\u2013pharmakeus''). As a concept, Pharmakos can be said to be related to other Derridian terms such as \"[[Trace (deconstruction)|Trace]]\".\n\n==See also==\n* [[Pharmacy#Etymology|Etymology of ''pharmacy'']]\n* [[Modes of persuasion]], which include [[ethos]], [[pathos]],[[logos]] & [[kairos]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*[http://www.rug.nl/Bibliotheek/catalogiBestanden/elekPubRUG/keur/11Bremmer Bremmer, Jan N.], [http://keur.eldoc.ub.rug.nl/wetenschappers/11/6576/ \"Scapegoat Rituals in Ancient Greece\"], ''Harvard Studies in Classical Philology'', Vol. 87. (1983), pp.&nbsp;299\u2013320.\n*Burkert, Walter, ''Greek Religion'', Cambridge, MA: Harvard University Press, 1985.\n*Burkert, Walter, ''Structure and History in Greek Mythology''. Berkeley: University of California Press, 1979, 59-77.\n*Calcagnetti, Daniel J., \"Neuropharmacology: From Cellular Receptors and Neurotransmitter Synthesis to Neuropathology & Drug Addiction\", First Edition, 2006.\n*[[Todd Compton|Compton, Todd]], [http://toddmcompton.com/pharmakos.htm \u201cThe Pharmakos Ritual: Testimonia.\u201d]\n*Compton, Todd, ''Victim of the Muses: Poet as Scapegoat, Warrior and Hero in Greco-Roman and Indo-European Myth and History''. Washington, D.C.: Center for Hellenic Studies/Harvard University Press, 2006.\n*Derrida, Jacques, \"Dissemination\", translated by Barbara Johnson, Chicago, University of Chicago Press, 1981.\n*Fiore, Robert L., [https://www.jstor.org/stable/473965 \"Alarcon's El dueno de las estrellas: Hero and Pharmakos\"], ''Hispanic Review'', Vol. 61, No. 2, Earle Homage Issue (Spring, 1993), pp.&nbsp;185\u2013199.\n*Frazer, James. ''The Golden Bough. Part VI. The Scapegoat'', pp.&nbsp;252ff.\n*Girard, Ren\u00e9. ''The Scapegoat.'' Trans. Y. Freccero. Baltimore, 1986.\n*Harrison, Jane Ellen, ''Epilegomena to the Study of Greek Religion'', 1921.\n*Harrison, Jane Ellen, ''Prolegomena to the Study of Greek Religion'', 1908.\n*Harrison, Jane Ellen, ''Themis: a Study of the Social Origin of Greek Religion'', 1921.\n*Hirayama, Koji, [http://www.bun.kyoto-u.ac.jp/classics/CSJ/49_2001.html#hirayama ''Stoning in the Pharmakos Ritual''], [http://www.bun.kyoto-u.ac.jp/classics/CSJ/jcs.html Journal of Classical Studies], XLIX(2001), Classical Society of Japan, [[Kyoto University]].\n*Hughes, Dennis, ''Human Sacrifice in Ancient Greece'', London 1991, pp.&nbsp;139\u2013165.\n*Nagy, Gregory. [http://www.press.jhu.edu/books/nagy/BofA.html ''The Best of the Achaeans: Concepts of the Hero in Archaic Greek Poetry.''] The Johns Hopkins University Press, 1979, pp.&nbsp;280\u201390 in print edition.\n*Nilsson, Martin P., [http://www.sacred-texts.com/cla/gpr/index.htm ''Greek Popular Religion''], 1940. See the discussion of the Thargelia in the chapter \u201cRural Customs and Festivals.\u201d\n*Ogden, Daniel, ''The Crooked Kings of Ancient Greece'' London 1997, pp.&nbsp;15\u201346.\n*Parker, Robert, ''Miasma, Pollution and Purification in Early Greek Religion.'' Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1983, pp.&nbsp;24\u201326, 257-280.\n*Rinella, Michael A., ''Pharmakon:  Plato, Drug Culture, and Identity in Ancient Athens''. Lanham, MD:  Lexington Books, 2010, 73-74.\n* Whibley, Leonard, MA, ''A Companion to Greek Studies''. Cambridge University Press.\n*Wiechers, A. ''Aesop in Delphi''. Meisenheim am Glan 1961.\n\n[[Category:Injustice]]\n[[Category:Ancient Greek religion]]\n", "text_old": "{{more footnotes|date=October 2014}}\n{{Ancient Greek religion|expanded=practices}}\nA '''pharmak\u00f3s''' ({{lang-el|\u03c6\u03b1\u03c1\u03bc\u03b1\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2}}, plural '''''pharmakoi''''') in [[Ancient Greek religion]] was the ritualistic sacrifice or exile of a human [[scapegoat]] or victim.\n\n==Ritual==\nA slave, a cripple or a criminal was chosen and expelled from the community at times of disaster (famine, invasion or plague) or at times of calendrical crisis. It was believed that this would bring about purification. On the first day of the [[Thargelia]], a festival of [[Apollo]] at Athens, two men, the ''Pharmakoi'', were led out as if to be sacrificed as an expiation.\n\nSome scholia state that ''pharmakoi'' were actually sacrificed (thrown from a cliff or burned), but many modern scholars reject this, arguing that the earliest source for the ''pharmakos'' (the iambic satirist [[Hipponax]]) shows the ''pharmakoi'' being beaten and stoned, but not executed. A more plausible explanation would be that sometimes they were executed and sometimes not, depending on the attitude of the victim. For instance, a deliberate unrepentant murderer would most likely be put to death.{{citation needed|date=June 2014}}\n\nIn ''Aesop in Delphi'' (1961), Anton Wiechers discussed the parallels between the legendary biography of [[Aesop]] (in which he is unjustly tried and executed by the Delphians) and the ''pharmakos'' ritual. For example, Aesop is grotesquely deformed, as was the ''pharmakos'' in some traditions; and Aesop was thrown from a cliff, as was the pharmakos in some traditions.\n\nGregory Nagy, in ''Best of the Achaeans'' (1979), compared Aesop's ''pharmakos'' death to the \"worst\" of the Achaeans in the ''[[Iliad]]'', Thersites. More recently, both Daniel Ogden, ''The Crooked Kings of Ancient Greece'' (1997) and [[Todd Compton]], ''Victim of the Muses: Poet as Scapegoat, Warrior and Hero'' (2006) examine poet ''pharmakoi''. Compton surveys important poets who were exiled, executed or suffered unjust trials, either in history, legend or Greek or [[Indo-European myth]].\n\n==Modern interpretations<!--'Plato's Pharmacy' redirects here-->==\n[[Walter Burkert]] and [[Ren\u00e9 Girard]] have written influential modern interpretations of the ''pharmakos'' rite. Burkert shows that humans were sacrificed or expelled after being fed well, and, according to some sources, their ashes were scattered to the ocean. This was a purification ritual, a form of societal [[catharsis]].<ref>Walter Burkert. ''Greek Religion'', p. 82.</ref> Girard likewise discusses the connection between catharsis, sacrifice, and purification.<ref>Ren\u00e9 Girard. ''I See Satan Fall Like Lightning'', pp. 37\u201338, 51, 78, 131</ref> Some scholars have connected the practice of [[ostracism]], in which a prominent politician was exiled from Athens after a vote using pottery pieces, with the ''pharmakos'' custom. However, the ostracism exile was only for a fixed time, as opposed to the finality of the ''pharmakos'' execution or expulsion.\n\nPharmakos is also used as a vital term in Derridean [[deconstruction]]. In his essay \"'''Plato's Pharmacy'''\"<!--boldface per WP:R#PLA-->,<ref>''Dissemination'', translated by Barbara Johnson, Chicago, University of Chicago Press, 1981</ref> [[Derrida]] deconstructs several texts by [[Plato]], such as ''[[Phaedrus (dialogue)|Phaedrus]]'', and reveals the inter-connection between the word chain ''pharmakeia\u2013pharmakon\u2013pharmakeus'' and the notably absent word ''pharmakos''. In doing so, he attacks the boundary between inside and outside, declaring that the outside (pharmakos, never uttered by Plato) is always-already present right behind the inside (''pharmakeia\u2013pharmakon\u2013pharmakeus''). As a concept, Pharmakos can be said to be related to other Derridian terms such as \"[[Trace (deconstruction)|Trace]]\".\n\n==See also==\n* [[Pharmacy#Etymology|Etymology of ''pharmacy'']]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*[http://www.rug.nl/Bibliotheek/catalogiBestanden/elekPubRUG/keur/11Bremmer Bremmer, Jan N.], [http://keur.eldoc.ub.rug.nl/wetenschappers/11/6576/ \"Scapegoat Rituals in Ancient Greece\"], ''Harvard Studies in Classical Philology'', Vol. 87. (1983), pp.&nbsp;299\u2013320.\n*Burkert, Walter, ''Greek Religion'', Cambridge, MA: Harvard University Press, 1985.\n*Burkert, Walter, ''Structure and History in Greek Mythology''. Berkeley: University of California Press, 1979, 59-77.\n*Calcagnetti, Daniel J., \"Neuropharmacology: From Cellular Receptors and Neurotransmitter Synthesis to Neuropathology & Drug Addiction\", First Edition, 2006.\n*[[Todd Compton|Compton, Todd]], [http://toddmcompton.com/pharmakos.htm \u201cThe Pharmakos Ritual: Testimonia.\u201d]\n*Compton, Todd, ''Victim of the Muses: Poet as Scapegoat, Warrior and Hero in Greco-Roman and Indo-European Myth and History''. Washington, D.C.: Center for Hellenic Studies/Harvard University Press, 2006.\n*Derrida, Jacques, \"Dissemination\", translated by Barbara Johnson, Chicago, University of Chicago Press, 1981.\n*Fiore, Robert L., [https://www.jstor.org/stable/473965 \"Alarcon's El dueno de las estrellas: Hero and Pharmakos\"], ''Hispanic Review'', Vol. 61, No. 2, Earle Homage Issue (Spring, 1993), pp.&nbsp;185\u2013199.\n*Frazer, James. ''The Golden Bough. Part VI. The Scapegoat'', pp.&nbsp;252ff.\n*Girard, Ren\u00e9. ''The Scapegoat.'' Trans. Y. Freccero. Baltimore, 1986.\n*Harrison, Jane Ellen, ''Epilegomena to the Study of Greek Religion'', 1921.\n*Harrison, Jane Ellen, ''Prolegomena to the Study of Greek Religion'', 1908.\n*Harrison, Jane Ellen, ''Themis: a Study of the Social Origin of Greek Religion'', 1921.\n*Hirayama, Koji, [http://www.bun.kyoto-u.ac.jp/classics/CSJ/49_2001.html#hirayama ''Stoning in the Pharmakos Ritual''], [http://www.bun.kyoto-u.ac.jp/classics/CSJ/jcs.html Journal of Classical Studies], XLIX(2001), Classical Society of Japan, [[Kyoto University]].\n*Hughes, Dennis, ''Human Sacrifice in Ancient Greece'', London 1991, pp.&nbsp;139\u2013165.\n*Nagy, Gregory. [http://www.press.jhu.edu/books/nagy/BofA.html ''The Best of the Achaeans: Concepts of the Hero in Archaic Greek Poetry.''] The Johns Hopkins University Press, 1979, pp.&nbsp;280\u201390 in print edition.\n*Nilsson, Martin P., [http://www.sacred-texts.com/cla/gpr/index.htm ''Greek Popular Religion''], 1940. See the discussion of the Thargelia in the chapter \u201cRural Customs and Festivals.\u201d\n*Ogden, Daniel, ''The Crooked Kings of Ancient Greece'' London 1997, pp.&nbsp;15\u201346.\n*Parker, Robert, ''Miasma, Pollution and Purification in Early Greek Religion.'' Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1983, pp.&nbsp;24\u201326, 257-280.\n*Rinella, Michael A., ''Pharmakon:  Plato, Drug Culture, and Identity in Ancient Athens''. Lanham, MD:  Lexington Books, 2010, 73-74.\n* Whibley, Leonard, MA, ''A Companion to Greek Studies''. Cambridge University Press.\n*Wiechers, A. ''Aesop in Delphi''. Meisenheim am Glan 1961.\n\n[[Category:Injustice]]\n[[Category:Ancient Greek religion]]\n", "name_user": "Timpo", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also:*Modes of persuasion, whic includeethos,pathos,logos,kairos", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pharmakos"}
{"title_page": "Cosmopolis (film)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Cosmopolis\n| image          = Cosmopolis Poster.jpg\n| image_size     = \n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[David Cronenberg]]\n| producer       = David Cronenberg<br />[[Paulo Branco]]<br />Renee Tab<br />[[Martin Katz (producer)|Martin Katz]]\n| screenplay     = David Cronenberg\n| based on       = {{Based on|''[[Cosmopolis (novel)|Cosmopolis]]''|[[Don DeLillo]]}}\n| starring       = [[Robert Pattinson]]<br />[[Paul Giamatti]]<br />[[Samantha Morton]]<br />[[Sarah Gadon]]<br />[[Mathieu Amalric]]<br />[[Juliette Binoche]]<br />[[Jay Baruchel]]<br />[[Kevin Durand]]<!--DO NOT CHANGE THIS CAST, THIS IS ACCORDING TO THE CREDIT BLOCK ON THE POSTER-->\n| music          = [[Howard Shore]]<br />[[Metric (band)|Metric]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Metric and K'naan's Contributions to David Cronenberg's 'Cosmopolis' Soundtrack Revealed|url=http://exclaim.ca/News/metric_knaans_contributions_to_david_cronenbergs_cosmopolis_soundtrack_revealed|work=Exclaim.ca|publisher=Ian Danzig|accessdate=9 September 2012|author=Alex Hudson|date=15 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Citation | url = http://www.soundtrackgeek.com/v2/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/Cosmopolis-by-Howard-Shore-Metric-Benno-2012-297x297.jpg | title = Cosmopolis by Howard Shore Metric Benno |date=May 2012 | publisher = Sound track geek | format = [[JPEG]]}}.</ref>\n| cinematography = [[Peter Suschitzky]]\n| editing        = [[Ronald Sanders (film editor)|Ronald Sanders]]\n| studio         = {{plainlist|\n* [[Paulo Branco|Alfama Films]]\n* Prospero Pictures\n* Kinologic Films (DC)\n* [[France 2|France 2 Cin\u00e9ma]]\n* [[Telefilm Canada|T\u00e9l\u00e9film Canada]]\n* Talandracas Pictures\n* [[France T\u00e9l\u00e9visions]]\n* [[Canal+]]\n* [[RAI|Rai Cinema]]\n* [[Radiotelevis\u00e3o Portuguesa]]\n* Ontario Media Development Corporation\n* Astral Media\n* The Harold Greenberg Fund\n* Jouror Productions\n* Leopardo Filmes\n}}\n| distributor    = {{ubl|\n* [[Entertainment One]] <small>(Canada)</small>\n* Stone Angels <small>(France)</small>\n* 01 Distribution <small>(Italy)</small>\n* Leopardo Filmes <small>(Portugal)</small>\n}}\n| released       = {{film date|df=y|2012|05|25|[[2012 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes]] and Italy|2012|05|31|Portugal|2012|06|08|Canada}}\n| runtime        = 109 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 108:49--><ref>{{cite web|title=''COSMOPOLIS'' (15)|url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/cosmopolis-2012-1|work=[[British Board of Film Classification]]|date=11 May 2012|accessdate=25 May 2013}}</ref>\n| country        = {{ubl|Canada|France|Italy|Portugal}}\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $20.5 million<ref>{{cite web|title=''Cosmopolis'' (2012)|url=http://www.movieinsider.com/m6208/cosmopolis/production/|publisher=Movieinsider|accessdate=2 January 2013}}</ref>\n| gross          = $6.1 million<ref name=BOM>{{cite web|title=''Cosmopolis'' (2012)|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=cosmopolis.htm|publisher=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=31 October 2012}}</ref> <!-- Please do not change the number unless it says so on Box Office Mojo! Furthermore, if you change the number, also update the access date! -->\n}}\n'''''Cosmopolis''''' is a 2012 [[drama film|drama]]-[[thriller film]] written, produced, and directed by [[David Cronenberg]] and starring [[Robert Pattinson]] in the lead with [[Paul Giamatti]], [[Samantha Morton]], [[Sarah Gadon]], [[Mathieu Amalric]], [[Juliette Binoche]], [[Jay Baruchel]] and [[Kevin Durand]]. It is based on the [[Cosmopolis (novel)|novel of the same name]] by [[Don DeLillo]]. On 25 May 2012, the film [[Film premiere|premiered]] in competition for the [[Palme d'Or]] at the [[2012 Cannes Film Festival]],<ref name=\"Official Selection\">{{cite web |url=http://www.festival-cannes.fr/en/article/58878.html |title=2012 Official Selection |accessdate=19 April 2012 |work = Cannes}}</ref> drawing mixed early critical reactions.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/cosmopolis/| title= Cosmopolis| publisher= [[Rotten Tomatoes]]| accessdate= 26 May 2012}}</ref> The film was released in Canada on 8 June 2012,<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.nowtoronto.com/movies/story.cfm?content=187151 | title = ''Cosmopolis'' | first= Norman | last= Wilner | work = [[Now (newspaper)|Now]] | location = [[Toronto]] | date = 7\u201314 June 2012 |  volume= 31 | issue= 41 | accessdate = 26 July 2012}}</ref> and began a [[limited release]] in the United States on 17 August 2012 by [[Entertainment One|eOne Films]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://collider.com/cosmopolis-release-date-robert-pattinson/171662/ | title =Cosmopolis, Playing The Field and The Words Release Dates|author=Adam Chitwood|date=7 June 2012|publisher=Collider.com |accessdate=7 June 2012}}</ref> It is Cronenberg's first foray into script writing since 1999's ''[[Existenz|eXistenZ]]''.\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- Please see WP:FILMPLOT. Plot summaries are recommended to be 400-700 words. -->\nTwenty-eight-year-old billionaire [[Speculation|currency speculator]]/[[asset manager]] Eric Packer rides slowly across [[Manhattan]] amid traffic jams, in his state-of-the-art luxury [[stretch limousine]] office, to his preferred barber. Various visitors discuss the meaning of life and inconsequential trivia. The traffic jams are caused by a visit of the [[President of the United States]] and the funeral of Eric's favorite musician, a [[rap artist]] whose music he plays in one of his two private elevators. Despite devastating currency speculation losses over the course of the day, Packer fantasizes about buying the [[Rothko Chapel]].\n\nHe meets his wife, Elise, in her taxi, for coffee, in a bookstore, as well as outside a theater. She declines sex with him. Packer has sex with two other women. When a day of poor trading destroys a large part of his wealth, his wife takes this as a reason to dissolve their union.\n\nAnti-capitalist activists demonstrate on the street. They wave rats and declare, \"[[The Communist Manifesto|A spectre is haunting the world]]: the spectre of [[capitalism]]\". They spray-paint Packer's limo and later subjects him to a [[pieing]]. Packer learns that an [[assassin]] is out to kill him, but seems curiously uninterested in who the person might be.\n\nIn his car, his doctor performs his daily medical checkup. Eric worries about the doctor's finding that he has an asymmetrical [[prostate]]. As the currency speculation wipes out most of his fortune, Eric's world begins to disintegrate. Eventually he kills his bodyguard. At the destination, the barber, who knew his father, cuts Eric's hair on one side. The barber and limo driver discuss their respective careers driving cabs. The barber gives Eric his gun because he had thrown away the bodyguard's.\n\nEric follows a path of further self-destruction, visiting his potential murderer, former employee Richard Sheets, a.k.a. Benno Levin. Eric seems ready to commit suicide,  but instead deliberately shoots himself in the hand. Sheets/Levin, who feels adrift in the capitalist system, explains that Eric's mistake in speculating was looking for perfect symmetry and patterns in the currency market: he should have looked for the lopsided\u2014his body with its asymmetrical prostate was telling him this.As Sheets points the gun to Eric's head, Eric seems to have overcome his fear of death and is waiting for it.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Cast listing|\n* [[Robert Pattinson]] as Eric Packer\n* [[Sarah Gadon]] as Elise Packer (n\u00e9e Shifrin), Eric's wife\n* [[Paul Giamatti]] as Benno Levin\n* [[Kevin Durand]] as Torval, Eric's Chief of Security\n* [[Abdul Ayoola]] as Ibrahim Hamadou, Eric's driver\n* [[Juliette Binoche]] as Didi Fancher, Eric's art consultant, with whom Eric has an affair\n* [[Emily Hampshire]] as Jane Melman, Eric's Chief of Finance\n* [[Bob Bainborough]] as Dr. Ingram, Eric's physician\n* [[Samantha Morton]] as Vija Kinsky, Eric's Chief of Theory\n* [[Zeljko Kecojevic]] as Danko, Eric's veteran bodyguard\n* [[Jay Baruchel]] as Shiner, Eric's Head of Technology and Cyber Security and startup partner \n* [[Philip Nozuka]] as Michael Chin, Eric's young Systems Analyst\n* [[Mathieu Amalric]] as Andr\u00e9 Petrescu aka The Pastry Assassin\n* [[Patricia McKenzie]] as Kendra Hays, Eric's new bodyguard, with whom Eric has an affair\n* [[K'naan]] as Brutha Fez, a rap artist who's one of Eric's favorite musicians\n}}\n\n==Production==\nNews about a film adaptation of ''Cosmopolis'' first emerged on 10 February 2009 when Geoffrey Macnab, writing for Screendaily.com, reported that \"In his most ambitious project to date, international producer [[Paulo Branco]] is plotting a $10m\u201312m film based on the novel ''Cosmopolis'' by legendary US writer Don DeLillo. Branco's Alfama Films is producing the film about a day in the life of a young billionaire financier who, over the course of a traumatic day, loses all his wealth. A director will be named shortly and DeLillo is on board to collaborate.\"<ref>{{Citation | last = Macnab | first = Geoffrey | publisher = Screen Daily | url =  http://www.screendaily.com/paolo-branco-plots-cosmopolis/4043226.article | title = Paolo Branco plots Cosmopolis}}.</ref> On 26 July 2009, it was announced that Canadian director [[David Cronenberg]] had become involved in the project and would now bring the novel to the screen. The film was scheduled to begin filming in 2010, with Paulo Branco's Paris-based production house Alfama Films co-producing with Cronenberg's Toronto Antenna Ltd.<ref>{{cite web | title = Director David Cronenberg takes on 'Cosmopolis' | publisher = Yahoo! | location = Canada | work = News | date = 26 July 2009 | url = http://ca.news.yahoo.com/s/reuters/090726/entertainment/centertainment_us_cronenberg | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090730201844/http://ca.news.yahoo.com/s/reuters/090726/entertainment/centertainment_us_cronenberg | archivedate = 30 July 2009 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> On 3 September 2009, Paulo Branco officially confirmed to Screendaily.com that \"Cronenberg has now finished his screenplay and is now looking to cast the film.\"<ref>{{Citation | first = Geoffrey | last = Macnab | publisher = Screen Daily | url = http://www.screendaily.com/festivals/venice/venice-news/larry-clark-to-direct-troubled-teen-drama-wild-child/5005251.article | title = Lawrence 'Larry' Clark to direct trouble teen drama: wild child}}.</ref> On 13 January 2010, it was reported that Cronenberg was still committed to the film, although a cast and a starting date for production were yet to be announced. Cronenberg said that everyone was \"happy with the script\" and he was \"very fond\" of the project.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.680news.com/entertainment/article/16733--david-cronenberg-wants-keira-knightley-for-freud-jung-drama-the-talking-cure |title=David Cronenberg wants Keira Knightley for Freud-Jung drama 'The Talking Cure' |work=[[The Canadian Press]] |publisher=680 News |first=Victoria |last=Ahearn |date=13 January 2010 |accessdate=5 July 2012 }}{{dead link|date=October 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> [[Principal photography]] took place in [[Toronto]] and was completed in July 2011. [[Colin Farrell]] was initially cast in the main role but left due to scheduling difficulties with ''[[Total Recall (2012 film)|Total Recall]]''.<ref>Hubschman, Daniel (6 January 2011). [https://archive.is/20130103044857/http://www.hollywood.com/news/Robert_Pattinson_Replaces_Colin_Farrell_In_Cronenbergs_Cosmopolis/7746266 \"Robert Pattinson Replaces Colin Farrell In Cronenberg's 'Cosmopolis'\"]. ''Hollywood.com''. Retrieved 2011-05-27.</ref> He was later replaced by Pattinson. [[Marion Cotillard]] was involved in the project but also left because of scheduling conflicts.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ward|first=Kate|title=Marion Cotillard out of David Cronenberg's 'Cosmopolis'|url=https://ew.com/article/2011/01/20/marion-cotillard-out-of-david-cronenbergs-cosmopolis/|website=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=26 October 2019|date=20 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Music==\n{{Infobox album|\n| name       = Cosmopolis : Original Motion Picture Soundtrack\n| type       = Soundtrack\n| artist     = [[Howard Shore]], [[Metric (band)|Metric]] & Various Artists\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = 4 June 2012 <small>(U.S.)</small><ref name=\"all\">{{cite web|title=Cosmopolis [Original Motion Picture Soundtrack]|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/cosmopolis-original-motion-picture-soundtrack-mw0002375251|accessdate=19 November 2013}}</ref>\n| recorded   = Various times\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Pop rock]], [[alternative rock]], [[soundtrack]]\n| length     = 40:22<ref name=\"all\" />\n| label      = Howe Records<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/cosmopolis-soundtrack-details-revealed-features-3-new-songs-by-metric-howard-shore-score-more-20120508|title='Cosmopolis' Soundtrack Details Revealed, Features 3 New Songs By Metric, Howard Shore Score & More|accessdate=19 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140104211106/http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/cosmopolis-soundtrack-details-revealed-features-3-new-songs-by-metric-howard-shore-score-more-20120508|archivedate=4 January 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| producer   = Howard Shore & Metric\n| chronology = ''[[Howard Shore]]''\n| prev_title = '''[[Hugo (film)|Hugo]]'''\n| prev_year  = 2011\n| next_title = '''[[Jimmy P: Psychotherapy of a Plains Indian]]'''\n| next_year  = 2013\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n|rev1=[[AllMusic]]\n|rev1Score={{Rating|4|5}} <ref>{{Cite web\n|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=mw0002375251|pure_url=yes}}\n|title=Cosmopolis \u2013 Original Soundtrack\n|work=[[AllMusic]]\n|publisher=[[All Media Network]]\n|last=Monger\n|first=James Christopher\n|accessdate=19 November 2013\n}}</ref>\n|rev2=''[[iTunes]]''\n|rev2Score={{Rating|4.5|5}} <ref>{{Cite news\n|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20236536,00.html\n|title=Cosmopolis (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack)\n|accessdate=19 August 2011\n| work=Entertainment Weekly\n|date=30 October 2008\n}}</ref>\n|noprose=yes\n}}\nThe soundtrack reunited composer [[Howard Shore]] and the Canadian [[indie rock]] band [[Metric (band)|Metric]] who had previously collaborated on a song for [[The Twilight Saga: Eclipse (soundtrack)|''Twilight Saga: Eclipse'' soundtrack]] (which had also starred [[Robert Pattinson]]). While writing the score for ''Cosmopolis'', Shore desired a particular live sound and invited Metric to perform the score and co-write three songs. The music was recorded in November 2011 at the band's own Giant Studios in Toronto, produced by Shore and Metric guitarist Jimmy Shaw and mixed by John O'Mahony at ''Liberty Studios'' in Toronto and [[Electric Lady Studios]] in New York City. The ''Cosmopolis'' soundtrack also features \"Mecca\" by Somali-Canadian singer/rapper [[K'naan]] with lyrics by K'naan and Don DeLillo.<ref>{{cite web|title=Metric Score David Cronenberg's Don DeLillo Adaptation Cosmopolis|url=https://www.pitchfork.com/news/44282-metric-score-david-cronenbergs-don-delillo-adaptation-cosmopolis/|work=Pitchfork|publisher=Pitchfork Media Inc|accessdate=9 September 2012|author=Carrie Battan|date=13 October 2011}}</ref> ''Film Music Magazine'''s Daniel Schweiger praised the soundtrack as \"an environment of hallucinatory beauty. There's a real intelligence to the rock-alt. material here that goes beyond many indie star-composer collaborations.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=June Soundtrack Picks|url=http://www.filmmusicmag.com/?p=9676|work=Film Music Magazine|publisher=Global Media Online, Inc|accessdate=9 September 2012|author=Daniel Schweiger|date=25 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Soundtracks listing===\n\n{{tracklist\n|title1 = White Limos\n|music1 = [[Howard Shore]] & [[Metric (band)|Metric]]\n|length1 = 1:59\n\n|title2 = Long to Live\n|music2 = [[Howard Shore]] & [[Metric (band)|Metric]]\n|length2 = 4:26\n\n|title3 = Rat Men\n|music3 = [[Howard Shore]] & [[Metric (band)|Metric]]\n|length3 = 4:44\n\n|title4 = Asymmetrical\n|music4 = [[Howard Shore]] & [[Metric (band)|Metric]]\n|length4 = 4:11\n\n|title5 = I Don't Want to Wake Up\n|music5 = [[Howard Shore]] & [[Metric (band)|Metric]]\n|length5 = 4:14\n\n|title6 = A Credible Threat\n|music6 = [[Howard Shore]] & [[Metric (band)|Metric]]\n|length6 = 1:53\n\n|title7 = Call Me Home\n|music7 = [[Howard Shore]] & [[Metric (band)|Metric]]\n|length7 = 2:36\n\n|title8 = Haircut \n|music8 = [[Howard Shore]] & [[Metric (band)|Metric]]\n|length8 = 3:58\n\n|title9 = Mecca\n|music9 = [[K'naan]]\n|length9 = 2:55\n\n|title10 = The Gun\n|music10 = [[Howard Shore]] & [[Metric (band)|Metric]]\n|length10 = 2:34\n\n|title11 = Benno\n|music11 = [[Howard Shore]] & [[Metric (band)|Metric]]\n|length11 = 6:52\n|total_length = 40:22\n}}\n\n===Songs===\nThe soundtrack album features four songs.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cosmopolis|url=http://howerecords.com/cosmopolis/|accessdate=19 November 2013}}</ref> James Christopher Monger of Allmusic.com lauded [[Emily Haines]] for her \"strong vocal performances on the ghostly \"Long to Live\" and \"Call Me Home,\" switching to a full-on banshee wail for the pulsating \"I Don't Want to Wake Up\"\" and wrote that the score was \"one of the most engaging soundtracks of the year.\"<ref>{{Citation | url = https://www.allmusic.com/album/cosmopolis-original-motion-picture-soundtrack-mw0002375251 | publisher = All music | title = Cosmopolis original motion picture soundtrack}}.</ref> \"Long to Live\" won [[Academy of Canadian Cinema and Television Award for Best Achievement in Music \u2013 Original Song|Achievement in Music: Original Song]] at the [[1st Canadian Screen Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Seven SOCAN members win in 1st Canadian Screen Awards|url=http://www.socan.ca/news/seven-socan-members-win-2013-canadian-screen-awards|accessdate=19 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523101416/http://www.socan.ca/news/seven-socan-members-win-2013-canadian-screen-awards|archive-date=23 May 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Canadian Screen Awards winners: Rebelle cleans up movie awards, Flashpoint tops in TV drama|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/2013/03/03/canadian_screen_awards_winners_rebelle_cleans_up_movie_awards_flashpoint_tops_in_tv_drama.html|accessdate=19 November 2013 | location=Toronto|work=The Star|date=3 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! #\n! Song/artist\n! Writer\n! Length\n|-\n| 1\n| \"Long to Live\" by [[Metric (band)|Metric]]\n| [[Emily Haines]], [[James Shaw (musician)|James Shaw]] and [[Howard Shore]]\n| 4:26\n|-\n| 2\n| \"I Don't Want to Wake Up\" by [[Metric (band)|Metric]]\n| [[Emily Haines]], [[James Shaw (musician)|James Shaw]] and [[Howard Shore]]\n| 4:14\n|-\n| 3\n| \"Mecca\" by [[K'naan]]\n| [[Don DeLillo]] and [[K'naan]]\n| 2:55\n|-\n| 4\n| \"Call Me Home\" by [[Metric (band)|Metric]]\n| [[Emily Haines]], [[James Shaw (musician)|James Shaw]] and [[Howard Shore]]\n| 2:36\n|}\n\n==Reception==\n[[File:Cosmopolis Cannes 2012 2.jpg|thumb|[[David Cronenberg]], [[Robert Pattinson]] and [[Juliette Binoche]] promoting the film at the [[2012 Cannes Film Festival]]]]\n''Cosmopolis'' received generally positive reviews. [[Rotten Tomatoes]] gave the film a \"fresh\" 65%, based on 180 reviews, with an average rating of 6.03/10. The consensus says, \"Though some may find it cold and didactic, ''Cosmopolis'' benefits from David Cronenberg's precise direction, resulting in a psychologically complex adaptation of Don DeLillo's novel.\"<ref>{{rottentomatoes|cosmopolis}}</ref>\n\nJustin Chang of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' wrote: \"An eerily precise match of filmmaker and material, ''Cosmopolis'' probes the soullessness of the 1% with the cinematic equivalent of latex gloves. ... Pattinson's excellent performance reps an indispensable asset.\"<ref>{{Citation | last = Chang | first = Justin | date = 25 May 2012 | format = review | title = Cosmopolis | url = https://www.variety.com/review/VE1117947638/ | newspaper = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | accessdate = 29 May 2012}}.</ref> [[Robbie Collin]] of ''The Telegraph'' gave the film four stars out of five, stating, \"It's a smart inversion of Cronenberg's 1999 film ''[[eXistenZ]]'': rather than being umbilically connected to a virtual world, Packer is hermetically sealed off from the real one. At its heart is a sensational central performance from Robert Pattinson as Packer. Pattinson plays him like a human caldera; stony on the surface, with volcanic chambers of nervous energy and self-loathing churning deep below.\"<ref>{{Citation | last = Collin | first = Robbie | date = 26 May 2012 | title = Cannes 2012: Robert Pattinson in Cosmopolis | format = review | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/filmreviews/9290609/Cannes-2012-Robert-Pattinson-in-Cosmopolis-review.html | newspaper = The Telegraph | accessdate = 29 May 2012 | location=London}}.</ref> Ross Miller of ''Thoughts On Film'' also gave the film four out of five stars stating that, \"If, like me, you're in-tune with the tone, style and direction of the film then it provides for a fascinating and intellectually nourishing experience.\"<ref>{{Citation | last = Miller | first = Ross | date = 14 June 2012 | url = http://thoughtsonfilm.co.uk/movie-reviews/cosmopolis-movie-review/ | publisher = Thoughts on Film | accessdate = 26 August 2012 | title = Cosmopolis movie | format = review}}.</ref> [[Owen Gleiberman]] of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' stated, \"''Cosmopolis'' includes its own version of the [[Occupy movement|Occupy]] hordes: scruffy, vengeful protesters who run around the streets, and into restaurants, brandishing the bodies of dead rats. ... Pattinson, pale and predatory even without his pasty-white vampire makeup, delivers his frigid pens\u00e9es with rhythmic confidence.\"<ref>{{Citation | last = Gleiberman | first = Owen | date = 25 May 2012 | title=Cannes: Robert Pattinson plays a lethal finance bad boy in David Cronenberg's 'Cosmopolis.' Plus, a Palme d'Or conspiracy theory|url=http://insidemovies.ew.com/2012/05/25/cannes-robert-pattinson-in-cosmopolis/ |work=Entertainment Weekly| accessdate=26 October 2019}}.</ref> A very positive review came from ''The London Film Review'', which said \"The fact is, Cronenberg made a movie for YOU.  The 99%. A movie that reflects, comments on[,] satirizes and parodies our time.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.thelondonfilmreview.com/film-review/re-review-cosmopolis/| title=Re-review: Cosmopolis| accessdate=26 September 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120828131243/http://www.thelondonfilmreview.com/film-review/re-review-cosmopolis/| archivedate=28 August 2012| url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nHowever, [[Todd McCarthy]] of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' criticized the film, writing, \"Lifeless, stagey and lacking a palpable subversive pulse despite the ready opportunities offered by the material, this stillborn adaptation of Don DeLillo's novel initially will attract some Robert Pattinson fans but will be widely met with audience indifference.\"<ref>{{Citation | last = McCarthy | first = Todd | date = 25 May 2012 | url = https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/cosmopolis-review-robert-pattinson-cannes-329230 | newspaper = [[The Hollywood Reporter]] | accessdate = 29 May 2012 | format = review | title = Cosmopolis, Robert Pattinson, Cannes}}.</ref> Film magazine ''[[Sight & Sound]]'' listed ''Cosmopolis'' at #8 on its list of best films of 2012,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.hitfix.com/in-contention/the-master-named-2012s-best-in-sight-sound-critics-poll|title='The Master' named 2012's best in Sight & Sound critics' poll|accessdate=26 September 2014 }}</ref> and ''[[Cahiers du Cinema]]'' placed it at #2.<ref>{{cite web|work=Cahiers du cinema|url=https://www.cahiersducinema.com/produit/top-ten-2012|title=Top Ten 2012, D\u00e9cembre 2012 n\u00b0684}}</ref>\n\n==Accolades==\n{{Anchor|Awards}} \n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Recipient\n! Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2012\n| [[Cannes Film Festival]]\n| [[Palme d'Or]]\n| [[David Cronenberg]]\n| {{nom}}<ref>{{cite news|title=Cannes 2012: Michael Haneke wins second Palme d'Or for Amour|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2012/may/27/cannes-palme-haneke-amour|accessdate=22 May 2013 | location=London|work=The Guardian|first=Catherine|last=Shoard|date=27 May 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[World Soundtrack Academy]]\n| [[World Soundtrack Award for Soundtrack Composer of the Year|Soundtrack Composer of the Year]]\n| [[Howard Shore]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"10\"| 2013\n| rowspan=\"3\"| [[Canadian Screen Awards]]\n| [[1st Canadian Screen Awards#Adapted Screenplay|Adapted Screenplay]]\n| David Cronenberg\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[1st Canadian Screen Awards|Achievement in Music: Original Score]]\n| Howard Shore\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[1st Canadian Screen Awards|Achievement in Music: Original Song]]\n| [[Emily Haines]], [[James Shaw (musician)|James Shaw]] and Howard Shore, \"Long to Live\"\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Online Film Critics Society]]\n| [[Online Film Critics Society Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]]\n| David Cronenberg\n| {{nom}}<ref>{{cite web|title=2012 Awards (16th Annual)|url=http://www.ofcs.org/awards/2012-awards-16th-annual/|accessdate=22 May 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\"| [[Vancouver Film Critics Circle]]\n| [[Vancouver Film Critics Circle Award for Best Canadian Film|Best Film \u2013 Canadian]]\n| \n| {{nom}}<ref name=\"a\">{{cite web|title=2013 VFCC Nominees Announced!|url=http://vancouverfilmcritics.com/2012/12/27/2013-vfcc-nominees-announced/|accessdate=22 May 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Director \u2013 Canadian Film\n| David Cronenberg\n| {{nom}}<ref name=\"a\" />\n|-\n| [[Vancouver Film Critics Circle Award for Best Actor in a Canadian Film|Best Actor in a Canadian Film]]\n| [[Robert Pattinson]]\n| {{nom}}<ref name=\"a\" />\n|-\n|rowspan=2| Best Supporting Actress in a Canadian Film\n| [[Samantha Morton]]\n| {{nom}}<ref name=\"a\" />\n|-\n| [[Sarah Gadon]]\n| {{won}}<ref>{{cite web|title='Zero Dark Thirty' wins big with Vancouver critics|url=http://www.hitfix.com/in-contention/zero-dark-thirty-wins-big-with-vancouver-critics|accessdate=22 May 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award]]\n| [[Saturn Award for Best DVD or Blu-ray Release|Best DVD/Blu-ray Release]]\n| \n| {{nom}}<ref>{{cite web|title=2013 Saturn Award Nominees|url=http://scifi.about.com/od/awardsforscififantasy/a/Saturn-Award-Nominations-2013.htm|accessdate=22 May 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130510161358/http://scifi.about.com/od/awardsforscififantasy/a/Saturn-Award-Nominations-2013.htm|archivedate=10 May 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|}\n</center>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{official website|http://cosmopolisthefilm.com/en}}\n* {{IMDb title|1480656|Cosmopolis}}\n* {{mojo title|cosmopolis|Cosmopolis}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|cosmopolis|Cosmopolis}}\n* {{metacritic film|cosmopolis|Cosmopolis}}\n\n{{David Cronenberg}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cosmopolis}}\n[[Category:2012 films]]\n[[Category:2010s thriller drama films]]\n[[Category:Canadian thriller drama films]]\n[[Category:Canadian films]]\n[[Category:French thriller drama films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:Italian thriller drama films]]\n[[Category:Portuguese thriller drama films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by David Cronenberg]]\n[[Category:Films about financial crises]]\n[[Category:Films based on American novels]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Paulo Branco]]\n[[Category:Films set in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Films set in the future]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Howard Shore]]\n[[Category:Italian films]]\n[[Category:Portuguese films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Cosmopolis\n| image          = Cosmopolis Poster.jpg\n| image_size     = \n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[David Cronenberg]]\n| producer       = David Cronenberg<br />[[Paulo Branco]]<br />Renee Tab<br />[[Martin Katz (producer)|Martin Katz]]\n| screenplay     = David Cronenberg\n| based on       = {{Based on|''[[Cosmopolis (novel)|Cosmopolis]]''|[[Don DeLillo]]}}\n| starring       = [[Robert Pattinson]]<br />[[Paul Giamatti]]<br />[[Samantha Morton]]<br />[[Sarah Gadon]]<br />[[Mathieu Amalric]]<br />[[Juliette Binoche]]<br />[[Jay Baruchel]]<br />[[Kevin Durand]]<!--DO NOT CHANGE THIS CAST, THIS IS ACCORDING TO THE CREDIT BLOCK ON THE POSTER-->\n| music          = [[Howard Shore]]<br />[[Metric (band)|Metric]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Metric and K'naan's Contributions to David Cronenberg's 'Cosmopolis' Soundtrack Revealed|url=http://exclaim.ca/News/metric_knaans_contributions_to_david_cronenbergs_cosmopolis_soundtrack_revealed|work=Exclaim.ca|publisher=Ian Danzig|accessdate=9 September 2012|author=Alex Hudson|date=15 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Citation | url = http://www.soundtrackgeek.com/v2/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/Cosmopolis-by-Howard-Shore-Metric-Benno-2012-297x297.jpg | title = Cosmopolis by Howard Shore Metric Benno |date=May 2012 | publisher = Sound track geek | format = [[JPEG]]}}.</ref>\n| cinematography = [[Peter Suschitzky]]\n| editing        = [[Ronald Sanders (film editor)|Ronald Sanders]]\n| studio         = {{plainlist|\n* [[Paulo Branco|Alfama Films]]\n* Prospero Pictures\n* Kinologic Films (DC)\n* [[France 2|France 2 Cin\u00e9ma]]\n* [[Telefilm Canada|T\u00e9l\u00e9film Canada]]\n* Talandracas Pictures\n* [[France T\u00e9l\u00e9visions]]\n* [[Canal+]]\n* [[RAI|Rai Cinema]]\n* [[Radiotelevis\u00e3o Portuguesa]]\n* Ontario Media Development Corporation\n* Astral Media\n* The Harold Greenberg Fund\n* Jouror Productions\n* Leopardo Filmes\n}}\n| distributor    = {{ubl|\n* [[Entertainment One]] <small>(Canada)</small>\n* Stone Angels <small>(France)</small>\n* 01 Distribution <small>(Italy)</small>\n* Leopardo Filmes <small>(Portugal)</small>\n}}\n| released       = {{film date|df=y|2012|05|25|[[2012 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes]] and Italy|2012|05|31|Portugal|2012|06|08|Canada}}\n| runtime        = 109 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 108:49--><ref>{{cite web|title=''COSMOPOLIS'' (15)|url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/cosmopolis-2012-1|work=[[British Board of Film Classification]]|date=11 May 2012|accessdate=25 May 2013}}</ref>\n| country        = {{ubl|Canada|France|Italy|Portugal}}\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $20.5 million<ref>{{cite web|title=''Cosmopolis'' (2012)|url=http://www.movieinsider.com/m6208/cosmopolis/production/|publisher=Movieinsider|accessdate=2 January 2013}}</ref>\n| gross          = $6.1 million<ref name=BOM>{{cite web|title=''Cosmopolis'' (2012)|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=cosmopolis.htm|publisher=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=31 October 2012}}</ref> <!-- Please do not change the number unless it says so on Box Office Mojo! Furthermore, if you change the number, also update the access date! -->\n}}\n'''''Cosmopolis''''' is a 2012 [[drama film|drama]]-[[thriller film]] written, produced, and directed by [[David Cronenberg]] and starring [[Robert Pattinson]] in the lead with [[Paul Giamatti]], [[Samantha Morton]], [[Sarah Gadon]], [[Mathieu Amalric]], [[Juliette Binoche]], [[Jay Baruchel]] and [[Kevin Durand]]. It is based on the [[Cosmopolis (novel)|novel of the same name]] by [[Don DeLillo]]. On 25 May 2012, the film [[Film premiere|premiered]] in competition for the [[Palme d'Or]] at the [[2012 Cannes Film Festival]],<ref name=\"Official Selection\">{{cite web |url=http://www.festival-cannes.fr/en/article/58878.html |title=2012 Official Selection |accessdate=19 April 2012 |work = Cannes}}</ref> drawing mixed early critical reactions.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/cosmopolis/| title= Cosmopolis| publisher= [[Rotten Tomatoes]]| accessdate= 26 May 2012}}</ref> The film was released in Canada on 8 June 2012,<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.nowtoronto.com/movies/story.cfm?content=187151 | title = ''Cosmopolis'' | first= Norman | last= Wilner | work = [[Now (newspaper)|Now]] | location = [[Toronto]] | date = 7\u201314 June 2012 |  volume= 31 | issue= 41 | accessdate = 26 July 2012}}</ref> and began a [[limited release]] in the United States on 17 August 2012 by [[Entertainment One|eOne Films]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://collider.com/cosmopolis-release-date-robert-pattinson/171662/ | title =Cosmopolis, Playing The Field and The Words Release Dates|author=Adam Chitwood|date=7 June 2012|publisher=Collider.com |accessdate=7 June 2012}}</ref> It is Cronenberg's first foray into script writing since 1999's ''[[Existenz|eXistenZ]]''.\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- Please see WP:FILMPLOT. Plot summaries are recommended to be 400-700 words. -->\nTwenty-eight-year-old billionaire [[Speculation|currency speculator]]/[[asset manager]] Eric Packer rides slowly across [[Manhattan]] amid traffic jams, in his state-of-the-art luxury [[stretch limousine]] office, to his preferred barber. Various visitors discuss the meaning of life and inconsequential trivia. The traffic jams are caused by a visit of the [[President of the United States]] and the funeral of Eric's favorite musician, a [[rap artist]] whose music he plays in one of his two private elevators. Despite devastating currency speculation losses over the course of the day, Packer fantasizes about buying the [[Rothko Chapel]].\n\nHe meets his wife, Elise, in her taxi, for coffee, in a bookstore, as well as outside a theater. She declines sex with him. Packer has sex with two other women. When a day of poor trading destroys a large part of his wealth, his wife takes this as a reason to dissolve their union.\n\nAnti-capitalist activists demonstrate on the street. They wave rats and declare, \"[[The Communist Manifesto|A spectre is haunting the world]]: the spectre of [[capitalism]]\". They spray-paint Packer's limo and later subjects him to a [[pieing]]. Packer learns that an [[assassin]] is out to kill him, but seems curiously uninterested in who the person might be.\n\nIn his car, his doctor performs his daily medical checkup. Eric worries about the doctor's finding that he has an asymmetrical [[prostate]]. As the currency speculation wipes out most of his fortune, Eric's world begins to disintegrate. Eventually he kills his bodyguard. At the destination, the barber, who knew his father, cuts Eric's hair on one side. The barber and limo driver discuss their respective careers driving cabs. The barber gives Eric his gun because he had thrown away the bodyguard's.\n\nEric follows a path of further self-destruction, visiting his potential murderer, former employee Richard Sheets, a.k.a. Benno Levin. Eric seems ready to commit suicide,  but instead deliberately shoots himself in the hand. Sheets/Levin, who feels adrift in the capitalist system, explains that Eric's mistake in speculating was looking for perfect symmetry and patterns in the currency market: he should have looked for the lopsided\u2014his body with its asymmetrical prostate was telling him this.As Sheets points the gun to Eric's head, Eric seems to have overcome his fear of death and is waiting for it.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Cast listing|\n* [[Robert Pattinson]] as Eric Packer\n* [[Sarah Gadon]] as Elise Packer (n\u00e9e Shifrin), Eric's wife\n* [[Paul Giamatti]] as Benno Levin\n* [[Kevin Durand]] as Torval, Eric's Chief of Security\n* [[Abdul Ayoola]] as Ibrahim Hamadou, Eric's driver\n* [[Juliette Binoche]] as Didi Fancher, Eric's art consultant, with whom Eric has an affair\n* [[Emily Hampshire]] as Jane Melman, Eric's Chief of Finance\n* [[Bob Bainborough]] as Dr. Ingram, Eric's physician\n* [[Samantha Morton]] as Vija Kinsky, Eric's Chief of Theory\n* [[Zeljko Kecojevic]] as Danko, Eric's veteran bodyguard\n* [[Jay Baruchel]] as Shiner, Eric's Head of Technology and Cyber Security and startup partner \n* [[Philip Nozuka]] as Michael Chin, Eric's young Systems Analyst\n* [[Mathieu Amalric]] as Andr\u00e9 Petrescu aka The Pastry Assassin\n* [[Patricia McKenzie]] as Kendra Hays, Eric's new bodyguard, with whom Eric has an affair\n* [[K'naan]] as Brutha Fez, a rap artist who's one of Eric's favorite musicians\n}}\n\n==Production==\nNews about a film adaptation of ''Cosmopolis'' first emerged on 10 February 2009 when Geoffrey Macnab, writing for Screendaily.com, reported that \"In his most ambitious project to date, international producer [[Paulo Branco]] is plotting a $10m\u201312m film based on the novel ''Cosmopolis'' by legendary US writer Don DeLillo. Branco's Alfama Films is producing the film about a day in the life of a young billionaire financier who, over the course of a traumatic day, loses all his wealth. A director will be named shortly and DeLillo is on board to collaborate.\"<ref>{{Citation | last = Macnab | first = Geoffrey | publisher = Screen Daily | url =  http://www.screendaily.com/paolo-branco-plots-cosmopolis/4043226.article | title = Paolo Branco plots Cosmopolis}}.</ref> On 26 July 2009, it was announced that Canadian director [[David Cronenberg]] had become involved in the project and would now bring the novel to the screen. The film was scheduled to begin filming in 2010, with Paulo Branco's Paris-based production house Alfama Films co-producing with Cronenberg's Toronto Antenna Ltd.<ref>{{cite web | title = Director David Cronenberg takes on 'Cosmopolis' | publisher = Yahoo! | location = Canada | work = News | date = 26 July 2009 | url = http://ca.news.yahoo.com/s/reuters/090726/entertainment/centertainment_us_cronenberg | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090730201844/http://ca.news.yahoo.com/s/reuters/090726/entertainment/centertainment_us_cronenberg | archivedate = 30 July 2009 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> On 3 September 2009, Paulo Branco officially confirmed to Screendaily.com that \"Cronenberg has now finished his screenplay and is now looking to cast the film.\"<ref>{{Citation | first = Geoffrey | last = Macnab | publisher = Screen Daily | url = http://www.screendaily.com/festivals/venice/venice-news/larry-clark-to-direct-troubled-teen-drama-wild-child/5005251.article | title = Lawrence 'Larry' Clark to direct trouble teen drama: wild child}}.</ref> On 13 January 2010, it was reported that Cronenberg was still committed to the film, although a cast and a starting date for production were yet to be announced. Cronenberg said that everyone was \"happy with the script\" and he was \"very fond\" of the project.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.680news.com/entertainment/article/16733--david-cronenberg-wants-keira-knightley-for-freud-jung-drama-the-talking-cure |title=David Cronenberg wants Keira Knightley for Freud-Jung drama 'The Talking Cure' |work=[[The Canadian Press]] |publisher=680 News |first=Victoria |last=Ahearn |date=13 January 2010 |accessdate=5 July 2012 }}{{dead link|date=October 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> [[Principal photography]] took place in [[Toronto]] and was completed in July 2011. [[Colin Farrell]] was initially cast in the main role but left due to scheduling difficulties with ''[[Total Recall (2012 film)|Total Recall]]''.<ref>Hubschman, Daniel (6 January 2011). [https://archive.is/20130103044857/http://www.hollywood.com/news/Robert_Pattinson_Replaces_Colin_Farrell_In_Cronenbergs_Cosmopolis/7746266 \"Robert Pattinson Replaces Colin Farrell In Cronenberg's 'Cosmopolis'\"]. ''Hollywood.com''. Retrieved 2011-05-27.</ref> He was later replaced by Pattinson. [[Marion Cotillard]] was involved in the project but also left because of scheduling conflicts.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ward|first=Kate|title=Marion Cotillard out of David Cronenberg's 'Cosmopolis'|url=https://ew.com/article/2011/01/20/marion-cotillard-out-of-david-cronenbergs-cosmopolis/|website=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=26 October 2019|date=20 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Music==\n{{Infobox album|\n| name       = Cosmopolis : Original Motion Picture Soundtrack\n| type       = Soundtrack\n| artist     = [[Howard Shore]], [[Metric (band)|Metric]] & Various Artists\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = 4 June 2012 <small>(U.S.)</small><ref name=\"all\">{{cite web|title=Cosmopolis [Original Motion Picture Soundtrack]|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/cosmopolis-original-motion-picture-soundtrack-mw0002375251|accessdate=19 November 2013}}</ref>\n| recorded   = Various times\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Pop rock]], [[alternative rock]], [[soundtrack]]\n| length     = 40:22<ref name=\"all\" />\n| label      = Howe Records<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/cosmopolis-soundtrack-details-revealed-features-3-new-songs-by-metric-howard-shore-score-more-20120508|title='Cosmopolis' Soundtrack Details Revealed, Features 3 New Songs By Metric, Howard Shore Score & More|accessdate=19 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140104211106/http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/cosmopolis-soundtrack-details-revealed-features-3-new-songs-by-metric-howard-shore-score-more-20120508|archivedate=4 January 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| producer   = Howard Shore & Metric\n| chronology = ''[[Howard Shore]]''\n| prev_title = '''[[Hugo (film)|Hugo]]'''\n| prev_year  = 2011\n| next_title = '''[[Jimmy P: Psychotherapy of a Plains Indian]]'''\n| next_year  = 2013\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n|rev1=[[AllMusic]]\n|rev1Score={{Rating|4|5}} <ref>{{Cite web\n|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=mw0002375251|pure_url=yes}}\n|title=Cosmopolis \u2013 Original Soundtrack\n|work=[[AllMusic]]\n|publisher=[[All Media Network]]\n|last=Monger\n|first=James Christopher\n|accessdate=19 November 2013\n}}</ref>\n|rev2=''[[iTunes]]''\n|rev2Score={{Rating|4.5|5}} <ref>{{Cite news\n|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20236536,00.html\n|title=Cosmopolis (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack)\n|accessdate=19 August 2011\n| work=Entertainment Weekly\n|date=30 October 2008\n}}</ref>\n|noprose=yes\n}}\nThe soundtrack reunited composer [[Howard Shore]] and the Canadian [[indie rock]] band [[Metric (band)|Metric]] who had previously collaborated on a song for [[The Twilight Saga: Eclipse (soundtrack)|''Twilight Saga: Eclipse'' soundtrack]] (which had also starred [[Robert Pattinson]]). While writing the score for ''Cosmopolis'', Shore desired a particular live sound and invited Metric to perform the score and co-write three songs. The music was recorded in November 2011 at the band's own Giant Studios in Toronto, produced by Shore and Metric guitarist Jimmy Shaw and mixed by John O'Mahony at ''Liberty Studios'' in Toronto and [[Electric Lady Studios]] in New York City. The ''Cosmopolis'' soundtrack also features \"Mecca\" by Somali-Canadian singer/rapper [[K'naan]] with lyrics by K'naan and Don DeLillo.<ref>{{cite web|title=Metric Score David Cronenberg's Don DeLillo Adaptation Cosmopolis|url=https://www.pitchfork.com/news/44282-metric-score-david-cronenbergs-don-delillo-adaptation-cosmopolis/|work=Pitchfork|publisher=Pitchfork Media Inc|accessdate=9 September 2012|author=Carrie Battan|date=13 October 2011}}</ref> ''Film Music Magazine'''s Daniel Schweiger praised the soundtrack as \"an environment of hallucinatory beauty. There's a real intelligence to the rock-alt. material here that goes beyond many indie star-composer collaborations.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=June Soundtrack Picks|url=http://www.filmmusicmag.com/?p=9676|work=Film Music Magazine|publisher=Global Media Online, Inc|accessdate=9 September 2012|author=Daniel Schweiger|date=25 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Soundtracks listing===\n\n{{tracklist\n|title1 = White Limos\n|music1 = [[Howard Shore]] & [[Metric (band)|Metric]]\n|length1 = 1:59\n\n|title2 = Long to Live\n|music2 = [[Howard Shore]] & [[Metric (band)|Metric]]\n|length2 = 4:26\n\n|title3 = Rat Men\n|music3 = [[Howard Shore]] & [[Metric (band)|Metric]]\n|length3 = 4:44\n\n|title4 = Asymmetrical\n|music4 = [[Howard Shore]] & [[Metric (band)|Metric]]\n|length4 = 4:11\n\n|title5 = I Don't Want to Wake Up\n|music5 = [[Howard Shore]] & [[Metric (band)|Metric]]\n|length5 = 4:14\n\n|title6 = A Credible Threat\n|music6 = [[Howard Shore]] & [[Metric (band)|Metric]]\n|length6 = 1:53\n\n|title7 = Call Me Home\n|music7 = [[Howard Shore]] & [[Metric (band)|Metric]]\n|length7 = 2:36\n\n|title8 = Haircut \n|music8 = [[Howard Shore]] & [[Metric (band)|Metric]]\n|length8 = 3:58\n\n|title9 = Mecca\n|music9 = [[K'naan]]\n|length9 = 2:55\n\n|title10 = The Gun\n|music10 = [[Howard Shore]] & [[Metric (band)|Metric]]\n|length10 = 2:34\n\n|title11 = Benno\n|music11 = [[Howard Shore]] & [[Metric (band)|Metric]]\n|length11 = 6:52\n|total_length = 40:22\n}}\n\n===Songs===\nThe soundtrack album features four songs.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cosmopolis|url=http://howerecords.com/cosmopolis/|accessdate=19 November 2013}}</ref> James Christopher Monger of Allmusic.com lauded [[Emily Haines]] for her \"strong vocal performances on the ghostly \"Long to Live\" and \"Call Me Home,\" switching to a full-on banshee wail for the pulsating \"I Don't Want to Wake Up\"\" and wrote that the score was \"one of the most engaging soundtracks of the year.\"<ref>{{Citation | url = https://www.allmusic.com/album/cosmopolis-original-motion-picture-soundtrack-mw0002375251 | publisher = All music | title = Cosmopolis original motion picture soundtrack}}.</ref> \"Long to Live\" won [[Academy of Canadian Cinema and Television Award for Best Achievement in Music \u2013 Original Song|Achievement in Music: Original Song]] at the [[1st Canadian Screen Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Seven SOCAN members win in 1st Canadian Screen Awards|url=http://www.socan.ca/news/seven-socan-members-win-2013-canadian-screen-awards|accessdate=19 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523101416/http://www.socan.ca/news/seven-socan-members-win-2013-canadian-screen-awards|archive-date=23 May 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Canadian Screen Awards winners: Rebelle cleans up movie awards, Flashpoint tops in TV drama|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/2013/03/03/canadian_screen_awards_winners_rebelle_cleans_up_movie_awards_flashpoint_tops_in_tv_drama.html|accessdate=19 November 2013 | location=Toronto|work=The Star|date=3 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! #\n! Song/artist\n! Writer\n! Length\n|-\n| 1\n| \"Long to Live\" by [[Metric (band)|Metric]]\n| [[Emily Haines]], [[James Shaw (musician)|James Shaw]] and [[Howard Shore]]\n| 4:26\n|-\n| 2\n| \"I Don't Want to Wake Up\" by [[Metric (band)|Metric]]\n| [[Emily Haines]], [[James Shaw (musician)|James Shaw]] and [[Howard Shore]]\n| 4:14\n|-\n| 3\n| \"Mecca\" by [[K'naan]]\n| [[Don DeLillo]] and [[K'naan]]\n| 2:55\n|-\n| 4\n| \"Call Me Home\" by [[Metric (band)|Metric]]\n| [[Emily Haines]], [[James Shaw (musician)|James Shaw]] and [[Howard Shore]]\n| 2:36\n|}\n\n==Reception==\n[[File:Cosmopolis Cannes 2012 2.jpg|thumb|[[David Cronenberg]], [[Robert Pattinson]] and [[Juliette Binoche]] promoting the film at the [[2012 Cannes Film Festival]]]]\n''Cosmopolis'' received generally positive reviews. [[Rotten Tomatoes]] gave the film a \"fresh\" 66%, based on 177 reviews, with an average rating of 6.04/10. The consensus says, \"Though some may find it cold and didactic, ''Cosmopolis'' benefits from David Cronenberg's precise direction, resulting in a psychologically complex adaptation of Don DeLillo's novel.\"<ref>{{rottentomatoes|cosmopolis}}</ref>\n\nJustin Chang of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' wrote: \"An eerily precise match of filmmaker and material, ''Cosmopolis'' probes the soullessness of the 1% with the cinematic equivalent of latex gloves. ... Pattinson's excellent performance reps an indispensable asset.\"<ref>{{Citation | last = Chang | first = Justin | date = 25 May 2012 | format = review | title = Cosmopolis | url = https://www.variety.com/review/VE1117947638/ | newspaper = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | accessdate = 29 May 2012}}.</ref> [[Robbie Collin]] of ''The Telegraph'' gave the film four stars out of five, stating, \"It's a smart inversion of Cronenberg's 1999 film ''[[eXistenZ]]'': rather than being umbilically connected to a virtual world, Packer is hermetically sealed off from the real one. At its heart is a sensational central performance from Robert Pattinson as Packer. Pattinson plays him like a human caldera; stony on the surface, with volcanic chambers of nervous energy and self-loathing churning deep below.\"<ref>{{Citation | last = Collin | first = Robbie | date = 26 May 2012 | title = Cannes 2012: Robert Pattinson in Cosmopolis | format = review | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/filmreviews/9290609/Cannes-2012-Robert-Pattinson-in-Cosmopolis-review.html | newspaper = The Telegraph | accessdate = 29 May 2012 | location=London}}.</ref> Ross Miller of ''Thoughts On Film'' also gave the film four out of five stars stating that, \"If, like me, you're in-tune with the tone, style and direction of the film then it provides for a fascinating and intellectually nourishing experience.\"<ref>{{Citation | last = Miller | first = Ross | date = 14 June 2012 | url = http://thoughtsonfilm.co.uk/movie-reviews/cosmopolis-movie-review/ | publisher = Thoughts on Film | accessdate = 26 August 2012 | title = Cosmopolis movie | format = review}}.</ref> [[Owen Gleiberman]] of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' stated, \"''Cosmopolis'' includes its own version of the [[Occupy movement|Occupy]] hordes: scruffy, vengeful protesters who run around the streets, and into restaurants, brandishing the bodies of dead rats. ... Pattinson, pale and predatory even without his pasty-white vampire makeup, delivers his frigid pens\u00e9es with rhythmic confidence.\"<ref>{{Citation | last = Gleiberman | first = Owen | date = 25 May 2012 | title=Cannes: Robert Pattinson plays a lethal finance bad boy in David Cronenberg's 'Cosmopolis.' Plus, a Palme d'Or conspiracy theory|url=http://insidemovies.ew.com/2012/05/25/cannes-robert-pattinson-in-cosmopolis/ |work=Entertainment Weekly| accessdate=26 October 2019}}.</ref> A very positive review came from ''The London Film Review'', which said \"The fact is, Cronenberg made a movie for YOU.  The 99%. A movie that reflects, comments on[,] satirizes and parodies our time.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.thelondonfilmreview.com/film-review/re-review-cosmopolis/| title=Re-review: Cosmopolis| accessdate=26 September 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120828131243/http://www.thelondonfilmreview.com/film-review/re-review-cosmopolis/| archivedate=28 August 2012| url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nHowever, [[Todd McCarthy]] of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' criticized the film, writing, \"Lifeless, stagey and lacking a palpable subversive pulse despite the ready opportunities offered by the material, this stillborn adaptation of Don DeLillo's novel initially will attract some Robert Pattinson fans but will be widely met with audience indifference.\"<ref>{{Citation | last = McCarthy | first = Todd | date = 25 May 2012 | url = https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/cosmopolis-review-robert-pattinson-cannes-329230 | newspaper = [[The Hollywood Reporter]] | accessdate = 29 May 2012 | format = review | title = Cosmopolis, Robert Pattinson, Cannes}}.</ref> Film magazine ''[[Sight & Sound]]'' listed ''Cosmopolis'' at #8 on its list of best films of 2012,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.hitfix.com/in-contention/the-master-named-2012s-best-in-sight-sound-critics-poll|title='The Master' named 2012's best in Sight & Sound critics' poll|accessdate=26 September 2014 }}</ref> and ''[[Cahiers du Cinema]]'' placed it at #2.<ref>{{cite web|work=Cahiers du cinema|url=https://www.cahiersducinema.com/produit/top-ten-2012|title=Top Ten 2012, D\u00e9cembre 2012 n\u00b0684}}</ref>\n\n\n==Accolades==\n{{Anchor|Awards}} \n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Recipient\n! Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2012\n| [[Cannes Film Festival]]\n| [[Palme d'Or]]\n| [[David Cronenberg]]\n| {{nom}}<ref>{{cite news|title=Cannes 2012: Michael Haneke wins second Palme d'Or for Amour|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2012/may/27/cannes-palme-haneke-amour|accessdate=22 May 2013 | location=London|work=The Guardian|first=Catherine|last=Shoard|date=27 May 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[World Soundtrack Academy]]\n| [[World Soundtrack Award for Soundtrack Composer of the Year|Soundtrack Composer of the Year]]\n| [[Howard Shore]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"10\"| 2013\n| rowspan=\"3\"| [[Canadian Screen Awards]]\n| [[1st Canadian Screen Awards#Adapted Screenplay|Adapted Screenplay]]\n| David Cronenberg\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[1st Canadian Screen Awards|Achievement in Music: Original Score]]\n| Howard Shore\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[1st Canadian Screen Awards|Achievement in Music: Original Song]]\n| [[Emily Haines]], [[James Shaw (musician)|James Shaw]] and Howard Shore, \"Long to Live\"\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Online Film Critics Society]]\n| [[Online Film Critics Society Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]]\n| David Cronenberg\n| {{nom}}<ref>{{cite web|title=2012 Awards (16th Annual)|url=http://www.ofcs.org/awards/2012-awards-16th-annual/|accessdate=22 May 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\"| [[Vancouver Film Critics Circle]]\n| [[Vancouver Film Critics Circle Award for Best Canadian Film|Best Film \u2013 Canadian]]\n| \n| {{nom}}<ref name=\"a\">{{cite web|title=2013 VFCC Nominees Announced!|url=http://vancouverfilmcritics.com/2012/12/27/2013-vfcc-nominees-announced/|accessdate=22 May 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Director \u2013 Canadian Film\n| David Cronenberg\n| {{nom}}<ref name=\"a\" />\n|-\n| [[Vancouver Film Critics Circle Award for Best Actor in a Canadia